<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Italy-USOExplosion 5thLd-Writethru   04-14 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-USO Explosion, 5th Ld - Writethru,a0902,0812</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosion at USO Club Kills Navy Servicewoman, Four Italians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to INCLUDE fourth injured American,
CORRECT spelling of Capodanno; picks up 7th graf pvs, ``Italian
media ...; SUBS grafs 18-19, ``Navalta is ... with 22 grafs to
identify American.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb blew up in front of a club for
U.S. military personnel in Naples on Thursday, killing a U.S. Navy
enlisted woman and four Italians and wounding at least 17,
officials said.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the blast
that happened shortly after 8 p.m. (2 p.m. EDT) at the USO club.
   A Pentagon spokeswoman said the American woman was stationed at
Naval Communications Area Master Station in Naples. Lt. Janet
Mescus, the spokeswoman, said the woman's identity was being
withheld pending notification of next of kin.
   Italian media quoted officials as saying four Italians were also
killed. One of the bodies at the club's entrance was draped in a
U.S. flag.
   Lt. David Morris, a Navy spokesman in Naples, said an
undetermined number of crewmen from the frigates USS Capodanno and
USS Paul were injured but that no sailor from either ship was
killed.
   Morris said three sailors from the Capodanno and one from the
Paul were admitted to the U.S. Naval Hospital in Naples. He said
one crewman from the Capodanno was treated and returned to his ship.
   Italian media said the bomb exploded during a reception at the
club for the commander of the USS Paul, a torpedo boat destroyer
docked in Naples. Morris and a U.S. Consulate official could not
confirm the report.
   Passers-by screamed and ran when the explosion occurred outside
the club, which is in one of Naples' busiest areas.
   ``I was in the store and we were getting ready to lower the
shutters when the world exploded around us,'' said Valeria
Spinetti, 22, an employee in a nearby shop.
   A spokesmen for Pellegrini Hospital said 14 of the wounded,
including four Americans and eight Italians, were sent to the
hospital. The spokesman, who asked not to be identified, said the
Americans were moved to a U.S. military hospital.
   RAI, the state-run television network, said a 27-year-old
Italian woman was in grave condition.
   Morris said the Capodanno, based in Newport, R.I., and the Paul,
based in Mayport, Fla., were on routine deployment with 6th Fleet.
   Antonio Barrel, the inspector general of public security in
Naples, told the Italian news agency ANSA that authorities do not
yet know if the car bomb was set by foreigners or Italians.
   But ANSA quoted an unidentified police official as saying ``the
Middle East connection seems most likely.''
   Italian news media noted the blast occurred almost exactly two
years after U.S. warplanes bombed Tripoli and Benghazi in
retaliation for alleged Libyan involvement in the bombing of a
night club in West Berlin that killed an American soldier.
   Investigators said the Thursday blast destroyed the inside of
the club and wrecked cars on the street. The bomb apparently was
hidden in a Ford Fiesta that was destroyed by the blast.
   Mescus identified three of the injured Navy servicemen as Chief
Petty Officer Francisco A. Navalta, 39, of the USS Paul, and Petty
Officer 3rd Class Craig Lee Trent, 22, and Senior Chief Petty
Officer Charles Fifer Roberts, 38, both assiged to the USS
Capodanno.
   Morris identified a fourth injured sailor as Stanley Lawson, 27,
an electronics technician on the Capodanno. He was in stable
condition.
   Navalta, from Castillejos, Zambales, Philippines, and Trent,
from Gaither, Md., were also in stable condition.
   Roberts, from East St. Louis, Ill, was treated and released.
   ``Our sympathy goes out to the families and friends of those who
were killed or injured in this brutal act,'' said World USO
President Chuck Hagel from Washington.
   The bombing was the fourth attack in seven years aginst American
installations or personnel in Italy.
   In December 1981, Red Brigade terrorists disguised as plumbers
kidnapped U.S. Brig. Gen. James Dozier from his home in Verona. He
was freed 42 days later by a special police unit in Padua.
   In February 1984, terrorists in Rome fatally shot Leamon Hunt, a
U.S. diplomat and director-general of the Multinational Force and
Observers in the Sinai. The Red Brigades claimed responsibility.
   In June 1987, a car bomb exploded near the U.S. Embassy in Rome
and at least two rockets were fired at the embassy. There were no
injuries.
   The Navy has a major presence in Naples, headquarters for NATO's
southern command and the support center for the 6th Fleet. An
average of 45 ships, 200 aircraft and over 23,000 people comprise
the fleet, which is deployed in the Mediterranean.
</TEXT>
