<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0818EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Nut&HoneyProtest     04-14 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Nut & Honey Protest,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Won't Change Ads, Kellogg Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kellogg Co. has refused to change or
cancel one of its TV commercials for Nut & Honey Crunch cereal,
despite claims by an activist group that the ad promotes violence
against homosexuals.
   In the commercials, cereal eaters play off the Nut & Honey name
by answering the question of what they are eating with the reply,
``Nothing, honey.''
   The Chicago-based Coalition Against Media-Marketing Prejudice
called ``offensive'' one version that shows a western chuck wagon
cook being threatened by gun-toting cowboys who believe he has
called them ``honey.''
   The commercials ``send a serious and dangerous message _ that
gays and lesbians or anyone perceived as sexually or behaviorally
different are easy and acceptable targets for trivialization,'' the
group said Wednesday outside Kellogg headquarters.
   Kellogg, however, said it would be overreacting to change the
commercial or pull it off the air.The company refused to accept
evidence from experts on psychology, advertising and violence who
backed the group's claim, said spokesman Arthur Johnston.
</TEXT>
