<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RiceStatue     04-14 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rice Statue,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pranksters Make Statue Do About-Face</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The one ton bronze statue of Rice University
founder William Marsh Rice has been festooned with such things as
hats, coats and military regalia since it was placed on campus 58
years ago.
   But on Tuesday, it was facing south instead of north.
   Just before dawn, a campus police officer spotted about 20
people around the statue and noticed a spotlight that usually
illuminates it was dark. As he approached, the group scattered,
said Campus Police Chief Mary Voswinkel.
   Ms. Voswinkel said the officer was able to stop one student, who
was driving a pickup truck away from the quadrangle. The officer
took the student's name and let him go, then sped back to the
statue to investigate.
   The statue appeared intact _ but was facing the Fondren Library
to the south instead of the Lovett Building to the north.
   It took 3{ hours for a crew of professional movers using a crane
to fix the statue.
   ``It was a student prank,'' said Bill Noblitt, Rice's director
of university relations. ``It was a rite-of-spring type thing.''
   Noblitt said the vandalism could have had serious consequences
because students apparently used an A-frame built from 4-by-6 beams
to lift the statue. The devices that were found had cracked, and
the statue could have fallen.
   The pranksters apparently climbed to the roof of the
Architecture Building to disconnect the spotlight and had painted
the A-frame black to help conceal it.
   The student who was questioned will face disciplinary action
from the university, but officials did not release further details.
</TEXT>
