<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APArts:Olmos     04-14 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Olmos,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Miami Vice' Star Goes Home to Make Movie</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The working class neighborhood
that taught Edward James Olmos respect for humanity and watched the
``Miami Vice'' star mature into an acclaimed actor is home to his
latest movie.
   Olmos returned to an East Los Angeles high school last spring to
make ``Stand and Deliver,'' a movie about a magnetic, demanding
math teacher who led an unruly Hispanic class to academic triumph
in 1982.
   The 41-year-old actor was no stranger to the halls of Garfield
High School. His cousin teaches computer science there. Only 1{
miles from his childhood home, it is ethnically mixed, like the
neighborhood he remembers.
   ``Stand and Deliver'' was a smash when it opened in Los Angeles.
It brought in $411,000 during its first week last month, averaging
$14,000 at each of 30 theaters, he said.
   Olmos, an actor of Mexican-American heritage who won an Emmy
Award for his role as Lt. Castillo on the NBC-TV series ``Miami
Vice,'' was delighted with the movie and its reception in his home
area.
   ``This film is probably the most inspirational film I've done to
date,'' he said of the Warner Bros. release.
   ``Stand and Deliver'' is about overcoming racial stigmas. It
advances the humanities, something Olmos said he holds close to his
heart; something he learned in a family of eight living in a
neighborhood crowded with Russian, Mexican, Jewish and American
Indian families.
   Olmos, who co-produced and helped write the movie, claims he is
not making a political point.
   ``I'm not a political animal,'' he said. It's the advancement of
the humanities through acting that inspires Olmos.
   ``It's always been that way. It serves me well and makes me
stronger,'' he said.
   ``That doesn't mean I have to make message movies. I think that
art forms, especially films, should be used to entertain. Now if by
chance your entertaining and allowing (your audience) to experience
an event that has some value and some substance and some awareness
to it, well even better.
   ``The criterion, No. 1, is the story. If that story happens to
be socially relevant, well that's wonderful, but if it isn't,
that's OK too.''
   ``Stand and Deliver'' is about an event that drew national
attention to Garfield High School's 1982 calculus class. The
predominantly Hispanic class took and passed an Advance Placement
calculus test, in stark contrast to the rest of the school, which
faced loss of accreditation.
   The 18 students, who were badgered and inspired by computer
specialist-turned-teacher Jaime Escalante, were stripped of their
honors when the Educational Testing Service, which tests U.S.
students and provides their scores to colleges and universities,
accused the entire class of cheating.
   In the movie, Olmos, in his role as Escalante, accuses the
Educational Testing Service of racism. Students from wealthy
Beverly Hills would not be questioned if they passed an Advance
Placement calculus test, but students with Hispanic names from a
barrio high school were suspect, he says in the movie.
   Eventually, the students are vindicated with a second test.
   The movie is not meant to be manipulative, Olmos said. It
presents an event ``that allows you to experience with your own
values.''
   ``We don't give results,'' he said. ``We only give the facts.''
</TEXT>
