<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0037EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Scotch&Water     04-14 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotch & Water,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whisky-Maker Says San Francisco Water Not Good Enough</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought-threatened San Francisco Bay
region is getting a little help from an unlikely quarter _ the
makers of Famous Grouse Scotch whisky.
   The manufacturers of the liquor, Matthew Gloag & Sons of Perth,
Scotland, kicked off their latest U.S. sales campaign, but decided
they couldn't bear the thought that San Franciscans might mix their
prized whisky with local tap water.
   ``The fact is that San Francisco tap water does not taste very
good,'' said local Famous Grouse spokesman Ed Schwartz.
   So this month, it started selling a $14 package containing the
scotch and a bottle of water from Great Britain's Strathmore
Valley, a combination the company says is necessary to bring out
the best features of the liquor.
   ``Serious scotch drinkers in San Francisco have been loath to
mix Famous Grouse with the infamous chlorinated city water,'' read
several hundred invitations to a scotch and bagpipe bash Wednesday
at a chic watering hole.
   Famous Grouse, stung by the mere 1.5 gallon-per-capita
consumption of distilled spirits in this country, is trying to
heighten the figure with a U.S. campaign initially targeting San
Francisco and Washington, D.C.
   In the Bay region, a fringe benefit will be to ease ever so
slightly the water shortage threatened by an exceptionally dry
winter.

</TEXT>
