<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Niger-Condoms,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Authorizes Use of Contraception</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAMEY, Niger (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government authorized the use of
contraceptives to help control population growth and the spread of
disease.
   The move was regarded as significant in a predominantly Moslem
country of 7 million people, where the use of contraceptives has
been illegal without a doctor's prescription since independence
from France in 1960.
   The government said on Wednesday the use of condoms, diaphragms
and spercmicides would no longer require a doctor's prescription.
The communique did not say if the government also would begin
distributing contraceptives.
   Niger, located in the arid West African Sahel, suffers from
recurring serious food shortages related to drought and poor farm
land.
   Its population is growing at an annual rate of 2.9 percent. The
government has predicted the population will grow to 10 million by
the year 2000.
</TEXT>
