<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hepburn,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actress Audrey Hepburn Campaigns Against World Hunger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Audrey Hepburn, who visited
drought-stricken Ethiopia recently, joined UNICEF officials in
calling for help in the battle against world hunger.
   ``To save a single child is a blessing... to save millions of
children is a God-given opportunity presented to us by UNICEF,''
the 58-year-old actress said Wednesday at a news conference.
   Lawrence Bruce, the international children's fund president and
chief executive, announced UNICEF's latest drive to raise $22
million for medicine, vaccines and other non-food relief.
   ``We have the means of cutting by half the present global death
rate of 38,000 children each day ... and I find it unconscionable
that these children should die of preventable causes,'' Bruce said.
   Hepburn's eyes glistened with tears as she described the poor,
starving children she saw in Ethiopia while accompanying Bruce for
five days in mid-March.
   She noted that as an adolescent in Holland after World War II,
she was the recipient of food from a United Nations relief agency.
   ``Without that nutrition, my health might well have been
impaired for life,'' she said.
</TEXT>
