<DOCNO> AP880414-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabyDonors     04-14 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Donors,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Effort To Get Organs From Doomed Babies Continues Under New Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital will continue to harvest
organs for transplant from babies born with most of their brains
missing, despite a prior announcement that the program had been
suspended, officials said.
   Dick Schaefer, a spokesman for Loma Linda University Medical
Center, said Wednesday he was mistaken when he announced earlier in
the week that the hospital's program of keeping such babies alive
had been temporarily halted until new guidelines could be issued.
   On Tuesday night, hospital spokeswoman Anita Rockwell issued a
statement saying the program to admit anencephalic babies ``is to
continue without interruption.''
   The hospital's policy was slightly revised, however, so that
such babies will be placed on respirators only if their heart rates
slow or they have trouble breathing, Schaefer said from the
hospital 60 miles east of Los Angeles.
   Anencephalic babies _ those missing most of their brains _
inevitably die within days to weeks. Loma Linda's experimental and
so-far unsuccesful program is aimed at using such infants as organ
donors to save the lives of babies who otherwise would die of fatal
heart defects or other deadly ailments.
   Previously, the hospital's policy was to place the anencephalic
babies on respirators as soon as they were admitted to the hospital
so their organs wouldn't deteriorate as they died.
   A seven-day limit for keeping them on the respirators was
established to counter criticisms that the doomed anencephalic
babies were suffering only to benefit infants who need transplants.
   The revised life-support policy, which still maintains the
seven-day limit, apparently is aimed at increasing the proportion
of babies who can be declared brain-dead.
   Schaefer said Wednesday his earlier statement ``was a
misunderstanding on my part. I assumed that the program wouldn't be
started until the statement (of revised policy) was released.''
   Only one of the first six anencephalic babies admitted to Loma
Linda, Hope Lovette Mount, of Knoxville, Tenn., remained alive
Wednesday. She was taken off life-support Monday and will be
allowed to die, Schaefer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
