<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     04-14 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0854</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Atlanta-based organization for terminally ill
children has given out 100 tickets to pop star Michael Jackson's
concert here tonight, but needs a few more tickets to meet the
number they were asked to get.
   ``Once the word came out that we had tickets, the phone was
ringing off the hook,'' Linda Dozoretz of the Children's Wish
Foundation said Wednesday.
   Ms. Dozoretz said the organization needs 24 more tickets to
fulfill every request it got. ``We're trying to see what we can
do,'' she said. ``It would be a wonderful experience.''
   The group, which grants wishes to terminally ill children, was
awaiting confirmation from Jackson's staff on whether he will be
able to meet some of the children, Ms. Dozoretz said.
   Jackson brought his solo tour to Atlanta on Wednesday for three
sold-out shows.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban leader Fidel Castro has been honored by
the World Health Organization for giving up his famous cigar and
setting a smoke-free example for his countrymen, Cuba's official
news agency says.
   Castro was given two medals by Carlyle Guerra de Macedo,
director general of the Geneva-based organization, in a ceremony
Tuesday at Havana's Palace of the Revolution, said Prensa Latina in
a dispatch received here Wednesday.
   The WHO announced the honor on April 7, the first worldwide ``No
Tobacco Day.'' Castro, whose cigars were almost as much a trademark
as his beard, was cited for pledging in 1981 never to smoke in
public and subsequently quitting.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Counterculture journalist Hunter S.
Thompson canceled tonight's scheduled speaking engagement at the
University of Arizona because of alleged death threats, his agent
says.
   Thompson, 48, who lives near Aspen, Colo., has received numerous
telephone threats in the past week, agent Greg Werckman said
Wednesday in New York City.
   Thompson, creator of so-called ``gonzo'' journalism, has written
several books, including ``Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas'' and
``The Great White Shark Hunt.''
   Thompson has developed a reputation for rowdy behavior and
drinking on the speaking tour, and his appearance initially had
been opposed by student leaders.
   Werckman said Thompson was disappointed at having to cancel, but
has taken the threats seriously. Werckman said he did not know the
source of the threats, but that the writer previously had been
threatened by someone in Tucson.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Deborah Harry, songwriter Irving Berlin,
jazz musician Lionel Hampton, and transsexual tennis coach Renee
Richards are among dozens of celebrities who owe back taxes to New
York state, a newspaper says.
   Miss Harry owes $241,354 for record royalties and Berlin owes
$5,500, according to state records cited by the New York Post on
Wednesday.
   Richards, an ophthalmologist, owes nearly $33,000 and master
vibraphonist Hampton's Lionel Hampton Enterprises owes $10,500 in
withholding taxes, the paper said.
   The records also showed the state was seeking almost $289,000
from the estate of jazz great Duke Ellington and more than $91,000
from the estate of singer Brook Benton, who died Saturday.
   On Monday, movie reviewer Rex Reed pleaded guilty to evading
more than $20,000 in state income taxes.
   A secretary for Berlin denied that the 99-year-old songwriter
owed taxes. Hampton's manager, Bill Titone, said the tax problem
was cleared up in 1987. A secretary for Richards said the issue was
being handled by Richards' lawyer, according to the Post.
   Miss Harry's lawyer, Gary Kurfirst, said the singer was repaying
her debt in installments and would owe no money by the end of the
year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   P.D. James, one of Britain's top detective fiction
writers, has been named to the government-funded Arts Council to
lead a campaign to stimulate interest in literature, particularly
in schools.
   ``We have a wonderful, almost miraculous literary heritage,''
Ms. James said Wednesday. ``Now we need to stimulate our writers
and poets in the future.''
   Ms. James, whose books include ``Cover Her Face'' and ``Death Of
An Expert Witness,'' will preside over the council's literature
panel.
   The council, one of Britain's main sources of public support of
the arts, also is commissioning English translations of foreign
works, a television series about poetry, and subsidizing black
British authors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former network executive Fred Silverman says
he figures that since he's become an independent producer he's
committed about 100 murders.
   Silverman is the executive producer of NBC's ``Matlock'' and
``In the Heat of the Night'' and CBS' ``Jake and the Fatman.'' He
also produces the ``Perry Mason'' series and is planning two more
series, including a revival of ``Burke's Law'' with Gene Barry.
   ``But no more mysteries for me,'' said Silverman, formerly head
of programming at CBS, former president of ABC Entertainment and
former president of NBC.
   ``I feel like I've earned a law degree with all these lawyers,''
he said Wednesday. ``I think Dean Hargrove, my co-executive
producer, and I have committed about 100 murders so far.''
</TEXT>
