<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PenaRecall 1stLd-Writethru a0818 04-14 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pena Recall, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0818,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mayoral Recall Group Delivers Insufficient Petitions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with petitions falling short of
required numbers. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Mofford-Mecham, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A months-long recall effort to oust Mayor Federico
Pena failed Wednesday when an elections official announced that
petitions submitted fell more than 2,000 names short of the number
required by law.
   The backers of the drive delivered 21 bundles of petitions to
the Denver Election Commission Wednesday afternoon, beating a 5
p.m. deadline by several hours.
   They said they believed there were enough valid signatures to
support calling a new mayoral election.
   But late Wednesday, Felicia Muftic, president of the Denver
Election Commission, said that even without checking for validity,
the number of signatures was only 36,960.
   For a recall, the petitions would have to bear the valid
signatures of 39,091 registered Denver voters, which is 25 percent
of the number of votes cast in the last mayoral election, said Sam
Tarkington, executive director of the Election Commission.
   ``It appears that unofficially there's just not enough
signatures to continue,'' Muftic said.
   Pena, 41, one of the first Hispanics to be mayor of a major U.S.
city, reacted immediately with pleasure.
   ``The time for negativism and doubt is behind us. To those
people who opposed the recall I thank you. To those who supported
the recall I urge you to join with the city to help move the city
forward. These are critical times facing our city and we can't
afford to have disunity,'' he said at a news conference at his
office late Wednesday.
   Recall organizer Marge Doty said earlier Wednesday that she had
no exact count on the number of signatures, but said she was
confident there were ``more than enough'' to continue the recall
process.
   Doty, who launched the recall effort in January, requested a
police escort to and from the Election Commission office after she
reported receiving threats.
   The recall drive was started by a group angry over what its
members claimed was fiscal mismanagement by the Pena
administration. The group gathered support among residents stranded
for several days by a major holiday snowstorm when maintenance
crews plowed only major traffic arteries while Pena was vacationing
out of state.
   While there is some dispute about precise procedures, Denver's
charter calls for an entirely new, nonpartisan election if the
petitions are validated to recall Pena, a second-term Democrat.
   Any candidate who collected 300 names on a nominating petition
could run, and if no candidate mustered a clear majority, a run-off
would be held next.
   There have been hints of illegalities in the petition campaign.
Pena appeared on a KOA radio call-in show Wednesday morning, and
one caller informed him her daughter had been approached by
petitioners. The daughter said she was told she ``had to sign,''
and when she said she was not a Denver resident, she was allegedly
told, ``We'll give you a Denver address.''
</TEXT>
