<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CitySmelters Bjt   04-14 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-City Smelters, Bjt,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Annual Spawning Brings Smelt And Fish Stories To Chicago Lakefront</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On spring nights, pearls of light from lanterns
and campfires sparkle along Chicago's dark seawalls and breakwaters
as thousands of people wait for tiny silvery fish to wander into
their nets.
   The smelt are spawning again, a decades-old rite of spring that
is part social event, part business and part recreation along the
Great Lakes during the six-week season from April 1 to May 15.
   Smelting is almost a way of life.
   ``I've been doing it for 30 years, and I've run through friends,
family, my kids _ nobody loves it quite as much as I do,'' said
Herman Telkamp, who staked out his spot four hours before he could
legally lower his net at 7 p.m.
   ``My wife won't clean fish anymore, so I spend all night
smelting and all day cleaning.''
   Rainbow smelt, 6- to 8-inch members of a family resembling the
trout, have been eaten in Europe and Canada for centuries.
   In the Midwest, the rite began after 1912, when the smelt,
orginally a salt-water fish, escaped into the Great Lakes from a
small lake in Michigan where they had been stocked.
   The best smelting at Montrose Harbor was on the breakwater,
which was lined with Vietnamese, Cambodian and Korean families, and
a few Polish immigrants.
   Fathers lower and raise the nets, children pull the fish from
the mesh and mothers gut and clean.
   ``A lot of those fish are going to Argyle Street,'' said one
onlooker, referring to a nearby neighborhood with Vietnamese and
Cambodian restaurants.
   With the right water temperature, current and wind, the smelt
head in from open waters in great numbers. Chicago smelters run
their square gill nets out on anchored ropes, raising the nets
several times an hour.
   Nightly yields can reach 5,000 fish a person, but on nights when
the fish are fewer, it's time for six-packs and smelt stories. Like
the one Rob Ohagan, 24, of Darien, tells about the tipsy smelter
who weighted his net with his keys.
   ``A lot of guys fish without licenses and just abandon their
nets when the wardens come by,'' Ohagan said. ``They figure it's
cheaper to lose a $35 smelt rig than to pay a $50 fine.
   ``This guy remembered that his keys were on the net, and he
couldn't get into his car, so he had to take the fine,'' Ohagan
said.
   There's also the matter of upholding a tradition observed by
younger smelters: biting the head off the first smelt of the season.
   Ed Flowers, 25, of La Grange, pulled up his first net of the
spring and saluted the four dangling fish with a beer, but he
wouldn't take the bite.
   ``Now you won't have any more luck,'' said Jim Falduto, 25, of
Park Ridge.
   Chuck Roth and his wife, Laurie, had set up a net, a fire and a
tent for their two young daughters, Nicole and Chris.
   ``We've been smelting about five years _ always at this very
same spot,'' Roth said. ``We only ran out of last year's frozen
smelt last month.''
   The Roths, of Park Forest, like their smelt marinated in
home-made hot sauce, but Larry Wolfgang, also casting his net along
the breakwater, cooks his in a beer batter.
   ``I keep a couple of gallons for myself and give the rest away _
to friends or in the tavern,'' Wolfgang said. ``They're a lot
easier to give away than zucchini or tomatoes.''
   Wolfgang, 45, said this night he was catching a wedding present.
   ``My sister's getting married tomorrow in Eau Claire,
Wisconsin,'' he said. ``She likes smelt, but they're hard to come
by that far from the lakes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
