<DOCNO> AP880414-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz-Afghanistan Bjt   04-14 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Afghanistan, Bjt,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Confident Soviets Will Honor Afghan Agreement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top expected after Shultz arrival in Geneva, approximately 7
a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz says he is
confident the Soviets will keep their promise to withdraw from
Afghanistan under an agreement hailed as the first step toward
ending the bitter Afghan struggle.
   Shultz flew to Geneva today to join Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze at the ceremonial signing of a series of
settlement accords. Among them is a Soviet pledge to withdraw an
estimated 115,000 Red Army troops from Afghanistan.
   Shultz and Shevardnadze also plan to issue statements
reaffirming their nations' right to continue aiding the Afghan
factions _ assuring that the war will go on as a civil conflict.
   There was fresh evidence of continued warfare on the eve of the
signing.
   U.S. government sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed reports from Western diplomats in Pakistan earlier in the
week that Soviet forces near Kabul were sent to relieve Gardez, a
beleaguered Afghan Army garrison south of the capital, amid fierce
fighting with U.S.-backed guerrillas.
   The units were said to consist of an undetermined number of
soldiers and 420 vehicles, including T-72 tanks, armored personnel
carriers and mobile rocket launchers.
   Gardez is 80 miles south of Kabul and 60 miles from Pakistan,
staging area for U.S. aid to the resistance.
   Mujahedeen guerrillas recently cut the road to Gardez, where a
Soviet special forces regiment is garrisoned, said one source.
   Another source said convoys of trucks also were sent into
Afghanistan from the Soviet Union in the past week, but it was not
clear if the trucks were filled with troops or were empty.
   Before leaving for Geneva, Shultz told members of House and
Senate foreign affairs committees that he had faith in the Soviet
promise, committee members said.
   Rep. Charles Wilson, D-Texas, one of Capitol Hill's ardent
champions of U.S. support for anti-Soviet guerrillas in
Afghanistan, said after meeting Shultz he accepted the assurances.
   ``The bottom line is that the Soviets are getting out,'' Wilson
said.
   Under the withdrawal agreement, the Soviets are supposed to pull
out 50 percent of their troops within 90 days, and the entire
contingent by Feb. 15, 1989.
   That would mark the end of a Soviet troop presence in
Afghanistan that began with a December 1979 airlift of Red Army
forces into Kabul to back pro-Moscow Afghan leaders in their war
against insurgents. U.S. analysts believe the Red Army will pull
back from exposed positions and concentrate in Kabul and around the
northern city of Mazar-i-Sharif.
   The United States had hoped to reach agreement with the Soviets
to cut aid to both sides _ the U.S. backed guerrillas and the
Soviet-sponsored Afghan government _ but Moscow rebuffed an aid
cutoff and now both sides will continue arming their clients.
   Shultz said he hoped United Nations mediator Diego Cordovez, who
arranged the Soviet pullout, will be successful in arranging a
peace accord between the Afghans.
   Pakistan and the Afghan government have agreed under the accords
to stop interfering in each others' affairs and the superpowers are
signing the pact as ``guarantors.''
   Despite the likelihood of continued fighting, the prospect of a
Soviet withdrawal has been hailed by U.S. officials as a potential
milestone in superpower relations.
   Since 1979, the Carter and Reagan administrations have told the
Soviets that their continued presence in Afghanistan has made it
difficult for the United States to trust Soviet professions of
peaceful intent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
