<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-RealEstate Bjt-1stAdd   04-14 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Real Estate, Bjt - 1st Add,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: $22 million.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   At the immigration service, Assistant Commissioner Kennedy said
it was his job to recommend to Commissioner Alan C. Nelson whether
to stay in the Chester Arthur Building or move.
   If Nelson, a close friend of Meese's from the days when they
worked together in California, had demanded a move, the GSA would
have found a new building, according to Kennedy and GSA officials.
   But Kennedy recommended staying even though he was displeased
with the building management, particularly its maintenance of the
air system.
   ``At one point, a downtown, new building came on the market and
people thought about that for a while,'' Kennedy said. ``But when
you look at the logistics of uprooting your entire headquarters
staff for a month, it's not worth it.''
   Kennedy said other events tied his hands: The first immigration
reform bill in a generation was enacted Oct. 17, 1986.
   ``We couldn't even consider a move at that time, because of the
demands of the new act,'' Kennedy said. ``We had to get thousands
of new employees on board.''
   Kennedy said when he discussed the lease with Nelson ``there
were no options. When you look at the cost of moving and all that,
it's kind of the decision that doesn't have to be made.''
   But during this period, the immigration service outgrew Chester
Arthur; some employees were put in two other buildings, five and 10
blocks away.
   Kennedy says no one pressured him, and that he never heard
whether Meese had an opinion on the lease or about Ursula Meese's
salary being paid indirectly by the building owners.
   Sources familiar with McKay's investigation have said he is
interested in the role played by Meese's confidant and former
attorney, E. Robert Wallach, in obtaining the Benders' job offers
to Ursula Meese. Wallach has been indicted for allegedly trying to
peddle his influence with Meese in other matters.
   George Walker, Wallach's attorney, told The Washington Post that
Wallach played a peripheral role in Ursula Meese's taking the MS
job instead of the radio program. Walker did not return numerous
telephone calls over a week.
   Meanwhile, the man who sold Chester Arthur to the Bender
partnership still wonders why they bought it and gave him such a
good deal.
   ``We are still laughing because we did a very good deal there,''
said Dirk van Westreenen, president of Dutch Property Investment,
Ltd. The sale price more than tripled his $12 million investment
five years earlier.
   He decided to sell because ``the GSA gave us notice that they
wanted to get rid of a floor and a half. That was the risk: Are
they going to stay? Who is going to take this space, because it is
not first-class space and it is not a first-class location?''
   Of Howard Bender, Van Westreenen said, ``I don't know how much
of a gamble it was, but he took the gamble that we didn't want to
take.''
