<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CommunistPresident     04-14 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Communist President,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Judicial Board Disallows Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student judicial board at the University
of Massachusetts Wednesday declared invalid an election in which an
avowed communist and another student were chosen as co-presidents
of the student body.
   The board said the constitution of the Student Government
Association prohibited more than one person from holding the
presidency.
   ``Only one person can run for and hold the office of SGA
president,'' the three-member student court said in an opinion
issued late Wednesday night.
   The student court, whose decisions are binding on the student
government, ordered a new election. A date was not immediately set.
   Student attorney general William Collins asked the court to
declare the Jason Rabinowitz-Shari Silkoff ticket invalid because
of the joint candidacy.
   Rabinowitz, a 20-year-old member of the Young Communist League,
is believed to be the first such member elected campus president
since the group was formed five years ago. He and Silkoff, also 20
and a self-described progressive, were elected March 15 with 1,454
votes, 391 more than conservative candidate Aram Hamparian at the
19,000-student campus.
   ``This was a travesty of justice,'' Rabinowitz said after the
decision was announced. ``We're going to beat this. We want to
fight for the rights of the students.''
   A professor who testified at the hearing last week on behalf of
Rabinowitz and Silkoff said the constitution's language about the
presidency was vague.
   ``It could be read in different ways,'' said political science
professor Dean Alfange said.
   On whether it prohibited co-presidents, he said: ``That language
does not necessarily mean that to me, as a layman reading this
document.''
   Conservatives in the student senate had filibustered last week
to keep the election from being ratified and to stop Rabinowitz and
Silkoff from taking office.
</TEXT>
