<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WorldOutlook     04-14 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World Outlook,400</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 9:30 a.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Economic Prospects Improving in US But not in Poor Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic prospects have improved slightly over
the past six months in the United States and other industrial
countries, but have dropped sharply in poor countries, according to
estimates made public today by the International Monetary Fund.
   In the United States the fund predicts that production will
increase this year by the same 2.9 percent as it did in 1986 and
1987, with a slower increase of 2.7 percent in 1989. It predicts
declining unemployment from 6.2 percent last year to 6 percent this
year and 5.9 next year.
   Inflation in the industrialized countries is pegged at 3 percent
in 1988. But in the Third World, the report says, prices paid by
consumers will go up by 46.7 percent.
   Total growth in the Third World is put at 3.7 percent.
   The report does not include population figures, but since Third
World birth rates are high, the rise in income for each individual
may be only about half as much. For industrial countries, the new
growth figure is 3 percent.
   ``An important positive development in 1987 was the
strengthening of policy coordination among the major industrial
countries,'' says the fund's new ``World Economic Outlook.''
   ``The U.S. federal budget deficit fell substantially, as did
deficits in other large countries with troublesome fiscal
positions.''
   In the IMF's parlance, a country gets into a ``troublesome
fiscal position'' when its government fails to collect enough taxes
to cover its expenses.
   The fund says the three most economically important Latin
American countries _ Brazil, Mexico and Argentina _ have had
serious setbacks in curbing inflation and there are signs of rising
prices elsewhere. Fund officials doubt if their governments can do
anything effective to stabilize their economies.
   Sluggish growth in the Third World is blamed in part on a
slowdown in India due to drought, and to lower pay and less
investment in Brazil because of rising inflation.
   Growth in China, South Korea and Taiwan, on the other hand, was
called ``particularly buoyant.''
   The predictions are made on the assumption that government
policies and currency exchange rates will not change.
   For the major industrial countries taken as a group the
predictions include these for the years 1990 to 1992: a 2.8 percent
increase in production and a slight increase in the jobless rate to
6.9 percent.
</TEXT>
