<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TaxTime     04-14 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Time,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Minute Filers Can Save Time With Short Form</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you are among millions of taxpayers waiting
until the last minute to file federal returns, you might save time
and expedite any refund by avoiding the long Form 1040.
   The General Accounting Office, an arm of Congress, found during
a check of one of the 10 IRS processing centers that 14.1 percent
of filers had used 1040 when they could have filed the simpler
1040A or the one-page 1040EZ.
   Many of those probably were taxpayers who in the past itemized
deductions and thus had to file the long form, and stuck with it
this year even though repeal or reduction of several deductions
made it no longer profitable to itemize.
   The shorter forms are less complicated to fill out and present
fewer opportunities for errors. The IRS requires less time to
process them.
   But the shorter forms are not for everyone. If your itemized
deductions total more than your standard deduction, you'll save
money by itemizing, which requires the long form. And you must file
the long form if taxable income is $50,000 or more.
   Midnight Friday is the deadline for most individuals to file
their returns _ the first that reflect the far-reaching tax-law
revision enacted in 1986. So far, despite confusion about the law
and new forms, taxpayers and the IRS seem to be holding their own.
   ``This has been a very good filing season to date,'' Gibbs said.
``But it has been challenging ... because of the number of changes
made in the 1986 act.''
   Through April 8, the IRS had received 64.5 million returns,
compared with 65.7 million before the last week of the 1987 filing
season. The agency has processed 52.7 million this year, down
slightly from 52.8 million at this time last year.
   Refunds have been certified for 78 percent _ 41 million _ of the
returns that have been processed, compared with 79 percent at this
time last year. Refunds are averaging $830, up from $815.
   New restrictions on itemized deductions and higher standard
deductions have significantly reduced the number of couples and
individuals who are itemizing, Gibbs said.
   The one dark spot on this tax season, IRS and GAO agree, is that
taxpayers still find it difficult to get the correct answer when
they telephone tax questions to the IRS. GAO said IRS provided the
right answer to only 62 percent of the 1,523 test calls made by
GAO. A broader IRS survey, 15,000 calls, produced the correct
response to 72.1 percent of the questions.
   In each survey, the accuracy rate was up slightly from a
February check.
   ``You get better odds in Las Vegas,'' grumbled Rep. J.J. Pickle,
chairman of the House Ways and Means oversight subcommittee.
   ``We must and will improve our accuracy rate for our
customers,'' Gibbs promised. He mentioned plans to make telephone
``assistors'' full-time, rather than seasonal, employees; to raise
their pay and to give each immediate access to computerized
information necessary to answer questions.
   Despite all the confusion about new laws and complicated forms,
the subcommittee was told, taxpayers are having fewer problems than
anticipated:
   _The IRS has received 15.7 million telephone calls for
information this year, up 12.6 percent from last year but 7.8
percent fewer than expected.
   _Errors are showing up on 20.7 percent of returns, about 1.4
percentage points above last year. ``The amount of the increase has
been less than expected,'' said GAO Deputy Director Johnny F. Finch.
   _About 42 percent of the returns filed so far have been prepared
by professionals, up from 40 percent last year but less than in
1986. Some experts had predicted most taxpayers would have to turn
to professionals because of the new law.
   Finch said 48 percent of 892 taxpayers surveyed in four states
and the District of Columbia had more trouble filling out this
year's returns than last year's. Another 30 percent found little
difference, and 12 percent said this year's were easier. Ten
percent were not sure.
</TEXT>
