<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BankingDeregulation     04-14 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banking Deregulation,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nader Asks Congress to Keep Banks Out Of Securities Deals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader wants Congress
to reject efforts to restructure the nation's financial system to
allow banks and securities firms broad latitude to affiliate for
the first time since 1933.
   Nader, representing the Center for Study of Responsive Law, told
the House telecommunications and finance subcommittee Wednesday
that Congress should not repeal the provisions of the 1933
Glass-Steagall Act which prohibit banks and bank holding companies
from underwriting and dealing in corporate securities.
   Specifically, Nader said banking organizations should continue
to be barred from dealing in the following securities activities:
   _Underwriting or dealing in corporate debt or equity securities.
   _Sponsorship or investment management of mutual funds comprised
of corporate debt or equity securities.
   _Underwriting securities collateralized by their own loans.
   Nader told the subcommittee that commerical bank underwriting
and dealing in corporate securities ``involves serious conflicts of
interest that can injure public investors, undermine the integrity
of capital markets and are not readily controlled by any
realistically available set of safeguards.''
   Before Nader testified, David S. Ruder, chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission, told the subcommittee the
regulatory agency endorses Senate-passed legislation to permit
banks to enter the securities business ``so long as adequate
safeguards are established to address investor protection
concerns.''
   Ruder said the SEC believes the Senate legislation, sponsored by
William Proxmire, D-Wisc., has adequate safeguards for the repeal
of Glass-Steagall Act, which separated banking from the securities
business in the aftermath of the 1929 financial crash.
   ``The commission supports modification or repeal of the
Glass-Steagall Act as long as the investor protection concerns
arising from the entry of banks into securities activities are
simultaneously addressed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
