<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Democrats-Image Bjt   04-14 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats-Image, Bjt,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hollywood In Charge Of Look, Sound, Feel of Democratic National
Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood will add its touch to the
ready-made theater of the Democratic National Convention this
summer, but producers say the professional flourishes will be
tasteful and relevant.
   The Democratic National Convention Committee hired the
entertainment production company of Smith-Hemion to produce and
stage the Atlanta convention _ believed to be the first time the
Democrats have brought in theatrical producers to stage their
convention.
   Smith-Hemion has a history of staging ``events'' and has earned
20 Emmy awards over the years for its television extravaganzas,
said partner Gary Smith.
   Festivities like the Liberty Weekend celebration in Washington,
D.C., television's ``We the People 200'' featuring Walter Cronkite,
and Disneyland's 25th anniversary party were produced by the
company.
   Smith-Hemion will work with the media, create ``the look'' of
the arena, design the podium, oversee the sound and use big screens
to provide visual elements that have been pre-taped in support of
the speeches, Smith explained.
   ``Even in a convention there is room for relevant entertainment
_ tasteful and relevant,'' he said, adding that in his opinion a
convention should be more than a series of speeches.
   The agenda of the convention is up to the Democrats, he
emphasized, but the producers will supply ``things that are
emotionally effective or emotionally motivated and good information
that is visually enhanced.''
   Smith said it was too early to identify entertainers or special
effects to be used during the convention. Those things will be part
of the it, he said, ``but the Democrats have not gone into show
business. The most important priority is the need to maintain their
agenda.''
   Smith-Hemion's team of about 100 people started working six
weeks ago and will continue working until the convention is staged
July 18-21 in The Omni.
   ``This is a news event that TVs are picking up. Opening ceremony
on Liberty Weekend was a bit created. This convention is an
official American event. We would do it whether it was on
television or not,'' Smith said.
   He said the convention is more meaningful to him because ``if I
have ever been affiliated with any party, it would be Democratic.
But I have always voted for the person, not the party.''
   In addition to the staging and production work, Smith-Hemion
will provide closed circuit, gavel-to-gavel coverage that will be
available by satellite to every television station in the country,
he said.
   The art director for the convention is Rene Lagler, who worked
on both Liberty Weekend and the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles. ``He
is designing the look of the podium and how the arena will look
from a scenic standpoint,'' Smith said.
   How will Smith-Hemion rate the success of its work?
   ``I don't think ratings will enter into it whatsoever,'' he said
of the television ratings which usually tell networks whether they
have scored a commercial success.
   Emmy nominations and awards are a measure of creative success,
but that won't be a good gauge in this case either, he said.
   It will come down to whether ``the DNC says we did a good job,''
said Smith, who refused to identify a favorite candidate.
   If the Democratic nominee wins the presidential race in
November, ``that would make us feel pretty good. Obviously that is
the ultimate goal _ to win the election come November,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
