<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack-Arabs,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijacking Draws Attention Away From Palestinian Uprising In Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICK LUDINGTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hijacking of a Kuwaiti jet by Shiite
Moslems and the killing of two Kuwaiti hostages have embarrassed
Arab leaders who want world attention to remain focused on the Arab
uprising in Israel.
   Sheik Sabah Al-Ahmed, foreign minister of Kuwait, asked by
reporters about the hijackers, said ``regrettably we have to
concede they are Arabs.''
   The 4-month-old Palestinian uprising in Israeli-occupied
territory has brought an unusual degree of unity among Arabs,
radical and moderate, supporting Arabs youths defying Israeli armed
forces with stones and bottles.
   Pictures of the two Kuwaiti bodies thrown out of the jumbo jet
in Cyprus on Saturday and Monday and wired to newspapers and
television stations around the world, shook that unity. ``This
incident has spoiled the image of the Arabs in the world,'' said
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt.
   Mubarak said Israeli attempts to put down the uprising in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, where more than 140 Palestinians
have been killed since Dec. 8, were ``our prime preoccupation.''
   Yasser Arafat, leader of the Palestine Liberation Organization,
issued a message to the hijackers of the Kuwait Airways Boeing 747
that ``their action is not only hurting the Kuwaitis but the Arab
and Islamic nation.''
   Arafat said the hijacking _ which has taken the plane and
hostages from Mashhad, Iran, to Larnaca, Cyprus, to Algiers,
Algeria, in nine days _ took away the glare of world publicity from
the Palestinian revolt.
   ``This action diverts world attention from the uprising in the
West Bank and Gaza, and from the brutal and oppressive measures of
the Israeli occupying authorities,'' Foreign Minister Taher Masri
of Jordan told The Associated Press in Amman on Wednesday. Israel
captured the Gaza Strip from Egypt and the West Bank from Jordan in
the 1967 Middle East war.
   Marwan Dudin, Jordanian minister of occupied territories, said
the hijack ``contributed to harming the image of Arabs worldwide.''
   Dudin said most Europeans link Islam and Arabs and connect any
Moslem group with the fundamentalist revolution in Iran of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Masri said the hijack should not affect the Arab image. ``After
all we are the victims'' he said. Furthermore, he said: ``It is
clear they (the hijackers) are backed by the Iranian regime.''
   Although the current hijack is complicated by an alleged role
played by Iran _ which is Persian, not Arab _ it is not the first
time Arabs have hurt the image of their cause by violent disunity.
   Infighting including assasinations have plagued the PLO.
   For 13 years the world has been seeing gory scenes of Arab
killing Arab in the complicated carnage of the Lebanese civil war.
In the summer of 1977, border clashes brought Egypt and Libya to
the brink of war.
</TEXT>
