<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Drugs-Rail     04-14 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drugs-Rail,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One In Five Train Crews In Accidents Had Positive Drug, Alcohol
Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new General Accounting Office report shows
that drug and alcohol abuse by railroad crew members has become ``a
runaway train,'' a senator says.
   Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., offered that characterization on
Wednesday after the report was released by GAO, the investigative
arm of Congress. It reported that one in five crews involved in
train accidents during 1987 had at least one member test positive
for drugs or alcohol.
   The finding came during a review of the Federal Railroad
Administration's policy of requiring railroad workers in major
accidents to submit to drug and alcohol tests.
   On Feb. 11, the testing was struck down as unconstitutional by
the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco. But the
program remains in place while the Reagan administration appeals.
   ``Substance abuse on the rails is fast becoming a runaway
train,'' said Heinz, who requested the GAO study.
   Of 179 accidents during 1987, GAO found at least one positive
drug or alcohol finding in 37, or about 20 percent. However, the
report did not identify in how many of those cases the drugs or
alcohol actually figured in the accident.
   In all, 42, or 5.5 percent, of 770 rail workers sampled last
year following accidents tested positive for alcohol or illicit
drugs, said the FRA, which released its own figures this week in
answer to a reporter's query.
   GAO also reported that the amount of time needed to report drug
and alcohol test results has substantially improved.
   In April 1987, it took an average of 16.2 working days to report
initial screening test results for accidents where all crew members
tested negative. By October, the reporting time had been reduced to
4.8 working days, GAO said. It takes longer when positive results
are found, because they must be confirmed.
   Heinz had complained that long lags were hampering
investigations and unfairly placing suspicion on innocent crew
members.
   FRA ended an agreement with a Federal Aviation Administration
laboratory in Oklahoma City in March 1987 because it said it
discovered discrepancies in the results, according to GAO. In
April, FRA contracted with a toxicology center at the University of
Utah for the tests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880414-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ElderlyAlone     04-14 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elderly Alone,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Independent Elderly Live Longer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elderly people living alone are more likely to
maintain their independence and live longer if they visit with
friends and neighbors and attend church or other group events, a
government study reports.
   And people over age 70 who live alone are more likely to survive
over a two-year period than those who live with someone, the
National Center for Health Statistics found in the study made
public Wednesday.
   Both living alone and engaging in various activities were
indications of better health. The less active elderly were more
likely to die or become institutionalized over time.
   There is a noticeable difference for those people who have
contact with friends ands neighbors, who go to church or synagogue
or attend sports events, reported Dr. Mary Grace Kovar, author of
the study.
   Her findings in ``Aging in the Eighties, People Living Alone _
Two Years Later'' are based on interviews in 1984 and 1986 with
people who were 70 and older in 1984.
   Of those living alone who reported regular meetings with friends
and neighbors in 1984, 92.5 percent were still alive two years
later and 89.3 percent were still living on their own.
   On the other hand, of those who had no such contact, 86.6
percent survived two years and 81.5 percent still lived alone.
   For regular churchgoers in 1984, 94.9 percent survived two years
and 91.9 percent were still alone. Of those who didn't attend
church or synagogue, 86.2 percent survived and 81.9 percent lived
on their own.
   But regular contact with family did not seem a significant
factor in longer life and more independence. Perhaps those
reporting extra family contacts needed the help because they were
not well, Kovar speculated.
   ``Children may have come around more frequently ... just to make
sure'' the older folks were all right, she said.
   ``The most important thing (found in the study) is the
stability,'' Kovar said in a telephone interview.
   ``Most of these people, two years later, are still living in the
community. Those who were living alone are still alone, and those
with someone else are still with someone else,'' she said.
   ``As you would expect, because these people are 72 or older,
death rates are high. But relatively few of them are in nursing
homes,'' she noted.
   Of nearly 6.4 million elderly people living alone in 1984, 89.8
percent were still alive two years later, she found.
   By comparison, 89.0 percent of those living with a spouse
survived two years and 84.3 percent who had been living with
someone else were still alive.
   Of those who had been on their own in 1984, Kovar found that by
1986, 77.8 percent were still living by themselves. Some 7.4
percent of them had moved in with someone else _ most often family
_ and 4.6 percent were in an institution.
   ``It certainly appears that for some of them life is better''
two years later, she added. ``Some have remarried _ not many but
some _ and when we asked those who had moved why ... we got''
answers ranging from health to being nearer to children to spending
the summer in Maine and winter in Florida. One, she said, even
cited lower golf fees for moving.
   A major factor in continued independence is likely that those
living alone were more healthy at the start of the study, she
concluded in the report.
   Health was also a factor in the stability of those living alone,
she found.
   For example, people who needed help with basic daily activities
such as bathing, dressing, eating or using the toilet, were much
more likely to have died over the two year span.
   While only about 10 percent of all those living alone died in
the two year period, 25 percent of those who had needed help in
basic daily activities died and 16 percent were in nursing homes
after two years.
   ``It is very difficult ... to disentangle'' all the factors
affecting these people, she said. Another follow-up series of
interviews is scheduled for this summer, to compare the same group
of elderly in 1988.
   Overall, she found that nursing homes appear to be a last resort
for the elderly.
   These is evidence of a progression, she reported, ``people live
alone, then with other people if others are available, then they
may become nursing home residents.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
