<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmDebt     04-14 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Debt,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FmHA Plans to Erase $8.8 Billion in Farm Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some $8.8 billion in lingering debt owed by
agricultural producers will be wiped from the books of the Farmers
Home Administration under a measure approved by lawmakers last
year, the agency's administrator says.
   ``It is true that we are probably writing off upwards of $8
billion to $9 billion over the next couple of years and the
agricultural credit act is responsible for a substantial portion of
that,'' FmHA Administrator Vance Clark told a Senate Appropriations
panel Wednesday.
   Under provisions of the Farm Credit Act approved last year, FmHA
will ``write down,'' or defer payments, on $2.1 billion in debt
owed by farmers who will be restored to profitability as a result,
the agency said.
   Eventually, it said, the government may still be able to recover
some of that money.
   But it said would simply write off $6.7 billion in
non-performing loans to farmers who even with such help will not be
able to turn a profit.
   Last year's legislation required the government to take such
actions if they would be less expensive for the taxpayers than
foreclosure.
   Clark's disclosure followed an unconfirmed report last month
that the government most likely would write off $7 billion in FmHA
loans.
   The disclosure came in response to a question from Sen. Charles
Grassley, R-Iowa, who had seen the earlier published report and was
concerned about it.
   Grassley was critical of Clark, however, for saying that it was
the Farm Credit Act that was costing the money.
   He said that in every case foreclosure would have been more
expensive and thus the taxpayers were not losing anything that they
would not have lost anyway.
   ``They're including costs that would have been there even if
Congress had not passed the bill,'' Grassley said.
   He called the foreclosure-expense test ``a very objective,
bottom line decision that really means what Congress passed isn't
costing the federal government anything.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
