<1ST_LINE>r p PM-VotingBlocs     04-14 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Voting Blocs,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Few Of The Large Voting Blocs Have Settled On Democratic Favorite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most black and Jewish voters have coalesced
around the two chief competitors in New York's Democratic
presidential primary but other potentially large voting blocs
remain fragmented, political analysts say.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s attempt to outflank Gov. Michael Dukakis
for the Jewish vote appears destined to fall short, an expert in
Jewish opinion said Wednesday. And Jesse Jackson's strength remains
greatest with blacks, said other experts.
   The analysts said other major groups _ such as union members,
homosexuals and Roman Catholics _ do not seem to be drawn to any of
the candidates by a single overriding issue in next Tuesday's vote.
   What then may come into play for these Democratic voters is the
pragmatic issue of which candidate is most likely to win the
presidency, said Meyer S. Frucher, a leading political strategist.
   A key battle has been for Jews, up to a quarter of the
Democratic vote. Gore has sought their support by placing himself
to Dukakis' right on Middle East policy, flatly opposing formation
of a Palestinian state.
   The hard line may help Gore in Brooklyn, where 25 percent of the
400,000 Jews are in the Orthodox sect, said Steven M. Cohen, a
sociology professor at Queens College who has polled Jewish
attitudes for a decade.
   But the effort likely will fail overall, Cohen said, because
Dukakis and Gore are close enough on Middle East policy for either
to be acceptable to the majority of Jews, and Dukakis appeals to
them on other grounds.
   ``Dukakis is seen as friendly because he's a Northeast liberal
ethnic,'' Cohen said. ``He's our type of guy.''
   Jackson has received black backing in the 90-percent range in
other states, and blacks, like Jews, account for up to a quarter of
the Democratic vote in New York. He also may count on broad support
from Hispanics, said Victor Alicea, a Hispanic leader. But in 1984,
Hispanics made up just 4 percent of the state primary vote.
   Organized labor is divided, said Theodore W. Kheel, a longtime
labor mediator in the city. The Central Labor Council and the State
Federation of Labor are neutral, he said, while local leaders ``are
all over the lot.''
   In the absence of a defining issue, Catholics also do not
constitute a strong voting block, and ``I don't think there's going
to be a Catholic groundswell for any Democratic candidate,'' said
Ed Wilkinson, editor of The Tablet, the newspaper of the
Archdiocese of Brooklyn and Queens.
   Nonetheless, said pollster Lee Miringoff of the Marist College
Institute for Public Opinion, ``I think the white ethnic vote is
going to Dukakis at this point.''
   Dukakis, a Greek-American, also expects enthusiastic support
from the Greek community, which has about 65,000 adult U.S.
citizens in the city.
   Homosexuals are in far more of a quandary. Many activists reject
Dukakis because of his opposition to homosexual couples as foster
parents, said Thomas B. Stoddard, director of the Lambda Legal
Defense and Education Fund. But many fear Jackson or Gore would
lose to the Republican.
   The result is that some voters will go for Jackson, who is
viewed overall as better on homosexual issues, said Stoddard. Those
less concerned about the foster parent issues will back Dukakis. A
few will vote for Gore, whose standing is ``uncertain'' on
homosexual issues other than AIDS.
   ``Some,' Stoddard added, ``will simply stay home.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
