<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     04-14 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Jackson Lead In Federal Matching Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission says the eight
former and current presidential candidates have collected a total
of $50.7 million from the public treasury for the 1988 presidential
race.
   The commission said the $2.7 million given to the group on
Wednesday is included in that amount.
   Vice President George Bush received $322,500, bringing his total
FEC draw to $7.7 million _ second only to the $8.5 million given to
vanquished GOP rival Pat Robertson, who got $33,750 in the latest
allotment.
   Among the Democrats, Jesse Jackson got the largest new influx of
federal matching funds, $903,000, bringing the FEC total for the
once financially strapped candidate to $2.4 million. Michael
Dukakis received $827,000 on Wednesday, putting his total at $6.7
million. The only other Democrat still actively campaigning,
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., got $270,235, bringing his total to
$2.9 million.
   The federal fund matches every contribution of $250 or less that
the candidates raise from individuals.
   The fund is supported by the $1 voluntary checkoff on individual
income tax returns.
</TEXT>
