<HEAD>Brock Volunteers To Help Bush Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. Bill Brock, who managed Bob
Dole's presidential campaign, has volunteered to help Vice
President George Bush since Dole withdrew from the race.
   Brock, who resigned as secretary of Labor to head the Senate
majority leader's campaign, said he woukld probably be a part-time
volunteer to the Bush campaign. But he said had no specific job in
mind when he spoke with the vice president.
   ``What it would entail I honestly don't know,'' Brock said in a
telephone interview on Wednesday. ``I didn't make any specific
suggestion to them.''
   Brock, who saw Dole's campaign crumble following the New
Hampshire primary on Feb. 16, described Bush as a ``good and honest
man'' who had run a first-rate campaign.
   Brock, former chairman of the National Republican Executive
Committee who has been known in the past for his organizational
skills, said trying to run a successful Dole campaign against Bush
was nearly impossible.
