<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Elections Board Spreads Word: Some NY Voters Need Not Show Up
Tuesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential primary elections
have been called off in 16 New York congressional districts where
delegates supporting Vice President George Bush are running
unopposed.
   Under election rules, the Bush delegates have automatically been
designated as part of the New York delegation to the GOP national
convention in New Orleans, according to state Republican Committee
Executive Director Ed Lurie.
   That GOP delegation will include 136 members. Primary day voters
will select 96. The state Republican Committee will designate the
rest after the primary.
   Steven LaFever, a spokesman for the state Board of Elections,
said Wednesday the board is ``trying to spread the word'' that
voters will find Republican voting machines locked at polling
places in the 16 uncontested districts if they show up for
Tuesday's primary.
   As things stood Wednesday, registered Republicans can cast their
ballots in 16 of the state's 34 congressional districts on primary
day. Those districts have delegate slates on the ballot supporting
Bush and candidates opposing the vice president.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Won't Adopt Flynn's Suggestion for Black VP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis says he won't limit his
vice presidential running mate choice to a black candidate as
suggested by Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn.
   In outlining qualities he would want in a running mate Wednesday
when the Democratic presidential candidate was asked his opinion of
Flynn's suggestion Dukakis said, if nominated, he would try to pick
a running mate who ``first and foremost'' is qualified to serve as
president if called upon. Secondly, Dukakis said, he would seek a
vice presidential candidate who would strengthen the ticket.
   ``I certainly wouldn't limit the choice to any one group of
people,'' he added.
   Flynn, a supporter of Dukakis and an admirer of Jesse Jackson,
said he would like to see Jackson run as vice president. But if not
Jackson, Flynn said, then some other black should be on the ticket.
   ``I'd rather see the Democrats lose than win without a black on
the ticket,'' the mayor said.
</TEXT>
