<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     04-14 0912</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feed Drug Found in Milk Samples, But Officials Say No Health
Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have found small residues of a
potentially cancer-causing animal drug in milk being sold in 10
U.S. cities, according to an official of the Food and Drug
Administration.
   The drug, sulfamethazine, is approved for use in pork and beef
cattle feed but is not supposed to be used in dairy cattle feed.
   ``The levels we were finding (in milk) should not cause a public
health problem, but we are concerned because this is an illegal use
and that drug must not be used in dairy cattle,'' Gerald Guest,
head of the agency's Center for Veterinary Medicine, said in a
statement Wednesday.
   ``We have been meeting with the appropriate industry groups, and
they already have programs under way to communicate this concern to
their respective industries,'' Guest said.
   FDA officials in early March bought and sampled pasteurized
whole milk from five grocery stores in each of the 10 cities _
Boston, Baltimore, Atlanta, Dallas, Chicago, Kansas City, Denver,
San Francisco, Seattle and New York.
   Of the 49 samples, 36 showed some sign of the drug, FDA
spokesman Chris Lecos said. Of the 36, he added, only five were
above trace levels.
   ``There is no reason for the public to be concerned about the
safety of the milk,'' Lecos said. ``The point is we don't want to
find it (sulfamethazine) in milk at all.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Congress Urged To Clear Up Muddled Ash Picture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawsuits, barges searching to dump garbage,
and piles of refuse all serve notice that Congress needs to clear
up confusion over how states should handle incinerator ash, say
some local officials.
   ``Ordinarily, municipal officials, as I'm sure you well know,
resist and resent endless federal mandates,'' said Beulah
Coughenour from Indianapolis, who spoke on behalf of the National
League of Cities before the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee
Wednesday.
   ``This time we come before you from the opposite perspective. We
are here to ask for exactly that _ federal intervention in an area
that is uniquely a local government responsibility,'' Coughenour
said. ``Our need right now is for certainty.''
   Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Lee Thomas told
the panel he supports the approach of a bill by Rep. Thomas Luken,
D-Ohio, that seeks to end confusion over the handling of ash from
140 municipal waste combustors processing about 15 million tons of
refuse each year.
   At issue is whether incinerator ash is to be considered
hazardous or non-hazardous solid waste. Thomas said EPA is looking
to Congress for help on whether ash from waste-to-energy
incinerators should be exempt from stringent hazardous waste
regulations that could mean high cost and lots of paperwork for
communities.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bill Would Provide Greater Protection Against Crimes By Foreign
Diplomats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers, police officers and New York City
officials are endorsing a bill that would give American citizens
greater protection against crimes committed by foreign diplomats
and dependents who are immune from arrest or prosecution.
   ``The passage of this bill will send a clear message to those
lawbreakers who know our hands have been tied by the present laws,
that they will no longer be able to wave a paper called diplomatic
immunity and walk away scot-free,'' said Dennis Ray Martin, deputy
sheriff of Saginaw County in Michigan and president of the
68,000-member American Federation of Police.
   Under an international agreement which was approved by the
Senate in 1965 and implemented in 1978, ambassadors and other
diplomats and their family members enjoy complete immunity from
criminal prosecution or civil lawsuits, but various exceptions are
made for lesser personnel.
   The bill, sponsored Wednesday chiefly by Rep. Stephen J. Solarz,
D-N.Y., would put Congress on record as favoring State Department
action to obtain waivers of diplomatic immunity or the forced
departure of diplomats who are charged with serious crimes.
   The State Department said recently that it generally supports
the draft legislation but objects to several provisions as
unnecessary or potentially harmful to U.S. relations with other
countries.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Witnesses Say Foster Care Law Not Being Enforced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foster children continue to be neglected and
mistreated despite a law meant to make sure they have safe and
permanent homes, preferably with their own families, say children's
rights advocates.
   The Adoption Assistance and Child Welfare Amendments passed in
1980 are not being enforced by the federal government or the states
and the results are devastating, Marcia Lowry, director of the
Children's Rights Project of the American Civil Liberties Union
said at a congressional hearing Wednesday.
   Lowry was accompanied by a 12-year-old identified as Boyd A. who
spent years moving from one New York City foster home to another
while his mother, who had been temporarily hospitalized, used a
class action lawsuit to get her five children back.
   ``Sometimes we didn't like to visit our mother. You know why?
Sometimes they would have to tear us apart. We wouldn't leave. I
couldn't stand it,'' he said. ``They took almost five years away
from my life. That's almost one-half of my whole life that I spent
just waiting to come back to my real family.''
   More than 450,000 children spend some time in foster care each
year as a result of parental illness or disability, parent-child
conflicts, a child's severe emotional or behavioral problems or an
encounter with the law, said Rep. Tom Downey, D-N.Y., acting
chairman of the Ways and Means public assistance subcommittee.
</TEXT>
