<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KentuckyInvestigation     04-14 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kentucky Investigation,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shipment To Athlete's Dad Held $1,000 Cash, Paper Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Smrt in 8th graf and Claud in 9th graf are cq; a longer
version moving on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A package from the University of Kentucky to
the father of a high school basketball star contained $1,000 in
cash, a newspaper reported today.
   Chris Mills of Los Angeles' Fairfax High School, his father and
university officials denied any knowledge of the money, the Daily
News reported.
   Mills signed a Nov. 11 letter of intent to accept a basketball
scholarship from the university, which was reprimanded last month
by the National Collegiate Athletic Association for minor
violations after a lengthy investigation of alleged substantial
payments made to other players.
   University President David P. Roselle, in a statement Wednesday,
said the school learned Friday of possible new NCAA violations from
a Daily News reporter's telephone call, and asked for NCAA help to
investigate.
   ``It is our intention to find out what happened, to report
everything we find to the NCAA, to take full responsibility for
whatever is proved to have occurred,'' he said.
   Mills, one of the top high school basketball players in
California, was heavily recruited across the nation. The 6-foot-7
Los Angeles City 4-A player of the year in 1987 scored an average
of 28.3 points a game.
   Charles Smrt, an investigator for the NCAA, was in Los Angeles
on Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. He declined to discuss the case.
   A shipment record obtained by the Daily News showed the package
was sent March 30 via Emery Worldwide air freight by Kentucky
assistant basketball coach Dwane Casey to the player's father,
Claud Mills.
   In interviews in the last week, Emery employees told the Daily
News they noticed cash when a package broke open during handling
March 31 at their Los Angeles shipment center.
   Casey denied he put money in the package. ``We don't recruit
that way,'' Casey said. ``But I have never, ever put any money in a
package. That accusation is ridiculous.''
   Casey said the package he sent contained Claud Mills' videotape
of his son playing basketball.
   Claud Mills said he had been interviewed by the NCAA, and no
money was in the package when he got it. He acknowledged that an
Emery employee told him a package containing cash was addressed to
him and was awaiting delivery.
   His son said Friday that he knew nothing about any money from
the university, according to the newspaper.
   Officials at Kentucky denied any wrongdoing. ``I can promise you
it didn't occur,'' said Kentucky head basketball coach Eddie Sutton.
   NCAA officials said serious penalties could be imposed if the
allegation is substantiated.
   Eric Osborn, the Emery employee who found an opened package when
it arrived in Los Angeles, said he looked inside and saw money
sticking out of a videocassette box.
   His supervisor, Paul Perry, said he called over several
employees as witnesses and counted out $1,000 in $50 bills and then
had the package sealed by security personnel.
   Claud Mills acknowledged he received a videotape from Casey on
March 31. He said his son signed for the package and that when he
got home he found the videotape, but no cash, in the opened packet.
   ``I didn't receive no money from Dwane Casey,'' Claud Mills
said. ``Nobody from Kentucky gave me no money. They sent me a tape,
but I don't know nothing about no money.''
   Claud Mills said his son, a two-time Parade magazine
All-America, picked the University of Kentucky because of coach
Sutton, and the style of play there.
   Claud Mills said an NCAA investigator had questioned him earlier
about a car he bought for his son. He said he paid $6,800 for the
car, a 1984 Datsun 300ZX, with the proceeds of a lawsuit.
</TEXT>
