<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PLOMission-Suit     04-14 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO Mission-Suit,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Seeks to Dismiss Action to Close U.N. Observer Mission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has refused one request to
temporarily block legal action to close the Palestine Liberation
Organization's United Nations observer mission.
   But U.S. District Judge Edmund Palmieri has scheduled an April
20 hearing on another request to block enforcement of the 1987
Anti-Terrorism Act. The law declared the PLO and its affiliates a
terrorist organization.
   Meanwhile, lawyers for the PLO are seeking to dismiss a federal
lawsuit that would force the closing of the mission.
   The government's lawsuit seeks a court order barring the PLO;
Zehdi Labib Terzi, head of the observer mission; and five other
mission officials or employees from continuing to operate the
mission or any other PLO office in this country.
   But PLO counsel Ramsey Clark, a former U.S. attorney general,
said in papers filed Monday at federal court that no U.S. court has
jurisdiction to issue such an order because it would violate
international law as well as the treaty setting up U.N.
headquarters in New York.
   The Justice Department has yet to file a response.
   In a related matter, Palmieri refused on Tuesday to grant a
preliminary injunction, blocking enforcement of the Anti-Terrorism
Act.
   He ruled that a group of U.S. citizens who say the act violates
their First Amendment rights had shown insufficient proof they
would suffer undue hardship or irreparable harm unless an
injunction were granted.
   Palmieri has scheduled a hearing for later this month on another
aspect of the lawsuit. Riyad Mansour, a U.S. citizen and No. 2
official at the PLO mission, said the law does not apply to him in
his official capacity at the United Nations, or if it does it is
unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
