<DOCNO> AP880414-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0536EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WrongCounty     04-14 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wrong County,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial in Wrong County Starts Ethical, Legal Arguments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mistrial granted to a murder defendant whose
case was prosecuted in the wrong county has triggered debate on
whether he should go free, and on the ethics of his lawyer, who
knew about the error but kept mum.
   ``All this guy's got going for him is me,'' public defender Bob
Joiner said Wednesday. ``If I've got to help the prosecutor, my
God, he'd be better off without a lawyer.''
   Stephen Craig Schiefelbein, 38, was accused of fatally stabbing
a man who invited him to dinner Christmas Eve 1986 at an Atlanta
home that purportedly straddles the line between Fulton and DeKalb
counties.
   The mistrial was granted April 6, the second day of his trial in
Fulton County Superior Court, when a prosecutor learned that the
house actually is in DeKalb County and that Joiner had known it all
along.
   Joiner contends that his client should go free because a second
prosecution, this time in DeKalb County, would violate the
constitutional prohibition against double jeopardy.
   ``It would be a miscarriage of justice if he were able to escape
because of a problem like that,'' said Steve Roberts, chief
assistant district attorney in DeKalb County, where the state may
press for a trial.
   Law officers in both counties assured prosecutors the house was
in Fulton County, said Assistant District Attorney Linda Finley,
who learned the truth when she telephoned a witness after the first
day of Schiefelbein's trial.
   Ms. Finley said she was reviewing the next day's testimony with
the owner of the house when ``he informed me that his house was in
fact about two houses over the line in DeKalb County.''
   The next day, Joiner said he had known of the mixup and Judge
Philip Etheridge declared a mistrial, telling Joiner he had
``wasted a lot of time and did your client absolutely no service
whatever.''
   Joiner said Wednesday it ``never even occurred to me'' to tell
the judge earlier because ethics rules for lawyers require him to
use any defense that is not frivolous.
   Joiner ``had an obligation not to say anything,'' said Geoffrey
C. Hazard Jr., a Yale Law School professor of legal ethics and the
main draftsman of the American Bar Association's model code of
ethics.
   ``The defendant in a criminal case is permitted to require the
state to go to its proof on every possible issue, and it's the
state's responsibility to carry the burden in that respect,''
Hazard said. ``The defendant did nothing to mislead the
prosecution, and I think (Joiner) did the right thing.''
   University of Georgia law professor L. Ray Patterson said legal
codes of ethics discourage disclosures of information by defense
lawyers but conflict with a lawyer's duties as an officer of the
court.
   ``Frankly, I sympathize with the lawyer,'' said Patterson, a
former dean of Emory University's law school. ``The courts have not
given good guidance on this. They've waffled on the issue.''
   Joiner says federal courts have held that part of a criminal
case is proving it is being brought in the right court, so failure
to prove that voids the entire prosecution. Another trial would be
double jeopardy, he said.
   Etheridge disagreed with that argument, saying his court never
really had jurisdiction over the case so ``anything we did would be
a nullity.''
   Roberts said the DeKalb County prosecutors already have found
legal precedents supporting a retrial, but no decision will be made
until the case file and the judge's order are received from Fulton
County.
   Joiner also contends that there are factual issues in the case.
   He said victim Michael G. Hadden, Schiefelbein and others in the
house had been drinking, that no one thought Hadden's wound was
serious enough to summon help, and he might have died simply from a
lack of medical attention.
   Schiefelbein also contends Hadden was choking him, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
