<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NicaraguanPrisoner     04-14 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaraguan Prisoner,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoner Tells of Sandinista Abuse, Threats _ Says Cubans Involved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot held five years in Sandinista prisons said
he was threatened with death and denied medical treatment as part
of systematic psychological torture apparently directed by Cuban
intelligence agents.
   Roberto Amador, 42, shot down during a Contra supply flight in
1983, was one of the first prisoners freed as part of last month's
truce agreement between the Nicaraguan Resistance and the leftist
Sandinista government.
   He arrived here Saturday to join his wife and three children.
   Amador and other Contra officials said at a news conference here
Wednesday they believe there are up to 12,000 political prisoners
inside Nicaraguan jails despite government claims to the contrary.
   Amador said he had been threatened before leaving Nicaragua and
told not to talk to reporters.
   ``They told me, `If you make declarations to the press in the
United States, we will put a bomb in your car in Miami or anywhere
else you go,''' said Amador. They reminded him of the assassination
of former Nicaraguan dicator Anastasio Somoza in Paraguay after he
fled the Sandinista revolution in 1979.
   Amador, 42, said at least three of the seven crew members on his
doomed 1983 flight died in Sandinista hands even though all
survived the crash of their plane, which he said was flying
medicine, books and clothes to the rebels.
   When they were captured, some of the men were bound hand and
foot and flown to El Chipote prison in Managua.
   ``We expected death at any minute,'' said Amador. ``They said
they were going to kill us.''
   Two crew members stayed behind and were never heard from again,
and he later found a third was officially reported dead.
   At the prison, where he was kept in solitary confinement for 1{
years, Amador was regularly seated for 12 to 16 hours in a chair
while he was threatened and interrogated.
   In the partially darkened room, he said, he could hear
Cuban-accented men speaking Spanish and occasionally heard German,
which he believed was spoken by East German advisers. Two Cuban
exile Contra sympathizers still in prison in Nicaragua later told
him they were being interrogated by Cuban G-2 intelligence agents,
he said.
   He said he believes the Cubans were teaching their techniques to
the Sandinistas.
   ``They worked on the mind with constant death threats,'' said
Amador. ``They told me if I didn't talk they would get my family in
the United States, they would kill my children, and they would kill
me.'' At one point they falsely claimed they were holding ``someone
I loved,'' the pilot said.
   He said the guards held drills in which they would send soldiers
to the door of each cell and point a Soviet-made rifle at the
prisoners.
   ``They were waiting for an American invasion,'' said Amador.
``They said as soon as the 82nd (Airborne Division) landed, we
would be eliminated.''
   Amador said he was told his family, the United States, and the
resistance had abandoned him.
   The pilot suffered what he later found out was a crushed disc
during his crash landing, and was in constant pain, which his
interrogators used against him, he said.
   ``They would open the cabinet and show me the medicine for my
pain,'' he said. ``Then they would say, `are you going to talk?'''
He said he refused and was never given the pain-reliever. Doctors
in the United States later said his jailers had unintentionally
helped him by forcing him to sleep on the floor, giving some relief
to his back.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
