<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-14 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Hit Record High In Japan; Dollar Down Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today
closed above 27,000 points for the first time, while the dollar
fell marginally against the Japanese yen in quiet trading.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 54.71-point
winner Wednesday, reached a record high for the fifth time since
last Thursday, adding another 125.80 points, or 0.46 percent, to
finish the day at 27,111.35.
   Since the current upward trend began at the end of March, the
Nikkei index surged by about 1,400 points.
   The market continued to be in a bullish mood, boosted by the
agreement by the seven top industrialized nations to work together
to keep the U.S currency from falling further and by prospects for
favorable U.S. trade figures to be announced today in Washigton,
said Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko Securities.
   In a two-page, joint communique issued Wednesday in Washington,
the finance ministers and central bank governors of the seven
nations announced the extension of a Dec. 22 agreement in which
they pledged to work together to keep the U.S. currency from
falling further against the Japanese yen.
   Participating in the meeting were the United States, Japan,
France, Britain, Canada, Italy and Germany.
   Shimoyama said share prices were generally higher with
construction and housing issues among the most popular.
   There was nothing to hold the market back and the major brokers
were apparently determined to push the Nikkei index through the
27,000 barrier, traders said.
   Volume of the first-section trade was a heavy 1.2 billion
shares, up from 1 billion shares on Wednesday. Advancing issues
outpaced decliners 504 to 375, while 185 issues were unchanged.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at
126.15 yen, down 0.30 from its close of 126.45 yen Wednesday. It
had opened the day at 126.20 and ranged between 126.10-126.43 yen.
   ``The meeting in Washington of the seven major nations didn't
really affect trading, as the results were what had been
expected,'' said Makoto Sato of the Bank of Tokyo. He said the
market was rather quiet while awiting the announcement of U.S.
trade figures today in Washington.
   The United States' huge trade deficit has affected the dollar's
direction in recent months because the U.S. government has
supported a lower dollar as a way of narrowing the gap.
</TEXT>
