<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DenverRecall     04-14 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Denver Recall,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Effort to Recall Denver Mayor Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A months-long effort to recall Mayor Federico Pena
on grounds of mismanagement was rebuffed when a city official
announced the number of signatures on petitions fell more than
2,000 short of the total needed.
   The backers of the drive delivered 21 bundles of petitions to
the Denver Election Commission on Wednesday, beating a 5 p.m.
deadline by several hours and expressing confidence there would be
enough valid signatures to support a new mayoral election.
   But late Wednesday Felicia Muftic, president of the election
commission, said only 36,960 names were counted, short of the
minimum 39,091 needed. The validity of the signatures was not
checked.
   Pena reacted with pleasure, saying, ``To those people who
opposed the recall, I thank you. To those people who supported the
recall, I urge you to join with the city to help move the city
forward. These are critical times and we cannot afford to have any
disunity.''
   Critics, however, said the troubled city government will only be
worse unless Pena gets the message and starts ``running things in a
little better way,'' as city councilman Paul Swalm said.
   ``If he doesn't, why you know I just think the city is going to
be in very bad shape in a year or two. It's already in bad shape
now, but it'll be worse,'' he said.
   Pena, 41, one of the first Hispanics to be mayor of a major U.S.
city, was elected to his second term last June by 3,000 votes in a
hotly disputed contest that required a runoff of top contenders.
   The recall drive was started by a group angered over what they
claimed was fiscal mismanagement by the Pena administration. The
group gathered supporters among a number of Denver residents left
stranded for several days by a major holiday snow storm.
   Maintenance crews plowed major traffic arteries, leaving side
streets filled with snow for several days. At the time, Pena was
vacationing out-of-state.
   The 39,091 votes needed for the recall represented 25 percent of
the voters in the last mayoral election, said Sam Tarkington,
executive director of the election commission.
</TEXT>
