<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Chebrikov     04-14 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Chebrikov,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>KGB Chief Blames National Unrest On Education, Secret Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the KGB secret police blamed ethnic
unrest that broke out in two southern republics and other areas of
the Soviet Union on poor education and foreign secret services.
   Viktor Chebrikov's speech on Wednesday in the Volga River city
of Cheboksary was his first public comment on ethnic tensions in
the Soviet Union since rioting occurred in the Azerbaijan republic
on Feb. 28.
   At least 32 people were killed in the rioting, 26 of them ethnic
Armenians. Thousands of people began mass protests in neighboring
Armenia in mid-February to demand that the Nagorno-Karabakh region
of Azerbaijan be annexed to Armenia.
   Three-quarters of the region's residents are ethnic Armenians,
who traditionally are Christians. Azerbaijanis traditionally are
Moslems.
   Chebrikov did not mention Azerbaijan and Armenia, but said
``anti-social actions of a nationalistic nature took place in a
number of regions of this country,'' according to a report issued
by the Tass news agency.
   ``I believe that one of the major reasons for those anti-social
actions is a serious negliect of the internationalist education of
popular masses,'' Chebrikov was quoted as saying.
   He also blamed wrong approaches to solving social-economic
problems, and said ``groundless notions'' about the problem-free
development of relations between nationalities also played a part.
   The latter was an apparent reference to the Soviet Union's
claims in the past to have solved the problem of relations among
nationalities.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev said at a Communist Party
Central Committee meeting in February that the problem is one of
the country's most serious, and that the Central Committee will
devote an upcoming meeting to it.
   The Soviet Union, a country of more than 100 ethnic groups,
tries to teach citizens to de-emphasize nationalistic feelings in
favor of what is termed a spirit of friendship and equality with
other ethnic groups.
   But ethnic groups often resent domination by Russians and other
Slavs, and ages-old tensions exist among some of the ethnic groups.
   Chebrikov also said that foreign secret service organizations
that he did not identify played a part in stirring up ethnic
tensions. ``It is an open secrety that secret services of
imperalist powers and foreign anti-Soviet centers actively join
extremist nationalistic actions,'' he said.
   ``Later on they start playing the part of open instigators of
hostile actions aimed at kindling hostility among nations,''
Chebrikov said.
   ``One should not underestimate the danger of this method of
subversive actions against this country. However, in my opinion,
the main attention should be concentrated on a timely solution of
the emerging socio-economic problems, on the education in patriotic
and internationalist spirit,'' he said.
   In a televised speech in September, Chebrikov accused the West
of trying to undermine Soviet economic reforms and sow discord
among nationalities.
   Besides the tensions in Armenia and Azerbaijan, there also has
been an increase in nationalist activities in the Baltic republics
of Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, in Kazakhstan, and among Crimean
Tatars who were deported from their homeland by Stalin because of
alleged cooperation with Nazi invaders in World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
