<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-TearGas     04-14 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Tear Gas,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Says Israelis Use Gas Causing Miscarriages, Muscular
Weakness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Israel, Bjt
^By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. health official who visited
Israel's occupied territories said today that Palestinians are
suffering abdominal pain, miscarriages and muscular weakness from
tear gas Israel is using against them.
   Dr. John Hiddlestone, U.N. Relief and Works Agency director of
health affairs, said in a telephone interview that he saw
Palestinians experiencing symptoms ``which were not those usually
associated with tear gas.''
   But he added: ``I'm not actually accusing anybody of anything.''
   The agency said the gas was being used improperly. The Israeli
army denied the charge.
   Agency spokesman Ron Wilkinson reported several cases in which
tear gas had been thrown into closed areas, houses, schools and a
clinic in Israeli-held territory.
   ``It says right on the canisters that it must not be used in a
confined area. So it (the gas) has particular toxic effects when it
is thrown into a room,'' he said.
   ``One label says: `For outdoor use only. Contents may cause
severe injury if not used in accordance with this warning
instruction.'''
   In the Israeli-occupied Gaza Strip, agency spokeswoman Christine
Debaigh said a 70-year-old woman, Wadfah Farraj Allah, was dead on
arrival at Jabaliya's U.N. clinic on Wednesday after troops hurled
a tear gas canister into her home.
   Shifa Hospital officials said Mrs. Allah suffocated after
inhaling the gas. An army spokesman denied the account and said
that ``results of an autopsy carried out by the (government-run)
Pathological Institute in Abu Kabir showed the woman died of
natural causes.''
   UNRWA is providing shelter, education and medical assistance to
Palestinian refugees living in the Middle East.
   ``I am a physician and my worry is that people are having other
symptoms than normal tear gas symptoms,'' Hiddlestone said.
   ``We need to know what's being used in the hope we can do more
for these people because the abdominal pain is extremely severe of
women who have been miscarrying and have had premature labor,'' he
said.
   The doctor said he also met people suffering from ``great
muscular weakness'' after exposure to gas used by the Israelis.
   He said those ailments occurred without eye, nose or throat
irritation, ``so that even though you have tear gas which is in
improper concentrations when it's put into closed spaces, the
symptomatology of some people is not that which is normal as a
result of tear gas.''
   An army spokesman said: ``There is no truth to the report we are
using a new type of toxic gas. The purpose of tear gas is to limit
casualties and to cause as little damage as possible by avoiding
physical confrontation with the rioters.''
   He said tear gas could be lethal if inhaled by people already
suffering from heart or other health problems, or if used in a
small enclosed space.
   ``The army does not use tear gas in small enclosed spaces, at
least not on purpose,'' said the spokesman, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   The Boston-based Physicians for Human Rights has expressed
concern that the Israelis may be misusing tear gas.
   The American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee, a lobbying
group, contends that more than 30 people have died in Israel and in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip from exposure to tear gas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880414-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0826EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BaltimoreFire     04-14 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baltimore Fire,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waterfront Fire Destroys Three Companies</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserColor BA3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire raged out of control for eight hours along
the Baltimore waterfront, shooting flames 100 feet into the air and
filling the sky with thick, black smoke. Three businesses were
destroyed.
   More than 200 firefighters battled the intense heat and flames
of the seven-alarm blaze, which was not brought under control until
6:30 a.m. today. Five firefighters suffered minor injuries.
   The fire was discovered about 10:30 p.m. Wednesday at an
automotive lubricant company, and arson was suspected, said Fire
Department spokesman Capt. Patrick Flynn.
   ``It's a very hot fire,'' Flynn said during the night battle.
The solvents and motor oils ``added a lot of fuel to the fire. The
troubling thing about this, you don't know what's going to happen
next.''
   The fire threatened the vacant Allied Chemical plant, but did
not reach the building. Fire officials had been afraid the heat
would trigger an explosion there.
   The fire apparently began at Autoline Lubricants Inc., and sent
55-gallon drums of oil and lubricants rocketing into the sky. It
spread to Atlantic Mill and Lumber Co., then engulfed Lacy
Foundries.
   ``It looked like the world was on fire,'' said Meg Craft, 36,
who was awakened when an explosion shook her home.
   The area lies on a peninsula across the water from the Inner
Harbor and a few blocks from the historic Fells Point area.
   The flames soared 100 feet into the air and could be seen for
several miles, drawing Fells Point residents into the streets to
watch. Dense, black clouds of smoke hung over the area.
   The fire went to seven alarms within a half-hour, Flynn said.
Firefighters stood poised on hydraulic booms, aiming their hoses
down onto the blaze, while others manned fireboats in the harbor.
   Autoline President Edward Peres, 46, and executive vice
president Bob Scott, 45, watched somberly. Peres said the company
had about $1.2 million in inventory.
   Autoline receptionist Sally Nowicki, 33, was near tears. ``It's
terrible, it's awful, My heart just aches for them,'' she said of
Peres and Scott. ``They're watching everything they owned go up in
smoke. They worked so hard, they don't deserve this.''
   ``I'm in no condition to talk,'' said Sidney Meyer, president of
Atlantic Mill and Lumber. ``I'm in shock.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
