<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Blasts,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Explosion At Ammunition Dump Was Sabotage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq said
today that sabotage caused an explosion at an ammunition dump that
killed at least 96 people.
   Zia also denied that the weapons in the dump were intended for
guerrillas fighting the government of neighboring Afghanistan.
   ``My personal assessment is that it couldn't be anything but a
very effective way of sabotage,'' Zia told reporters at an informal
briefing at the presidential place.
   ``Somebody who is not in line with us,'' was responsible, he
said. The president would not elaborate, citing the ongoing
investigation into Sunday's blast at the ammunition depot between
Islamabad and Rawalpindi.
   The latest death toll stands at 96, but officials said scores of
people were still missing. More than 1,000 were reported injured by
the explosion, which send rockets flying into the cities.
   Zia said the depot was used only by the army of Pakistan and
that none of the weapons was destined for the Afghan guerrillas,
who have headquarters in Pakistan. The guerrillas receive foreign
military aid, inlcuding U.S. arms, through Pakistan.
   Eyewitnesses said that after the explosion and fire, they saw
burning trucks with Afghan license plates near the dump.
   Moslem guerrillas have been at war with the Afghan government
for 10 years, since a communist coup installed a government
friendly to the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
