<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Obit-Simon     04-14 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Simon,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Omaha Mayor Bernie Simon Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Bernie Simon, who once said that
achieving the office fulfilled a lifetime dream, died today after a
yearlong battle against cancer. He was 60.
   Simon was was taken to Methodist Hospital by rescue squad before
dawn and was pronounced dead on arrival, said Anne Johnson, Simon's
press aide.
   Simon became mayor on Feb. 3, 1987, after he was chosen by the
City Council to fill out the 2{ years left in the term of Mike
Boyle, who was recalled from office in a special election.
   Simon said he had considered running for mayor in 1989 and that
achieving the office fulfilled a lifetime dream.
   A native of Omaha, Simon was an all-city tackle on the Creighton
Preparatory High School football team in 1944. After graduating in
1945, he served briefly in the U.S. Navy before the end of World
War II.
   He then went to work as a lineman for Northwestern Bell and
retired in 1981 as a marketing manager.
   Simon sought treatment for alcoholism in 1979 and said he
abstained from drinking ever since.
   A Democrat, he was elected to the City Council in 1981 and
re-elected in 1985.
   When he took over as mayor, Simon said: ``I'm not ready to sit
down in a rocking chair. It's a zest for life.''
   He was in office only two months when doctors discovered an
inoperable tumor in his lungs. That tumor was destroyed during
treatment, but two more tumors showed up in Simon's brain later in
the year.
   ``Don't look so gloomy,'' he told reporters then. ``I've whipped
cancer before and I'm going to whip this one.''
   Radiation treatments and chemotherapy reduced the tumors, but
they reappeared just before Christmas. Simon kept up a full
schedule as mayor until March, when he began taking time off to
rest.
   Acting Mayor Fred Conley was informed of Simon's death by
Simon's son, Ray.
</TEXT>
