<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Nofziger     04-14 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nofziger,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Ex-Reagan Aide Still Proclaims Innocence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House political director Lyn
Nofziger said today he felt ``a total lack of remorse'' as he
continued to claim innocence despite his recent conviction for
illegally lobbying his former government colleagues on behalf of
the scandal-ridden Wedtech Corp. and others.
   ``You have to be guilty before you can feel remorse. I do not
think I'm guilty,'' Nofziger said in an interview on ABC-TV's
``Good Morning America.''
   ``If you want me to go out and grovel in order to avoid this
kind of a sentence, I'm going to get the sentence,'' said Nofziger.
Last week he was given a 90-day prison sentence and fined $30,000
for three counts of illegally lobbying then-presidential counselor
Edwin Meese and other White House aides.
   When he was sentenced, Nofziger charged that prosecutor James C.
McKay was ``out to get'' him ``because I would not cop a plea and
because I would not say I was remorseful.''
   ``We were not allowed to plead that we had advice of counsel,''
Nofziger said today. ``We did talk to lawyers.''
   Nofziger, 63, also repeated his criticism of the ethics statute,
saying, ``We also find the law very vague. We think it's
unconstitutionally vague. It doesn't really tell you what you can
do and what you can't do.''
   Nofziger said he does think there should be some kind of ethics
law applicable to former government employees but it should not
interfere with constitutional rights. The former White House aide
charged that the current law tells you ``you can't do what the
Constitution tells you you can do.''
   Nofziger was asked whether he thought President Reagan has been
hurt by the cases of former aides being accused and convicted of
violating laws in connection with their service in his
administration. Nofziger, a longtime Reagan friend, said, ``Most of
the people who have gotten in so-called trouble, it's been after
they got out. ... I don't know why anybody should blame the
president for things that have happened to people after they left
the White House.''
</TEXT>
