<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Farrakhan-Penn     04-14 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farrakhan-Penn,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Students Cheer Farrakhan; Others Protest Campus Appearance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan urged
cheering students at the University of Pennsylvania to support
Jesse Jackson for president. Outside, other students protested
Farrakhan's on-campus lecture.
   ``Jackson is running to save a people, he is running to save the
nation,'' said Farrakhan, who endorsed the Chicago minister four
years ago and campaigned with him. Farrakhan has not been involved
in the 1988 Jackson campaign.
   ``I don't care if he (Jackson) rejects me,'' said Farrakhan who
told reporters at an earlier news conference Wednesday the
Democratic contender ``does not want my help, nor needs my
support.''
   ``America is growing up to respect men of wisdom in black
skins,'' Farrakhan told the mixed black and white crowd of 2,000,
most of whom stood and applauded. ``You should thank God Jesse
Jackson has emerged.''
   Jackson accepted Farrakhan's endorsement in 1984 and refused to
denounce some of Farrakhan's anti-white, anti-Jewish statements.
Farrakhan was quoted as praising Adolf Hitler and calling Judaism a
``gutter religion.''
   The counter-demonstration on the sidewalks outside Penn's Irvine
Auditorium attracted a crowd which police estimated at 1,000 but
which university leaders said was no more than 400.
   It preceded a memorial service held nearby commemorating the
Holocaust in which 6 million Jews were exterminated during World
War II by Hitler's Nazis.
   At the anti-Farrakhan rally, speakers denounced the Muslim
leader for what they said was his anti-Semitic, anti-white rhetoric
and called on students to denounce the remarks.
   Students held signs saying: ``Unity, Yes. Anti-Semitism, No.''
and ``Free Speech, Yes. Hatred, No.''
   ``No matter what Farrahkan says, it doesn't erase what he said
in the past,'' said Daniel Gemulka, the rally organizer and
chairman of the Council of Jewish Students. ``We must work together
as a community instead of being at odds.''
   Last week, university officials refused a Jewish group's request
to cancel the visit, saying they respected Farrakhan's right to
free speech. A letter condemning Farrakhan and signed by more than
700 students and teachers appeared in the student paper Wednesday.
   University President Sheldon Hackney defended the Farrakhan
visit, insisting that ``in an academic community, open expression
is the most fundamental value. We can't have free speech just some
of the time for some of the people.''
   Farrakhan spoke for more than two hours. He called America ``a
racist, white society.'' He claimed the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
was assassinated ``with the express consent of the U.S.
government.''
   ``How can I ask black people to fight for this country that
don't give a damn for us?'' he asked. Cheers roared from a crowd of
2,000 who had to pass through electronic metal detectors to enter
the auditorium. The university spent about $6,000 in additional
security for the lecture.
   He predicted that ``in less than 100 years blacks will equal the
number of whites in America and we won't have to ask, `Will there
be a black in the White House?'''
   He also denied he was an anti-Semite, had denigrated Judaism, or
had boasted about the greatness of Hitler, despite his negative
comments about Jews in the past and during the speech.
   It was these charges, he said, that Jews are repeating in New
York, which will hold a presidential primary next week.
   ``They are using me in New York to try to derail Jackson,''
Farrakhan said.
   Farrakhan was paid $10,000 plus travel expenses by the two
groups sponsoring the appearance: the Organization of Black
Consciousness and the predominantly white Penn Political Union.
</TEXT>
