<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WinterCost     04-14 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Winter Cost,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warm March Saves $450 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans saved $450 million on their heating
bills last month thanks to warmer-than-normal weather over most of
the nation, the government reported today.
   That means that a typical homeowner paid $88.46 to keep warm
during the month, $6.26 less than would have been expected in
normal March weather, according to figures compiled by the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
   Savings peaked in the Pacific Coast states, where the average
home heating bill of $54.28 was $9.52 below normal. The average
bill of $54.79 in the west south central states was just about
normal for the month.
   Here is a regional rundown of March heating costs for a typical
household and the comparison to costs in normal March weather.
   _Middle Atlantic: $126.98, or $8.73 below normal. Includes New
York, New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
   _New England: $114.63, or $4.88 below normal. Includes Maine,
Vermont, New Hampshire, Connecticut, Massachusetts and Rhode Island.
   _East North Central: $103.65, or $5.84 below normal. Includes
Wisconsin, Michigan, Illinois, Indiana and Ohio.
   _East South Central: $86.84, or $2.63 below normal. Includes
Kentucky, Tennessee, Mississippi and Alabama.
   _Mountain, $85.71, or $5.71 below normal. Includes Montana,
Idaho, Wyoming, Nevada, Colorado, Utah, Arizona and New Mexico.
   _West North Central: $83.02, or $9.43 below normal. Includes
North Dakota, South Dakota, Minnesota, Nebraska, Iowa, Kansas and
Missouri.
   _South Atlantic: $75.22, or $4.42 below normal. Includes
Maryland, Delaware, District of Columbia, West Virginia, Virginia,
North Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia and Florida.
   _West South Central: $54.79, normal. Includes Oklahoma,
Arkansas, Texas and Louisiana.
   _Pacific: $54.28, or $9.52 below normal. Includes Washington,
Oregon and California.
   Alaska and Hawaii are not included in the monthly weather
impacts report.
</TEXT>
