<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 4thLd-Writethru a0557 04-14 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0557,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Reported Killed, Two Wounded; Arabs Stage General Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to RECAST. Pick up 6th pvs, `Protests
broke...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians staged a general strike across the
occupied territories today to protest mass arrests of Arabs.
Hospital officials said one Arab protester was killed and two
wounded in clashes with Israeli soldiers.
   The strike, ordered by the PLO-affiliated underground
leadership, was to support 4,800 Palestinians detained by Israeli
troops since an Arab uprising was launched last December.
   Most of the 110,000 Palestinians with jobs in Israel didn't show
up for work. Arab shopowners closed their doors in the cities of
Ramallah, Nablus, Bethlehem, Hebron, Jerusalem and Gaza.
   Since Dec. 8, 144 Palestinians and two Israelis have been killed
in anti-occupation unrest in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
according to U.N. figures.
   Protests broke out today in two refugee camps in the Gaza Strip
and two cities in the West Bank, according to Arab media reports.
   Wael Hassan Asmar, 24, was shot in the heart and died at Al
Ittihad Hospital in the West Bank city of Nablus, an emergency room
official told The Associated Press.
   The two wounded were identified as 12-year-old Mohammed Fuad
Taha, who lost his right eye after being hit by a rubber bullet in
Tulkarem, and Rebhi Shihada Rehan, 17, who was in critical conditon
with a bullet wound in the stomach, said an official at Rafidiyeh
Hospital in Nablus.
   The army denied allegations that soldiers were using tear gas
improperly against Palestinians or using a particularly toxic form
of the gas.
   ``There is absolutely no truth to the report we are using a new
type of toxic gas. The Israeli army does not use any toxic gases in
dealing with Palestinian demonstrators,'' said an army spokesman,
who in keeping with regulations, spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Dr. John Hiddlestone, director of health affairs for the U.N.
Relief Works Agency, said today that Palestinians are suffering
abdominal pain, miscarriages and muscular weakness from tear gas.
He said the symptoms are not usually associated with the gas.
   The director of Israel's Government Press Office, Yoram
Ettinger, said he plans to bar Palestinians from distributing press
releases to foreign journalists in their mailboxes at the press
office.
   ``Being committed to the PLO they shouldn't expect Israel, whom
the PLO wants to destroy, to facilitate their dissemination of
information,'' Ettinger told the English-language Jerusalem Post
daily.
   Ettinger's plans were protested by the Foreign Press Association.
   On Wednesday, soldiers arrested 70 Palestinians in a raid on the
West Bank village of Salfit, whose residents had rejected Israeli
authority and set up their own government, Israeli media reported.
   Salfit, 20 miles north of Jerusalem, became a symbol of an
organized liberated town, a model of quiet civil disobedience,
Israeli media reports said, and the army feared the model would be
adopted by other communities.
   The village was headed by a committee of Communist Party members
and representatives of the Palestine Liberation Organization's
Fatah branch that had provided community services for 6,000
residents and created a system of guards, Israel Television said.
Residents were barred from painting anti-Israeli slogans or
erecting roadblocks.
   Israeli media reported as many as 70 people were arrested. The
army put the number of detainees at ``several dozen.'' The
television showed many of the men, blindfolded with white rags,
sitting on the ground on a village street.
   At the Lebanese border, troops killed three Palestinian
guerrillas who tried to enter Israel before dawn on Wednesday on a
hostage-taking mission.
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers wounded 53 Arabs in a refugee camp
with metal bullets, rubber bullets, tear gas and beatings, U.N. and
hospital officials said.
   On Wednesday, Arab activists punished Palestinian merchants
defying PLO orders to open their stores only for three hours in the
morning. The activists firebombed a money-changer's shop in east
Jerusalem and set fire to stalls at a produce market in Bethlehem,
police and witnesses said.
</TEXT>
