<1ST_LINE>u w PM-BusinessInventories     04-14 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Inventories,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Inventories Rose 0.1 Percent in February</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business inventories rose a slight 0.1 percent
in February, much slower than the pace in recent months, the
government said today.
   The Commerce Department said the gain in inventories pushed them
up by $825 million during February to a seasonally adjusted $715.9
billion. The inventory gan came as total business sales were
climbing 0.6 percent to a seasonally adjusted $468.3 billion in
February, reversing a 0.5 percent decline in January.
   The February gain in inventories held on shelves and backlots
followed a 0.7 percent gain in January. The February rise was held
back by a 1.1 percent fall in inventories held by retailers.
   This decrease reflected primarily a 5.2 percent drop in the
backlog of unsold cars.
   Analysts had worried that the rise in unsold inventories late in
1987 and in January would force production cutbacks and weak
economic growth in the early part of 1988.
   But recently economists have modified their views, contending
that the slowdown in growth in the early part of this year will not
be as severe as they had first feared.
   The 1.1 percent decline in inventories held at the retail level
was accompanied by increases of 0.9 percent in inventories held at
the wholesale level and 0.5 percent in inventories held by
manufacturers.
   The 0.6 percent overall sales rise was led by a 1.2 percent
increase in wholesale sales in February, a 0.6 percent rise in
sales by retailers and a 0.1 percent rise in sales by manufacturers.
   In an advance report on Wednesday, the government said retail
sales increased 0.8 percent in March.
   The combination of rising sales and slightly rising inventories
pushed the inventory to sales ratio down from 1.54 in January to
1.53 in February. That means it would take 1.53 months to exhaust
inventories at the February sales pace. That ratio is not
considered abnormally high.
</TEXT>
