<1ST_LINE>r w PM-InventorAward 1stLd-Writethru a0560 04-14 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inventor Award, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0560,260</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Merck in 3rd graf, The four.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The developers of a drug used to lower
cholesterol were named ``Inventors of the Year'' today by
Intellectual Property Owners Inc.
   Selected for the honor were Alfred W. Alberts, Georg
Albers-Schonberg, Richard L. Monaghan and the late Carl H. Hoffman,
who developed the drug Mevacor.
   The four were part of a research team at Merck Sharp & Dohme
Research Laboratories in Rahway, N.J., said the association, a
non-profit group which represents people who hold patents,
trademarks and copyrights.
   Mevacor, also known as lovastatin, was one of the first of a new
class of drugs approved by the Food and Drug Administration for use
in lowering cholesterol levels. High cholesterol has been
associated with heart disease.
   The Inventor of the Year Award carries a $4,000 cash prize.
   In addition, the IPO honored five other people as
``Distinguished Inventors of 1988.'' They are:
   _Elbert L. ``Burt`` Rutan of Mojave, Calif., for development of
high performance aircraft. Rutan designed the aircraft Voyager,
which circled the globe nonstop in 1986.
   _Janine Jagger of the University of Virginia Medical School for
invention of a retractable safety needle, which could help prevent
the spread of disease by eliminating the danger of medical workers
accidentally being stuck by needles.
   _Charles L. Dumoulin and Christopher J. Hardy, General Electric
researchers in Schenectady, N.Y., who developed a magnetic
resonance technique that can help physicians monitor heart patients.
   _James J. Duffy of Ford Motor Co. for a variable assist power
steering mechanism.
</TEXT>
