<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan-Pakistan 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Pakistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0564,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Foresees Trouble In Afghanistan Following Accord</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf, `When asked...' to ADD details on Pakistan's
role in talks. Pick up 6th pvs, `He said...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghan-Signing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq said
today that he foresees more bloodshed in Afghanistan because an
accord to end Soviet military involvement there does not address
the issue of a new Afghan government.
   Zia said that as long as the Kabul government remains in power
and the guerrillas fight to overthrow it, the war will continue and
an estimated 5 million Afghan refugees will not be able to return
home safely.
   ``I see trouble and turmoil in Afghanistan through the
insurgency, through the Mujahedeen trying to achieve their
objective to overthrow this regime and establish their own
authority, and that will mean more loss of life,'' Zia told
reporters at an informal news briefing.
   ``That will mean insurgency in Afghanistan will not stop unless
the Afghan Mujahedeen have achieved their end.''
   When asked why Pakistan agreed to sign the accord in Geneva
today, Zia cited the provision calling for the withdrawal of Soviet
troops backing the Kabul government. Pakistan, which borders
Afghanistan and hosts about 3 million of the 5 million Afghan
refugees, represented the rebels in the talks.
   He said the withdrawal ``made the task of the Mujahedeen less
strenuous,'' implying that it would be easier for the guerrillas to
overthrow the communist regime.
   ``Once they're (Soviets) withdrawn, the logical conclusion ...
(is) that it will be a little difficult for the present regime to
stand for a longer period,'' Zia said.
   The accord signed in Geneva does not guarantee the end of the
10-year-old war in Afghanistan, but it calls for the estimated
115,000 Soviet troops to begin leaving the country by May 15.
   It does not address the issue of an interim government to
replace the one in power now. The guerrillas have said they will
continue fighting until the government is deposed.
   In addition to Pakistan, the United States, Soviet Union and
Afghanistan signed the agreement.
   The civil war began 10 years ago after a communist coup
installed a government friendly to the Soviet Union. Red Army
troops intervened in December 1979.
</TEXT>
