<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1037EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TurnpikeExplosives 1stLd-Writethru a0533ENT 04-14 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turnpike Explosives, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0533,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Terrorism Task Force Investigates Japanese Man Linked to Red Army</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Japanese
Foreign Ministry spokesman, also CORRECTS man's age to 35, sted 25.
Picks up in 3rd graf, `Kyodo news ... Hearing scheduled for 1:30
p.m. EDT. No PMs lead expected</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A terrorism task force is investigating
a Japanese national arrested on the New Jersey Turnpike with three
homemade bombs, each powerful enough to destroy a building,
authorities said.
   The suspect was identified by Tokyo police today as Yu Kikumura,
35, a former bookstore owner who was extradited to Japan by the
Netherlands two years ago on charges of illegal possession of
explosives.
   In Tokyo, acting Foreign Ministry spokesman Koichi Haraguchi
said the National Police Agency ``has a strong suspicion that he
(Kikumura) might have a relationship with the Japan Red Army,'' a
terrorist group that gained notoriety for a series of attacks
abroad in the 1970s.
   However, Japanese police ``haven't made a final conclusion that
he is a member of the Red Army,'' Haraguchi told a news conference.
   Kyodo news service in Tokyo said Kikumura's arrest had raised
suspicions the Red Army might be planning attacks during the summit
of leaders of advanced industrial nations June 19 in Toronto,
Canada.
   The task force was formed by state police and FBI agents in
response to concerns about the sophistication of the bombs found in
the suspect's car, and ``inquiries from overseas,'' state police
Superintendent Clinton Pagano said at a news conference Wednesday.
   ``The material was loaded and charged and ready to use,'' Pagano
said. ``It was intended to injure people.''
   Kikumura was arrested Tuesday at a Turnpike rest stop after a
state trooper noticed him acting oddly, stopped his car and found
explosive devices and three homemade bombs resembling fire
extinguishers in his car.
   The suspect was carrying a stolen Japanese passport and
international driver's license. The man named on the passport and
license, Masatoshi Kishizono, had reported his passport was
missing, Pagano said.
   Kikumura was charged with possession of explosive devices and
possession of explosives. State police experts who defused the
bombs say each of the devices contained enough power to destroy a
building.
   A bail hearing was scheduled this afternoon in Superior Court
for the suspect, who was being held at the Bergen County Jail.
   Pagano and John C. McGinley, special agent in charge of the
FBI's Newark office, told the news conference they would not
speculate on where the suspect was headed or what he planned to do
with the bombs.
   During a hearing Wednesday, Bergen County Assistant Prosecutor
Paula Dumas told Judge Charles R. DiGisi that authorities were
unable to identify the suspect.
   The address he had given U.S. immigration officials upon
entering the country May 8, 1987, turned out to be that of an
unoccupied New York City apartment, police said.
   Also, the man had indicated he did not understand questions
posed in English, although he had spoken in clear English to the
trooper who arrested him, Ms. Dumas said.
   Japanese police said Kikumura, a dropout of Tokyo University of
Foreign Studies, was deported to Tokyo by the Netherlands in August
1986, three months after police at a local airport found 2.2 pounds
of dynamite in his luggage.
   He was acquitted of the Dutch charges in a Japanese court later
in 1986 and dropped out of sight, police said.
   The Japanese police spokesman refused comment on news reports
that authorities believed Kikumura established links to the Red
Army, a Japanese terrorist group, in 1974 when he ran a bookshop in
Athens, Greece.
   The Red Army was a radical splinter faction of the leftist
General Federation of Japanese Students, which claimed support from
850,000 of the nation's 1.3 million college students in the 1960s.
   After gaining notoriety from a series of terrorist activities
abroad in the 1970s, including the attack on Israel's Ben-Gurion
International Airport in which 28 people were killed, the Red Army
has been relatively silent in recent years.
</TEXT>
