<1ST_LINE>r a PM-`Colors'Protest     04-14 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-`Colors' Protest,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Colors' Director, Producer Defend Gang Film As Protest Mounts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Director Dennis Hopper defended his new film
``Colors,'' a gritty street-gang drama, as a story told from a
police viewpoint, while a downtown theater scratched the movie for
fear it would spark violence.
   The film, scheduled for release Friday, used active Los Angeles
gang members as extras and advisers as well as the actual
identifying colors of blue for the Crips and red for the Bloods
gangs.
   ``Colors'' has drawn criticism from police, city officials and
community leaders who claim it glorifies the violent youth gangs
that have been plaguing the city.
   Outside a private, celebrity screening Wednesday night, 10
Guardian Angels chanted ``Don't Show `Colors''' while Hopper
defended the film starring Sean Penn and Robert Duvall as
gang-fighting police officers.
   The Guardian Angels claims that ``Colors'' glamorizes the
street-gang lifestyle and wants distribution of the film halted or
some of its proceeds donated to community organizations that combat
gang violence.
   ``There is nothing in this film that glorifies being in a
gang,'' Hopper said, adding that the film is told from a police
viewpoint. ``I don't know how people can twist it around and say
I'm glorifying gangs.''
   At the celebrity screening, the movie's producer, Robert H.
Solo, called the protests misguided.
   ``I think the people who are making those predictions are
whipping up the probability and the possibility,'' of violence, the
producer said. ``The people who are saying blood is going to flow
in the streets are asking for blood to flow in the streets. I think
it's very irresponsible behavior.''
   Attending the VIP screening were Best Actress Oscar-winner Cher,
and last year's winner Marlee Matlin, Richard Dean Anderson of
ABC-TV's ``McGyver,'' U-2's Bono Hewson and actor-director Emilio
Estevez.
   The downtown Laemmle Grand, adjoining the posh Sheraton Grand
Hotel, decided not to show the film because its staff feared a
reaction from nearby gangs.
   ``The staff at the theater were in a panic because the home turf
of one of the gangs in the movie is just a couple of miles from
downtown,'' said Bob Laemmle, co-owner of the theater chain.
   About 70 theaters in the Los Angeles area plan to show the movie.
   The Beverly Hills-Hollywood chapter of the National Assocition
for the Advancement of Colored People joined police and city
leaders who objected to the film premiering in Los Angeles during a
period of heightened public concern about gang violence.
   More than 85 people have been killed so far this year in
gang-related violence in Los Angeles County. Last year, there were
387 gang-related killings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
