<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Aquino 2ndLd-Writethru a0519 04-14 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Aquino, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0519,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Arrives in Beijing After Visit to Ancestral City</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with arrival in Beijing, details
Mrs. Aquino's Chinese ancestry. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONGJIAN, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino of
the Philippines today burned incense at her ancestral temple and
bowed three times in front of her ancestral tablets.
   Mrs. Aquino, making her first trip abroad since going to Japan
in November 1986, left behind a nation on full military alert amid
concerns of a coup attempt during her absence.
   Later, on the first day of a three-day trip to China, Mrs.
Aquino traveled to Beijing.
   Presidential spokesman Teodoro Benigno said everyone on the
presidential plane was very upbeat and there was no talk of dangers
posed by the escape of former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo'' Honasan,
leader of a bloody coup last Aug. 28.
   ``Mr. Honasan has lost all capability of mounting any serious
threat on the government,'' Benigno said. ``If there was any
question about that, then the president would have wavered in her
decision to come to China, but not for one minute did she waver in
her plans.''
   Manila was quiet today with no signs of trouble.
   The president, accompanied by seven Cabinet ministers, was
greeted in Beijing by Vice Foreign Minister Liu Shuqing and taken
to the Diaoyutai state guest house where she will stay during her
three-day visit to China. Three of her four daughters also are
making the trip.
   On Friday, Mrs. Aquino will be officially welcomed by new
President Yang Shangkun outside the Great Hall of the People and
will hold talks with Premier Li Peng. She is also to sign a trade
protocol and a science and technology agreement.
   China stopped supporting communist rebels in the Philippines
after Beijing and Manila established full diplomatic relations in
the mid-1970s. Mrs. Aquino is the first Philippines leader to visit
China since Ferdinand Marcos in 1975.
   The high point of Mrs. Aquino's first day in China was a visit
to Hongjian, a village of 2,800 in coastal Fujian province that was
home to her maternal great-grandfather, Xu Yuhuan. Xu settled in
the Philippines in 1861 and changed his name to Cojuangco, Mrs.
Aquino's maiden name.
   More than half the residents of Hongjian are surnamed Xu.
   Mrs. Aquino and her entourage left for the one-hour drive to
Hongjian immediately after arriving by special flight in Xiamen.
Crowds lined the roads passing through fertile, terraced farmland.
   At Hongjian, residents waved yellow banners and Chinese and
Philippine flags, and set off firecrackers while a school band
played.
   At the Xu family ancestral temple, which had been restored and
painted for the visit, Mrs. Aquino burned incense and bowed three
times before memorial tablets.
   ``I came to China for reasons of state and for reasons personal
to me, for I am both head of state of my country and a daughter of
this village.'' she said in English.
   She ended the speech by saying in Chinese, ``I and my daughters
and my colleagues again thank you for your welcome, which we will
never forget.'
   Mrs. Aquino visited a kindergarten, where she gave yellow ``Cory
Aquino'' t-shirts to the children and looked at family photos in
the home of an uncle, Xu Yuanxiang.
   Some villagers expressed regret that her one-hour visit was so
brief. Her contacts with the 49 relatives was limited mainly to
handshakes just before her departure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
