<DOCNO> AP880414-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Farrakhan-Jackson     04-14 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farrakhan-Jackson,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Cheer Farrakhan's Jackson Endorsement; Others Protest
Appearance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan urged
cheering students at the University of Pennsylvania to support
Jesse Jackson for president. But others outside protested
Farrakhan's on-campus lecture.
   ``Jackson is running to save a people; he is running to save the
nation,'' Farrakhan said Wednesday night.
   He campaigned with Jackson four years ago, but became a focus of
controversy for what were widely considered anti-Jewish statements.
He has been quoted as calling Adolf Hitler a great man and Judaism
``a gutter religion.''
   Jackson has distanced himself from his former ally since then.
   ``I don't care if he rejects me,'' said Farrakhan who told
reporters at an earlier news conference Wednesday the Democratic
contender ``does not want my help, nor need my support.''
   ``America is growing up to respect men of wisdom in black
skins,'' Farrakhan told the mixed black and white crowd of 2,000,
most of whom stood and applauded. ``You should thank God Jesse
Jackson has emerged.''
   He denied he was an anti-Semite, had denigrated Judaism, or had
boasted about the greatness of Hitler. He said Jews are repeating
those charges in New York, which has its presidential primary next
Tuesday.
   ``They are using me in New York to try to derail Jackson,''
Farrakhan said.
   A counter-demonstration on the sidewalks outside the
university's Irvine Auditorium attracted a crowd which police
estimated at 1,000 but which university leaders said was about 400.
   Speakers at the rally denounced Farrakhan for what they said was
his anti-Semitic, anti-white rhetoric. Students held signs saying:
``Unity, Yes. Anti-Semitism, No'' and ``Free Speech, Yes. Hatred,
No.''
   University President Sheldon Hackney defended the Farrakhan
visit, saying that ``in an academic community, open expression is
the most fundamental value. We can't have free speech just some of
the time for some of the people.''
   Farrakhan, in a speech lasting more than two hours, called
America ``a racist, white society.'' He contended the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. was assassinated ``with the express consent of the
U.S. government.''
   ``How can I ask black people to fight for this country that
don't give a damn for us?'' he asked. The crowd cheered.
   He predicted that ``in less than 100 years blacks will equal the
number of whites in America and we won't have to ask, `Will there
be a black in the White House?'''
</TEXT>
