<HEAD>Republicans Launch Offensive Against Income-Tax Increases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of House Republicans today used the
approaching tax-filing deadline as the occasion to launch an
offensive aimed at blocking income-tax increases and requiring a
balanced budget.
   ``The Democratic leadership of the House is systematically
denying the American people a vote on the balanced-budget
amendment'' to the Constitution, Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., told a
news conference.
   He and several GOP colleagues joined representatives of several
lobbying groups to press for support for:
   _A promise to oppose increases in tax rates or any further cuts
in deductions unless accompanied by rate reductions. Seventy-eight
House Republicans have signed the vow.
   _A petition that would force the Judiciary Committee to allow a
vote on a measure that eventually could amend the Constitution to
prohibit the government from spending more than it takes in. Rep.
Larry Craig, R-Idaho, a sponsor of the proposal, said the petition
has 190 of the required 218 signatures.
   _A ``taxpayer bill of rights'' requiring the Internal Revenue
Service to give 30-day notice before seizing property. The
legislation, recently approved by the Senate Finance Committee,
also seeks to protect taxpayers in other ways in dealing with the
IRS.
   _A bill by Rep. Joe DioGuardi, R-N.Y., that would require the
IRS to send taxpayers an annual statement indicating their
``share'' of federal spending and debt.
   The Republican efforts were endorsed by the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, National Taxpayers Union, Citizens for a Sound Economy,
and Free the Eagle, a conservative lobbying organization.
</TEXT>
