<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Murdering Son 25 Years Ago</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with father charged in slaying. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BATLEY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today charged a 50-year-old man
with murdering his young son, who vanished 25 years ago but whose
remains weren't discovered until last week.
   William Leonard Jennings sobbed loudly as he appeared in a
magistrates court in West Yorkshire and was charged with killing
his 3-year-old son, Stephen, who was last seen alive on Dec. 12,
1962.
   Jennings, handcuffed to a plainclothes policeman, wept
throughout the 70-minute court hearing. The judge denied bail and
ordered him to remain in custody until another court appearance
next week.
   Police arrested Jennings on Wednesday after a dog found
Stephen's skull and bones under a stone near a footpath less than a
half a mile from the boy's home.
   Forensic scientists confirmed the bones were Stephen's but have
not disclosed the cause of death.
   Stephen disappeared after setting off on a cold winter morning
from his home in Little Gomersal, near Bradford in northern
England, to follow his 4-year-old brother, Paul, who was visiting
an aunt.
   Despite a massive search, police found no clues to the boy's
disappearance until the bones turned up.
</TEXT>
