<HEAD>Heckling Fans Disrupt Performance At La Scala Opera House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opera fans apparently angered by the
withdrawal of star tenor Luciano Pavarotti disrupted La Scala's
season premiere of ``Elisir d'Amore'' with whistles and shouts at
some of the principals.
   Most of Wednesday night's heckling was aimed at Welsh singer
Marie McLaughlin and Syrian-born Italian director Andree Ruth
Shammah.
   One fan shouted ``You are an amateur!'' at McLaughlin, and a
deluge of whistles and shouts of ``Buffoon!'' greeted Shammah when
she appeared on stage at the end of the performance. Milan's daily
newspaper Corriere della Sera called her direction
``untraditional.''
   Conductor Giuseppe Patane also got his share of heckling.
Differences between Pavarotti and the conductor reportedly erupted
during rehearsals last week but La Scala officials said Pavarotti
dropped out because of a cold.
   Pavarotti's substitute, Vincenzo La Scola, received tepid
applause.
   ``He worked hard to make up for the absence of Pavarotti but his
personal success did not save the performance,'' Corriere della
Sera said.
</TEXT>
