<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--RottenEggs     04-14 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Rotten Eggs,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paris Reeks Of Rotten Eggs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   April in Paris is supposed to smell of blossoms and
perfume, but for residents in some neighborhoods, it reeked of
rotten eggs.
   Fire department officials said Thursday that for the second time
in a week, they had received telephone calls inquiring into the
source of the unpleasant odor that greeted them when they woke up
Wednesday.
   Officials said they did not know where the smell was coming
from, but that it posed no health hazard.
   The stench permeated three southern Paris neighborhoods and
suburban areas.
   ``People start to worry when they leave their own neighborhoods
and find the same awful smell in other parts of the city,'' said
the official, who declined to be identified in keeping with
departmental policy.
   The spokesman said the fire department had received about a
dozen complaints. He said pollution levels were normal and that
there was no evidence a toxic substance had leaked over the city.
   ``No industrial facilities warned of spills,'' he said.
   The smells could not be identified, he said, because ``smells
are very subjective and different people smelled different things.''
</TEXT>
