<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chernobyl-Crops     04-14 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chernobyl-Crops,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ukrainian Crop Yields Increase, Despite Chernobyl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop yields in the Soviet Ukraine have increased
despite the Chernobyl nuclear accident two years ago, Tass reported
Thursday.
   The official news agency said the April 26, 1986, disaster
caused no ``irreparable damage'' to the region's agriculture.
Chernobyl is about 80 miles north of the Ukrainian capital of Kiev.
   In the seven months after a blast and fire split open one of
Chernobyl's reactors, 31 people died. Thousands were exposed to
dangerous levels of radiation.
   There were concerns that the agriculture of the Ukraine,
traditionally one of the breadbasket regions of the Soviet Union,
might suffer from the release of radiation.
   Tass quoted Alexei Denisenko, deputy chairman of the state
agro-industrial committee of the Ukraine, as saying all farm
products within the Chernobyl area are checked for radiation and
pronounced safe before they are sold.
   He said grain yields per hectare in the Kiev region, which
includes Chernobyl, were up by 31 percent in 1987 as compared with
the previous year. Such increases are not believed linked to
mutations in plants that might be caused by radiation, he said.
   ``Crop rises are attributed only to introduction of intensive
technologies of cultivation, as well as to intrduction of contract
forms of labor organization,'' Denisenko told Tass.
   Denisenko said the type of crops grown at some farms were
switched on the recommendation of scientists. For instance, farms
which had been growing vegetables now are planted in grain and
potatoes which do not accumulate radioactive decay products, Tass
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
