<2ND_LINE>PM-Escapee Recaptured, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0554,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Escaped Murderer Recaptured in Ohio; Second Escapee Sighted in W.
Va.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with details of arrest; second escapee
sighted, runs away from police in W.Va. Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DALE LEACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An escaped murderer who had vowed revenge
on the people who helped imprison him was recaptured today, a
week-and-a-half after he and two other killers fled the West
Virginia State Penitentiary.
   Meanwhile, deputies in Marshall County, W.Va., were chasing one
of the other two escapees, who ran away when police checked his
identification at a routine traffic stop this morning.
   Robert Dean Stacy, 35, was arrested this morning at the
apartment of a friend, where he was hiding in a closet, the FBI
said.
   Stacy was unarmed and no weapons were found in the apartment
when police and FBI agents searched the apartment of James Kennedy
shortly before 8 a.m. Kennedy was taken into custody for
questioning, the FBI said.
   Stacy had been convicted of killing a Huntington, W.Va., police
officer and accused of shooting a Huber Heights officer and had
vowed revenge on those who had helped convict him, officials said.
   Police had assigned protection to the judge and prosecutor in
his case and a Columbus woman who testified against Stacy.
   A federal court magistrate ordered Stacy returned to West
Virginia to face a charge of unlawful flight to avoid prosecution _
a charge that stems from the April 3 escape of the three men from
the 122-year-old penitentiary.
   In Marshall County, W.Va., today, Tommie Mollohan, 45, one of
the other two men who escaped with Stacy, ran away after deputies
pulled him over.
   Mollohan, said Marshall County sheriff's dispatcher Lynell
Kearans, gave deputies his correct last name, Social Security
number and date of birth, but added a fictitious first name. He
fled when the deputy radioed headquarters for confirmation of the
information, she said.
   ``He ran down over the hill, and we're in the process of a
manhunt right now,'' Ms. Kearans said. Authorities found a shotgun
and shells in the car, as well as .22-caliber ammunition with no
corresponding weapon, and said they assume Mollohan is armed.
   Mollohan was convicted of robbing and then killing a grocer in
1973. At the time, Mollohan had escaped from a Florida prison and
also was wanted in Georgia and North Carolina on armed robbery
charges.
   The third escapee is David Williams, 28. He was convicted of
felony murder, arson and robbery in the December 1980 slaying of a
Marytown, W.Va., resident who was found bludgeoned in the rubble of
his burned home.
   All three men were serving life terms. Numerous sightings of the
escapees have been reported since the three used stolen bolt
cutters to escape from the prison at Moundsville, W.Va.
</TEXT>
