<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--HongKong-TV     04-14 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Hong Kong-TV,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov't Fines TV Station For Drama Series With `Excessive Violence'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hong Kong television station was fined the
equivalent of $2,500 Thursday for showing a TV series that
contained what the government called ``excessive violence.''
   It was the first such fine imposed by the Broadcasting Authority.
   The drama series ``The Final Verdict'' on Hong Kong Television
Broadcasts Ltd. depicted ``the brutal killing of a family of six''
that had ``contravened the codes of practice relating to program
standards,'' the authority said. The statement did not elaborate.
   It said the authority had received 97 complaints about the show,
including many that claimed the Cantonese-language series portrayed
the police force in a bad light. The series was in part about
police corruption.
   ``The Broadcasting Authority, while taking the view that proper
regard should be given to the needs of creative work in drama
productions, was of the opinion that the approach adopted in the
series could have been more balanced,'' the statement said.
   The TV station said it had been verbally informed of the
authority's decision and was awaiting further details.
</TEXT>
