<HEAD>Egyptian Relief Supplies to Palestinians</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt said Thursday it will send more than
150 tons of relief supplies to Palestinian victims of Israeli
security operations in the occupied West Bank and Gaza.
   Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif announced the decision
after a meeting President Hosni Mubarak had with some of his
Cabinet ministers.
   Mubarak later flew to Jordan's capital Amman for a two-day visit
and talks with King Hussein on U.S.-sponsored Middle East peace
efforts.
   El-Sherif told reporters the Red Crescent Society, which is
Egypt's equivalent of the Red Cross, will send 159 tons of food and
medical supplies ``as assistance to victims of the uprising'' in
the West Bank and Gaza.
   ``Contacts are in progress on how the supplies can be
delivered,'' he added, apparently referring to an Egyptian approach
to Israel.
   El-Sherif also said without elaboration that Mubarak and his
ministers ``discussed ways of supporting the uprising politically.''
   Egypt and Israel signed a peace treaty in 1979 and established
diplomatic relations at ambassadorial level.
   Cairo has condemned repeatedly what it terms Israel's
``repressive measures'' to quell the 4-month-old Palestinian
uprising.
   Mubarak has said the uprising should continue so as to spur
efforts for an overall peaceful settlement of the 40-year-old
conflict between Israel and the Arabs.
