<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hijack-Funeral     04-14 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack-Funeral,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kuwaitis Bury Hijack Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KUW4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trumpets blared and thousands of mourners shouted
``God is great!'' as this tiny country on Thursday buried two
people slain on a hijacked Kuwaiti jetliner and vowed it would not
meet the sky pirates' demands.
   ``Kuwait will never give in to blackmail, simple as that,'' said
Faisal al-Marzouk, chief editor of Al-Anbaa newspaper and one of
nearly 2,000 people attending the funeral.
   ``Even if they kill all the hostages there on the plane, we'll
never, ever release the killers who are here in Kuwait,'' he added,
referring to the hijackers' demand for the freedom of 17 convicted
terrorists.
   A military honor guard escorted the flag-draped bodies of Khalid
Ayyub Bandar, 20, and Abdullah Shibib al-Khalidi, 24, into the
ghost-like sea of mourners in traditional white Arab robes and
headdresses.
   Hundreds of men stretched out hands to touch the biers as
relatives carrying the bodies forced a weaving path through the
throng to reach the graves dug in sandy soil.
   Traditional Moslem chants of ``Allahu Akbar!'' (``God is
great!'') and ``La Illah Illa Allah!'' (``There is no God but
God!'') resounded across the cemetery as tightly packed mourners
passed stones over their heads to reach those at graveside who were
covering the bodies.
   The crown prince, Sheik Saad Abdullah Al-Sabah, led the
procession of mourners along a condolence line of more than 60 male
relatives of the slain men.
   Many kissed the prince, who has three distant relatives still
aboard the Kuwait Airways Boeing 747 that was seized April 5 on a
flight from Bangkok to Kuwait and flown to Iran, Cyprus and now
Algiers.
   All of those interviewed said they supported the government's
refusal to grant the hijackers' demands, and some blamed Iran for
the jet's seizure.
   ``Everybody agrees on one point, that we should not give in ...
no matter what the sacrifices,'' said Abdullah al-Saleh, a
businessman.
   ``I think if we get the hijackers we should kill them, one after
the other, so there'll be no one to do such a thing again,'' said
Ghassahn al-Kunaini, a mechanical engineer. ``I do not accept
anything, no deals.''
   He denounced the hijackers' claims to be acting for Islam.
``These people, they know nothing about Islam,'' Kunaini said.
   Marzouk said ``Kuwait has set an example that you never, ever
negotiate with terrorists.
   ``I think its unfortunate that the United States, Germany,
France, they have always wanted to negotiate for the release of the
hostages in Lebanon,'' he added. ``Once you give in to blackmail
once, you always give in to blackmail.''
   Kuwait has repeatedly refused to consider freeing the 17 Islamic
radicals, who were imprisoned for a series of bombings.
   On Wednesday, the defense minister, Sheik Nawaf al-Ahmad
Al-Sabah said ``Kuwait would not cave in, and would not change its
attitude toward blackmail.''
   The radical Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Watan said Thursday the
hijackers in Algiers were demanding that Kuwait commute the death
penalty for three convicts condemned to death who are among the 17.
Al-Watan did not give sources for its story.
</TEXT>
