<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Hope     04-14 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Hope,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comedian's Daughter-in-Law Due Judge's Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will nominate Washington
attorney Judith Richards Hope, daughter-in-law of entertainer Bob
Hope, to succeed Robert H. Bork on the U.S. Court of Appeals here,
the White House announced today.
   Mrs. Hope, who had reportedly turned down the offer once but
changed her mind after a call from Reagan, is a partner in the
Washington office of Paul, Hastings, Janofsky & Walker.
   Mrs. Hope 47, was national co-chairman of Lawyers for
Reagan-Bush in 1984 and general counsel to the presidential
campaign of Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan.
   From 1975 to 1977, she was an associate director in the domestic
policy office of the White House. She is a former deputy director
of the California Rural Development Corp.
   The nomination must be confirmed by the Senate.
   Mrs. Hope and her husband, Anthony, also a lawyer, have two
children.
   The appeals court here is considered among the most important
federal appeals courts because it handles disputes over
governmental regulations and programs. Judges are appointed for
life and now draw an annual salary of $95,000.
   Bork resigned from the bench in February, four months after his
nomination to the Supreme Court was defeated by the Senate in a
bitter fight.
</TEXT>
