<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HealthInsurance     04-14 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Insurance,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uninsured Workers Tell Hard-Luck Stories To House Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uninsured workers with medical problems told
their hard-luck stories Thursday to a House panel weighing a
sweeping plan to require that employers offer minimum health
benefits.
   The employees _ including a a grocery store clerk from
Philadelphia and a doctors' office receptionist from Denver _ said
they have had to cope with inadequate medical care, unaffordable
bills or both.
   Annette Lopez, the receptionist, said the federal Medicaid
program paid for her daughter Colleen's two-month stay in the
hospital after she was born prematurely. But she said five
subsequent hospital stays have cost $22,000 _ and there's no one to
pay it but herself and her husband on their wages of $6 an hour
each.
   ``Even if I paid $100 every month, she'd be in college if not
out of college by the time we ended up paying this bill,'' said
Mrs. Lopez.
   Daniel Casey, the clerk, said his parents were uninsured, had
diabetes and died in their 30s for lack of proper medical care. He
said he has diabetes and no insurance, and must depend on clinics
with spotty care and no evening hours.
   ``If I get sick I must choose between working and supporting my
family or going to the doctor and losing a day's pay,'' said Casey.
``If my employer had a mandatory insurance program, I could go to a
regular pharmacy and see a doctor in the evening.''
   The testimony came at a hearing before the House Energy and
Commerce subcommittee on health and the environment.
   There are an estimated 37.2 million Americans without health
insurance. About two-thirds of them are workers or dependents who
would be covered by the plan under consideration by Congress.
   The bill, introduced by Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and Rep.
Henry Waxman, D-Calif., would require employers to provide a
minimum package of health insurance to people working 17.5 hours a
week or more. Benefits would have to include hospital and doctor
care, prenatal and well-baby care, diagnostic testing and
catastrophic protection.
   Employers would pay at least 80 percent of the premium. Pool
arrangements and a phase-in period would make plans more affordable
to small or new firms. The Senate version of the bill, already
approved by Kennedy's Labor and Human Resources Committee, also
says very small or new employers would only have to provide
catastrophic protection.
   The business community is divided on the plan. Many firms say
they are philosophically opposed to mandated benefits, but
corporations with health plans complain they are indirectly footing
the bill for firms without them.
   The Washington Business Group on Health, representing hundreds
of Fortune 500 companies and other employers, said in a statement
Thursday that ``with each month, we hear from more members who
think that a federal mandate is far from the worst alternative.
And, many of the changes we wanted have been accepted.''
   Willis Goldbeck, president of the group, said the Kennedy-Waxman
bill ``clearly does not have the support of the business
community'' but said there is ``considerable strength to the
growing trend of acceptance among many major companies.''
   John Lester, owner of a small carpentry and construction
business in Warren, N.H., said the bill would help small companies
like his. He said he offers health insurance as an ethical
obligation but its high cost keeps him from expanding.
   Furthermore, Lester said, ``in my attempts to be responsible now
and in the future, I am put at a competitive disadvantage against
those (employers) who do not insure.''
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce is a prime opponent of the
Kennedy-Waxman bill and said Thursday it would cause many workers
to lose other benefits and maybe even their jobs.
   The group is proposing alternatives it says would encourage
rather than require employers to offer coverage. Among them:
eliminating state minimum benefit requirements and allowing
unincorporated businesses the same tax deductions enjoyed by
incorporated firms.
   The state of Hawaii has a law similar to the Kennedy-Waxman
bill. The Massachusetts legislature on Wednesday passed an even
more sweeping measure that guarantees health coverage to everyone,
not just people with jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880414-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0609 04-14 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0609,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Widens Nuclear-Policy Dispute With Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS new poll results in grafs 9-10, Dukakis had</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Gore Jr. widened his nuclear-policy dispute with rival
Michael Dukakis today, saying the Massachusetts governor and his
staff misstated U.S. and NATO positions on the subject. Meanwhile,
a new poll showed Dukakis leading Jesse Jackson in New York, with
Gore far behind both men.
   With less than a week to go before the big New York primary,
with 255 delegates at stake, Gore, in an attempt to get back in the
race, has vigorously attacked Dukakis on the nuclear issue. Dukakis
and his campaign aides have said Gore's charges are simply wrong,
the efforts of a desperate candidate.
   The latest controversy began Wednesday when Gore said Dukakis
erred in an interview in the New York Daily News by saying he would
consider first use of strategic nuclear weapons in case of a Soviet
conventional attack in Europe.
   Gore denounced that Wednesday as ``a major blunder'' but Dukakis
strongly denied that it was. Dukakis said he had merely reflected
existing American and NATO policy in holding open the option of a
nuclear response to a successful Soviet invasion of Western Europe
with conventional forces.
   In a speech today to the American Society of Newspaper Editors,
Gore said Dukakis' staff compounded the first mistake by misstating
NATO policy about using nuclear weapons.
   ``To say NATO policy is `no early first use' is another error.
... We have not adopted that policy. NATO has not adopted that
policy,'' Gore told the newspaper editors.
   ``Governor Dukakis and his campaign spokesman apparently don't
know that,'' Gore said at a news conference following the speech.
   The new poll released today indicated Jackson was gaining
support in New York but that Dukakis was maintaining his own
strength. Gore apparently had not picked up ground despite his
vigorous campaigning.
   Dukakis had the support of 46 percent of 359 registered
Democrats surveyed Monday and Tuesday by the Marist College
Institute for Public Opinion, followed by Jackson with 34 percent,
Gore with 7 percent and ``uncommitted'' with 5 percent. Eight
percent of those polled were undecided.
   A previous Marist poll, conducted April 5-6, showed Dukakis with
47 percent, Jackson 31 percent and Gore with 6 percent. Eight
percent were uncommitted and 6 percent undecided. The polls' margin
of sampling error was plus or minus 5 percentage points.
   On Wednesday, Jackson appeared in Albany, N.Y., with Gov. Mario
Cuomo. Cuomo called Jackson a ``singularly important Democrat,''
and Jackson thanked Cuomo for holding off on any endorsements until
after the primary season June 7.
   ``Gov. Cuomo, just keep a freeze on all endorsements and keep
extending your support,'' Jackson said.
   Jackson continued to be plagued, however, by hostility from the
Jewish community _ and from President Reagan, who said politicians
have withheld their criticism of Jackson for fear of being called
racist.
   Reagan has rarely singled out any of the Democratic candidates
for criticism. But he told the American Society of Newspaper
Editors in Washington: ``I have to believe that a great many of us
would find ourselves in great disagreement with the policies that
he is proposing, and would perhaps be more vocal about them, if it
wasn't for concern that that'd be misinterpreted into some kind of
a racial attack.''
   Republican George Bush called during the final day of a
three-day swing in New York for mandatory death penalties for
certain drug-related crimes, reflecting the prominence of the drug
issue in this year's campaign.
   ``And, frankly, I'd like to find a way to make this penalty
swift,'' he said in a breakfast speech to the Association for a
Better New York.
   Gore stirred the new foreign policy controversy after Dukakis
told the Daily News ``we reserve the right to use nuclear force''
in the event of a Soviet invasion of Europe ``when there appears to
be no other alternative.'' He added, ``I don't think that's going
to happen.''
   Gore, battling for survival, quickly jumped on the Massachusetts
governor and said he had ``made a significant mistake in saying
that he would launch a nuclear strike against the Soviet Union
under ... specific circumstances.''
   At a news conference in Boston, Dukakis said Gore ``ought to get
his facts straight.''
   ``The policy I advocated has been the policy of the government
of the United States for many, many years,'' he said. ``It's the
policy of the NATO alliance.''
   At an appearance Wednesday night before Westchester County,
N.Y., Democrats, Gore said the transcript of the interview showed
Dukakis had been asked whether he could conceive of the first use
of ``strategic'' weapons
   ``NATO has purposely refused to respond to that hypothetical,''
Gore said. ``The president of the United States has traditionally
refused to respond to that hypothetical.''
   James Steinberg, defense and foreign policy adviser to Dukakis,
said Dukakis started answering the question thinking he was being
asked about tactical nuclear weapons and that after Dukakis started
speaking the questioner made reference to ``strategic.''
   The transcript shows a comma before the phrase ``as a strategic
weapon?''
   Steinberg said he assumed Dukakis would have given a different
answer had he understood the question to be about strategic nuclear
weapons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
