<HEAD>U.S. to Meet with Soviets over Food Aid to Ethiopa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will consult with the Soviet
Union on problems of getting food to the more than 2 million people
threatened with starvation in northern Ethiopia, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said today.
   Fitzwater said he did not know the exact forum for the
discussions, but that Secretary of State George Shultz ``may raise
it'' during his meeting today in Geneva with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze, or at their meetings in Moscow next
week.
   The spokesman said the discussions would focus on ``helping to
bring pressure on the government of Ethiopia to allow food aid to
resume for the starving people of Tigray and Eritrea.''
   ``There are more than 2 million people at risk in that part of
the country. ... You recall the government of Ethiopia has ordered
relief workers out of the region and we are very concerned about
not being able to provide food supplies'' to the people, Fitzwater
said.
   On Thursday, the State Department called the Marxist
government's shutdown of international relief operations in
northern Ethiopia ``a human catastrophe.''
   The area has seen intense fighting between separatist rebels
battling Ethiopian leader Lt. Col. Mengistu Haile Mariam's rule and
loyalist troops.
