<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionLawsuit 1stLd-Writethru a0495 04-14 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Lawsuit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0495,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Goes Ahead With Abortion Despite Court Order</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf, `Their notice ...,' with
Supreme Court spokeswoman saying case will have to go through
normal appeals process.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman underwent an abortion in defiance of
a court order obtained by the would-be father, but attorneys for
both sides still want the state Supreme Court to settle the dispute.
   At issue is whether a woman has the sole authority to decide to
have an abortion or if a father has rights that give him a say in
the decision.
   Attorneys for the 18-year-old Terre Haute woman told the high
court Wednesday that she had terminated her first-trimester
pregnancy, but said the decision was hers alone.
   Their notice came a day after they asked the high court for an
immediate review of the lower court injunction that prohibited an
abortion.
   A spokesman for the Supreme Court said today that the case will
go through the normal appeals process because speed is no longer
essential.
   ``The case will go through the Indiana Court of Appeals since it
is not an emergency any more,'' said the spokeswoman. ``It probably
will get back to us eventually. But there is no emergency now, and
it has to go through the channels.''
   A 61-page brief by the man's attorney, James Bopp Jr., said the
woman's reasons for wanting an abortion are ``an immature reasoning
process, are insubstantial and border on the frivolous, and do not
outweigh the strong interests of the father in seeing the child
born and in his custody.''
   Bopp described the woman as an unemployed high school dropout
who began a relationship with the man, a delivery truck driver in
Terre Haute, following a date on New Year's Eve.
   The lower court ruling cited testimony that the woman wanted an
abortion to preserve her figure so she would look good in a bathing
suit and to avoid being pregnant during the summer, Bopp said.
   The woman's attorneys refused to say where or when the abortion
was performed.
   ``Faced with the decision of continuing with an unwanted
pregnancy and with violating a court order, she made the decision
she felt was right,'' said the notice signed by her attorney,
Richard A. Waples, legal director of the Indiana Civil Liberties
Union.
   ``She did what she had to do to protect both her physical and
emotional health,'' it said.
   Bopp, general counsel for the national Right to Life
organization, said Wednesday he thinks ``somebody was exploiting
and victimizing her to get her to get an abortion.''
   ``An extremely serious and distressing thing has happened,'' he
said, adding that his client ``is absolutely devastated that his
child has been taken from him.''
   Bopp said he and his client haven't considered seeking a
contempt citation against the woman for violating Vigo County
Circuit Judge Robert H. Brown's order issued last week. On Monday,
Brown issued a permanent injunction.
   ``He loves this girl,'' Bopp said of his 24-year-old client.
``He's not interested in punishing her.''
   If allowed to stand, Brown's ruling invites other Indiana courts
``to engage in the same pernicious and impermissible inquiry into,
and overruling of, a competent adult woman's decision to terminate
her first trimester pregnancy,'' Waples told the court.
   The woman's attorneys said her first trimester would have ended
sometime during the next two weeks.
   Waples argued Brown's injunction violated the 1973 U.S. Supreme
Court ruling in Roe vs. Wade, which upheld a woman's right to an
abortion during the first trimester of a pregnancy.
   Waples also said the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in 1976 that a
spouse cannot veto a woman's decision to end a pregnancy during the
first three months.
   Bopp said he wants a ruling detailing what rights a father has
in such cases. ``Fathers have rights in particular cases. All we
said in this case is we want those rights to be balanced'' with
those of the mother, Bopp said.
   Since the case involves a paternity action, neither the woman
nor the man has been identified in court records.
</TEXT>
