<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0541,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3,000 Guild Writers Picket Disney As Strike Intensifies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to explain what waiver would do, picking
up 4th graf pvs, ``We feel ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 West Coast writers picketed
Walt Disney Studios before they met to discuss granting waiver
contracts in their 6-week-old strike against movie and television
producers.
   The Los Angeles meeting of about 1,000 striking writers
following the mass picketing was closed to the public and news
media. Results of a vote on the waiver contracts was withheld until
the East Coast writers vote tonight.
   A ``yes'' vote would enable writers to negotiate contracts on a
case-by-case basis with producers, even during the strike, if the
Writers Guild of America grants a waiver. Such waivers are not
given lightly _ the WGA refused a special request for one at
Monday's Academy Awards show.
   Meanwhile, the union disclosed that it had asked a federal
mediator to step in to try to restart bargaining talks.
   ``We feel very strongly that what is needed now is for the two
parties to meet,'' said WGA spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden.
   Joining picketing writers in Burbank were Joanna Kerns, star of
the ABC television series ``Growing Pains,'' actor Mike Farrell and
``Cheers'' star John Ratzenberger.
   ``Every strike ultimately hurts everyone,'' said Ms. Kerns, who
said her show's shooting schedule for new fall episodes has been
pushed back from July to August.
   The picketing at Disney was the largest demonstration by the
writers since a mass protest outside CBS Studios in Los Angeles on
March 11.
   Circling overhead was an aircraft towing a banner reading,
``Stop Mickey Mousing Around With The WGA.''
   Federal mediator Leonard Farrell scheduled a Monday morning
meeting between union bargainers and negotiators for the Alliance
of Motion Picture & Television Producers.
   The meeting was requested by the writers union and ``by law we
must attend and will,'' said Herb Steinberg, a spokesman for the
producers. However, he added, ``Our attitude hasn't changed.''
   The 9,000-member WGA went on strike against the producers March
7. There have been no formal negotiations since talks broke off
March 10.
   Disputed issues include how much writers are paid for foreign
broadcasts of their material and for reruns on domestic television,
and how much creative control they have over their work.
</TEXT>
