<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Whaling     04-14 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Whaling,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Notify United States of End to Commercial Whaling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has followed up on informal
pledges and officially notified the United States that it has
stopped commercial whaling, U.S. Commerce Secretary C. William
Verity said Thursday.
   ``This is a significant international achievement which removes
a major obstacle to U.S.-Soviet cooperation in fisheries,'' Verity
told a news conference.
   The Soviets announced in 1985 that they would stop commercial
whaling and an offical of the ministry of the fishing industry
confirmed it to reporters in May. But it was unclear whether the
Soviet Union would continue limited whaling for scientific purposes.
   The International Whaling Commission, to which the Soviet Union
belongs, agreed in 1982 to a moratorium on commercial whaling
beginning in 1986 to give whale stocks a chance to recover from
severe cuts. The Soviet Union, Japan and Norway objected.
   William Evans, undersecretary of commerce for oceans and
atmosphere, told The Associated Press after the news conference
that Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin had formally notified Verity of
the cessation of commercial whaling in a meeting in Washington
earlier this month.
   Verity plans to certify to President Reagan that the Soviet
Union is complying with the whaling moratorium, Evans said.
   Under a 1967 law, the president may order an embargo of the
fishery products of any country conducting a fishing operation that
diminishes the effectiveness of an international fishery
conservation program.
   Verity said he hopes the Soviet cessation of commercial whaling
will allow for an expansion of fishing cooperation provided for in
a new agreement signed Feb. 21.
</TEXT>
