<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--WeatherWire     04-14 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Weather Wire,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Virginia Firm Wins Weather Wire Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contel ASC of McLean, Va., has been chosen to
modernize the national weather wire, the National Weather Service
announced on Thursday.
   The cost to upgrade the national weather information and warning
system is expected to be about $12 million, the National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration reported.
   The weather wire currently operates on a system of low-speed,
land based Teletype circuits. It will be replaced by a satellite
system broadcasting directly to subscribers, the agency reported.
   The changeover is expected to begin operation in October, with
full operation for the National Weather Service completed in a year.
   The new system will deliver information at a rate 16 times
faster than the current system, according to Weather Service
director Elbert W. Friday.
