<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MaulingTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0487 04-14 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mauling Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0487,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Recalls Fighting Off Lion As It Maimed Her Daughter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Durkovitz' testimony.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, ``She has ....' Note contents of this story.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with injury to a child
after his lion mauled a little girl testified today he had taken
all the safety precautions possible, but expressed his regret about
the attack.
   Gary Durkovitz, 35, of Houston, said he was walking his
350-pound pet lion Samson on a chain at the Texas Flea Market in
Houston when the lion pounced on 8-year-old Roxanne Hernandez.
   The animal bit into the girl's skull, exposing her brain.
Roxanne has undergone reconstructive surgery and faces more
operations to correct part of a missing skull and a bald spot on
her head.
   Defense attorney Robert Scardino has called the attack by the
lion ``a tragic accident.'' Durkovitz faces a maximum two- to
10-year sentence and $5,000 fine if convicted of the felony.
   Durkovitz testified today that he had taken all the precautions
he could think of while walking the lion, who was there as part of
an exhibit, out of the flea market building.
   ``I immediately jumped on top of him and kept yelling, `No.
No,''' Durkovitz said. ``I was trying to separate little Roxanne
from the lion.
   ``I looked up at (a security guard) and said, `Shoot him, shoot
him,''' Durkovitz said. ``About the same time he shot him, he bit
down on Roxanne.
   ``I took every step I knew possible that I had been using for
two years (to prevent an accident),'' he said. ``I'm very sorry
that it happened.''
   The state rested its case Wednesday after calling Roxanne and
her mother, Sonia Hernandez.
   Roxanne, wearing a white sailor's cap to cover her injured head,
testified that all she remembered about the attack was that ``the
lion got me. I didn't know what it was.''
   Mrs. Hernandez said her daughter was in the hospital for a month
and has had problems since she returned to school in February.
   ``She has trouble concentrating on her work during the day and
she has trouble following directions,'' Mrs. Hernandez said.
   Mrs. Hernandez testified that they went to the flea market to
buy a gift and the attack occurred shortly after they entered the
building.
   ``The lion was wrestling with my daughter and I was pulling it
trying to get it off my daughter,'' Mrs. Hernandez said. ``I was
screaming out for her and she was screaming out for me.
   ``I was screaming for help and she would call out my name, `Mom!
Mom! Help me!''' Mrs. Hernandez recalled.
   Mrs. Hernandez said she pulled the lion's mane, but to no avail
and that the animal tried to put the girl's head into its mouth.
   ``I saw the lion when he took her scalp off,'' Mrs. Hernandez
said. ``I felt really helpless at that time and at that moment I
felt it was going to kill her.''
   She said a security guard shot the lion and it loosened its grip
on her child. It later was destroyed.
   Scardino also complained to State District Judge Ted Poe of
Houston that the media coverage of the trial was intense and
``pro-prosecution.''The trial of Durkovitz, a Houston resident, had
been moved here because of pretrial publicity.
   Also Wednesday, David Ruhter, mammal curator at the Houston Zoo,
testified that lions seek out children, but are intimidated by
adults.
   ``It attacks its prey because it moves,'' Ruhter said. ``It's
his livelihood. You see it in 9-week-old cats when they attack a
ball.''
</TEXT>
