<DOCNO> AP880414-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1408EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TaxFreedom Bjt   04-14 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Freedom, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Average American Will Have Paid Tax Obligation by May 5 This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``average'' American will have to work 126
days this year _ two more than in 1987 _ just to pay federal, state
and local taxes, the Tax Foundation said Thursday. ``Tax Freedom
Day'' will fall on May 5, the latest ever.
   The best taxpayers have fared in the past decade was in 1984 _
when most of the big 1981 federal income-tax reduction had taken
effect _ when Tax Freedom Day fell on April 28, economists for the
foundation said.
   But federal tax increases enacted in 1982, 1984 and 1987 ``have
lopped off big chunks of the '81 cuts, and Social Security hikes
have made further inroads until, like the Cheshire Cat in `Alice in
Wonderland,' nothing remains but the smile,'' the foundation said.
   Last year, the big day was May 4; this year's May 5 date is two
days later because 1988 is a leap year, which meant there was a
Feb. 29 this year.
   With the approach of the Friday midnight deadline for filing
federal tax returns _ the first under the heavily revised tax law _
there were these other tax developments:
   _The Internal Revenue Service, whose telephone ``assistors''
have been giving the wrong answer to about 28 of every 100 tax
questions this year, disclosed some factors it will consider in
determining whether to waive certain penalties for taxpayers who
follow such bad advice.
   The agency said penalties for late filing, negligence and
failure to pay can be waived if the taxpayers proves he or she
acted reasonably.
   It will consider pertinent factors such as whether the taxpayer
also sought the correct answer in an IRS publication, as well as
what specific question was asked of the assistor and what was the
actual answer.
   It also would help the taxpayer to know the name of the IRS
employee and the time and date of the telephone call.
   _House Republicans and several business organizations began a
campaign to block future income-tax increases, amend the
Constitution to require a balanced budget and pass a ``bill of
rights'' to help taxpayers in disputes with the IRS.
   Seventy-eight Republican representatives have signed a promise
to oppose raising income taxes, while 190 (mostly Republicans)
lawmakers have signed a petition requiring the House Judiciary
Committee to allow a vote on the balanced-budget amendment. Such a
vote requires the assent of 218 representatives.
   ``The federal budget can be balanced in less than four years
without raising taxes if Congress controls the growth of spending
to less than the inflation rate,'' David Keating, vice president of
the National Taxpayers Union, told a news conference sponsored by
GOP lawmakers.
   _The National Federation of Independent Business released a
survey indicating that 75 percent of business owners polled think
the tax laws are more complex since the 1986 revision. About 55
percent say their companies are spending more time on tax forms,
but two-thirds would not be willing to pay more in order to get
simpler taxes.
   The Tax Foundation, a Washington-based research organization,
assumes that individuals pay all taxes _ including those collected
from corporations _ when it calculates Tax Freedom Day. The
economists simply divide all federal, state and local tax
collections among taxpayers and assume that every penny earned each
year goes to government until tax obligations are satisfied.
   Viewed from another perspective, the foundation estimates the
average taxpayer will work 1 hour and 50 minutes each eight-hour
day to pay federal taxes, and another 55 minutes for state and
local taxes. That's two minutes longer for federal taxes than in
1987 but the same as last year for state and local taxes.
   By the same measure, housing will require 1 hour and 24 minutes
(unchanged); food and tobacco, 56 minutes (two minutes less);
transportation 40 minutes (unchanged); medical care 39 minutes
(unchanged); clothing 22 minutes (one minute less); recreation 21
minutes (unchanged); and everything else will take 53 minutes of
work, one minute less than last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880414-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Helmsleys-Profile     04-14 0945</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helmsleys-Profile,0969</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Helmsleys</HEAD>
<HEAD>The King, The Queen, & Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harry Helmsley bought his first property, a
dilapidated office building, for $1,000 in 1936. A decade later he
sold it for $165,000; now his real estate equity is estimated at
$1.4 billion.
   Leona Mindy Rosenthal, the daughter of a Brooklyn hatmaker, had
been the Chesterfield cigarette girl before she settled on a career
in real estate and, ultimately, married Harry Helmsley.
   Now this king of Manhattan real estate and the queen of the
Helmsley hotel chain are in a court devoid of royalty; they
surrendered Thursday and pleaded innocent to federal and state
charges of tax evasion, falsifying business records and, in Leona's
case, extortion conspiracy.
   The charges are so shocking because they involve people whose
wealth is nearly unbounded. Helmsley was listed 21st on the Forbes
list of the 400 richest Americans last year; he owns the Empire
State Building.
   Their estate in Greenwich, Conn., central to the charges,
consists of a 28-room Tudor mansion on 29 acres. But that is not
the only Helmsley residence: Harry and Leona also spend time at a
duplex atop the Park Lane Hotel, and at a lakefront condominium in
Palm Beach, Fla.
   Harry and Leona shower each other with gifts (sometimes paid for
with company money, according to the indictment) and their
generosity sometimes extends to others. In 1986, they made the
single largest philanthropic gesture in the country, giving $33
million to New York Hospital.
   Neither of the Helmsleys was born of wealth. Helmsley's father
was a notions buyer for a wholesale dry goods firm; the son
graduated from high school but never attended college. His first
job, as office boy at the real-estate firm he eventually came to
own, paid $12 a week.
   His credo? ``All you have to do is buy, and if you make a
mistake, the market comes along and takes care of it,'' he once
said.
   Helmsley, 79, owns 50,000 apartments and 7 million feet of
commercial space. He bought the Empire State Building, then the
world's tallest building, in the 1950s: ``Every morning you would
look out of the window and the building is staring you in the face.
So, you'd say, `Well, I gotta buy it.''
   On July 4, 1976, Helmsley lit the Empire State Building in red,
white and blue _ a tribute not to the Bicentennial, but to his
wife's birthday. It cost $100,000. ``It was less than a necklace,''
he said.
   Leona Helmsley, 67, is Harry's second wife; his previous
marriage ended in divorce in 1972 after 33 years, with no children.
Leona, too, was married before, to a lawyer whom she divorced in
1959. Her only son died in 1982.
   The former showroom model and advertising mannequin was a
successful real estate broker when Helmsley met her in 1971; he
hired her as a $500,000-a-year senior vice president and married
her a year later. By all accounts, she is just wild about Harry;
People magazine records that she calls him ``gorgeous one ...
pussycat ... snooky, wooky, dooky.''
   Shortly after their marriage, in 1973, a man wearing a gas mask
broke into their Palm Beach bedroom. ``Wake up darling, we have
company,'' Leona told her husband, nudging him awake.
   The naked Helmsleys chased the intruder, but before he fled he
stabbed Leona in the chest with a bread knife, puncturing her lung.
   When Harry put Leona in charge of the Helmsley hotels in 1980,
he was not providing her with a sinecure. She took complete charge,
and became the star of ads for the hotel chain which trumpeted her
demanding nature as a guarantee of quality.
   ``It's the only palace in the world where the Queen stands
guard,'' said one ad for the Helmsley Palace in Manhattan.
   The royal appellation is matched by a volatile, queen-size
temper, according to many employees.
   ``She comes on as extremely forthright, but that sometimes turns
into brutality,'' said one former employee, advertising executive
Jane Maas. ``She's icy, without compassion; she is remorseless and
pitiless.''
   According to the federal indictment, Leona did more than harass
her employees _ she shook them down, demanding kickbacks in
exchange for their continued employment. Sources said some two
dozen Helmsley employees testified before the grand jury under
grant of immunity.
   Harry, by contrast, is known as a courtly gentleman. He does not
envy Leona's celebrity _ the ads, the interviews, the profiles on
``60 Minutes.''
   ``I think one person should take the limelight. It dilutes if
there are two,'' Helmsley said in 1986.
   ``I have a different aspect of the business. I like to plan
buildings, organize them and finance them. Once I build it, I
couldn't care less, and that's where she comes in. She is fantastic
at entertaining and day-to-day operations _ details I hate. The
only thing I like is adding up a column of figures and getting the
bottom line.''
   Even prior to their latest legal problems, Leona Helmsley
received some unwelcome publicity when it was reported she failed
to pay more than $38,000 in sales tax for jewelry at Van Cleef &
Arpels. She was never charged, but sources said she was given
immunity for her cooperation with authorities.
   Then last year, a series of reports in the New York Post
detailed allegations that the Helmsleys had charged millions of
dollars in renovations of their Connecticut mansion to their
business. Those revelations, the basis of the indictments, were
fueled by tips from the Queen's disgruntled subjects.
   ``Most of the calls seem to have been prompted by people's
dislike of Mrs. Helmsley,'' said Post reporter Ransdell Pierson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
