<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1435EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-TV     04-14 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-TV,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Approves Private Television In Spain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament voted Thursday to end the
32-year state monopoly on television broadcasting by passing a law
authorizing the creation of three private TV networks.
   The law takes effect following publication in the Official State
Bulletin.
   The law stipulates that no individual nor group may own more
than 25 percent of any of the three networks, a provision seen by
major publishing groups as an attempt to limit the influence of the
established media.
   Participation of foreign investors is limited to a second 25
percent share in any of the three networks.
   There are two state-controlled national television networks in
Spain and three more local networks controlled by the regional
governments of Galicia, the Basque Country and Catalonia.
   Spanish National Television was founded in 1956 during the
authoritarian regime of Gen. Francisco Franco. Spaniards watch more
TV than citizens of the other 11 European Economic Community member
nations except Great Britain.
   Channel 10, a London-based company with Spanish and foreign
participation, began broadcasting in Spanish to Spain via satellite
in January.
   Since entering office in 1982, the government of Socialist Prime
Minister Felipe Gonzalez had pledged to enact legislation creating
three nationwide private TV networks.
   Minister of Transport, Communications and Tourism Abel Caballero
has estimated that none of the three networks will be ready to go
on the air for 18 months to three years following enactment of the
law.
   The ministry has estimated the cost of upgrading the existing
transmission network and land lines at between $45 million to $180
million.
   Once the new law goes into effect, the government is expected to
request public bids for the private network licenses based on
criteria to be set by the Transport and Communications Ministry.
   In the last three years, several publishing groups in Spain have
formed groups in preparation for the bidding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
