<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru   04-14 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0634,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas and Contras Agree on Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with agreement reached. Edits to
trim. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government and Contra leaders today
agreed to renew technical talks on implementing a cease-fire and to
start high-level negotiations to end the six-year civil war.
   The stalled cease-fire technical talks were to start immediately
in the southern border post of Sapoa, site of earlier meetings. The
high-level talks were to start in Managua on Friday.
   A government delegation traveled to Sapoa almost immediately
after the agreement was announced at noon by the Contras and Manuel
Espinoza, information minister for the leftist Sandinista
government.
   The Sandinistas backed off from their demand that the technical
talks be held in Managua and agreed to a Contra request that they
be in Sapoa. In exchange, the Contras stopped insisting that
Friday's political talks begin only if the Sapoa talks were
successful.
   ``The Contras agreed that if the talks are not finished today,
they'll conclude in Managua,'' Espinoza told The Associated Press
in a telephone interview.
   Earlier today, Contra representatives Roberto Ferrey and David
Stadthagen flew into the capital's Sandino airport in a private
aircraft and were met by Tourism Minister Herty Lewites. It was the
first time the government had allowed Contras into Managua.
   On Wednesday, a Sandinista negotiator accused the Contras of not
being serious about ending the civil war.
   ``We have serious doubts they want to enter into a definitive
cease-fire,'' Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco told
reporter.
   ``There's a problem of confidence,'' he said, adding that the
Nicaraguan government did not want to see the talks unravel. ``If
they (Contras) don't come on the 15th (Friday), we'll have to see
the alternatives.''
   The cease-fire pact was signed March 23 in Sapoa. The talks are
to work out details of how to get Contra forces into several zones
inside Nicaragua as a prelude to ending the war.
   The military talks stalled April 8 after six rounds in which the
two sides agreed only to establish seven zones to which Contra
fighters would be confined during a 60-day truce that went into
effect on April 1.
   Still to be worked out are security for the rebels in those
zones, methods of resupplying them and other details concerning the
guerrillas during the two months allowed for negotiating a
permanent cease-fire.
   Rebel fighters are scheduled to be in the zones by Friday, but
they have not even begun gathering. The Sandinistas have agreed
that once they verify the rebels are in the zones, half of the
1,400 jailed Contras will be freed.
   Nicaragua is estimated to have more than 3,000 political
prisoners. The Sandinistas released 100 soon after the provisional
truce was signed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880414-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Gulf-Frigate 6thLd-Writethru a0656 04-14 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Frigate, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0656,680</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2 grafs for 3rd graf pvs to update injuries; inserts 1
graf new material after 12th graf pvs, ``They say</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Navy frigate on patrol in the Persian
Gulf apparently struck an underwater mine today, injuring six
sailors, the Pentagon said today.
   The ship, the USS Samuel B. Roberts, was in no danger of
sinking, said Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard. No one was killed and
the six sailors did not sustain life-threatening injuries, he added.
   The Pentagon said that four of the sailors had second-degree
burns; the other two had slight back injuries. None of the injuries
was considered life-threatening.
   All were flown from by helicopter from the ship for medical
treatment.
   The ship is based in Newport, R.I., and left there for Persian
Gulf duty on Jan. 11.
   ``At approximately 10:10 this morning EDT, the USS Sam Roberts
... experienced an underwater explosion in the Persian Gulf at a
point approximately 70 miles due east of Bahrain Bell (a
navigational aid),'' Howard said.
   The explosion ``caused flooding in the engine room and some hull
damage. The flooding is under control, and the ship is in the
process of pumping out the water. It's operating under auxiliary
power.''
   Howard said that the USS Wainwright, a cruiser, ``is en route to
the site to offer assistance and should be there soon.''
   The incident occurred in the central Persian Gulf, well to the
south of the spot near the Iranian-controlled Farsi Island where a
reflagged Kuwaiti tanker, the Bridgeton, hit a mine during the
first of the Navy's convoy operation last July. Howard said there
had been no recent reports by mine-sweepers in the area that mines
had been sighted.
   The spokesman refused to say that the underwater explosion had
been caused by a mine, citing the paucity of information from
initial reports.
   ``It really is too early to tell,'' Howard said. ``Underwater
explosion is the way to describe it. We don't know what caused the
explosion. All we've got is an underwater explosion at this point.''
   Howard said the Roberts was steaming in the area after
completing an escort operation Wednesday night. The spokesman said
he assumed ``there were no other U.S. vessels in close proximity,''
but couldn't say for sure.
   ``They say the flooding is under control and they're pumping the
thing out and doing that under auxiliary power,'' Howard said.
   Within hours of the explosion, the Pentagon said, the ship had
begun steaming toward port in Bahrain.
   The Roberts is the same type of guided-missile frigate as the
USS Stark, the frigate that was hit last May in an Iraqi air
attack. Thirty-seven Americans died in that attack.
   Ships of the Oliver Hazard Perry class normally carry a crew of
about 190 sailors and 13 officers. The Pentagon said the Roberts
was carrying about 225 men, however, because it had a helicopter
detachment aboard from Mayport, Fla..
   One Pentagon official who asked not to be named said the
explosion ``does not appear to have been caused by any failure of
systems on board the ship.''
   Another source added: ``The Roberts hit something; we are
assuming it was a mine.''
   The Pentagon said the Roberts was under the command of Cmdr.
Paul X. Rinn. It fixed the location of the explosion at 26.25
degrees north and 52.15 degrees east.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said President
Reagan had been told of the incident. Fitzwater said that he did
not know how Reagan was told, but that the president was
``routinely informed'' about such matters by national security
adviser Colin Powell or a member of the National Security Council
staff.
   Fitzwater said the incident ``only emphasizes our concern for
stopping the Iran-Iraq war,'' which has led to the mining of the
gulf.
   He said the administration intended to step up pressure in the
U.N. Security Council for a resolution that would not only put an
end to the war but put the group on record in favor of sanctions
against belligerents in the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
