<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghan-WorldReax     04-14 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-World Reax,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afhan Agreement Hailed in Both East & West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER C. PUTNAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The accord for a Soviet troop withdrawal from Afghanistan was
hailed Thursday by countries in both the East and West as a vital
first step toward peace, and some offered to help Afghan refugees.
   In southern Asia, however, skepticism remained over some aspects
of the plan, particularly the continued aid to combatants.
   The agreements, signed in Geneva by representatives of the
United States, the Soviet Union, Afghanistan and Pakistan, will
take effect May 15 and will commit Pakistan and Afghanistan not to
support ``directly or indirectly, rebellious or secessionist
activities'' against each other after nine years of civil war and
Soviet entanglement.
   In Brussels, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization welcomed the
agreements and said it hoped they would yield further improvements
in superpower relations.
   ``The Soviet occupation of Afghanistan has been a serious
impediment in East West relations,'' NATO said. ``The
implementation of the Geneva agreements will, we hope, lead to
further improvements in the atmosphere between East and West.''
   Austrian Vice Chancellor and Foreign Minister Alois Mock called
the agreements ``a step to the strengthening of East-West
relaxation.''
   The accords open the possibility that ``other regional conflicts
be settled peacefully,'' Mock said.
   Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi expressed concern, however,
about a continued flow of weapons to Afghan rebels and said some of
them were reaching India's Sikh extremists through neighboring
Pakistan.
   The Sikh extremists, fighting for a separate nation in Punjab,
used rocket-propelled grenades for the first time last month.
Officials in the northwest Indian state say the rebels also have
increased their stock of AK-47 assault rifles.
   Indian officials recently charged that Pakistan was helping
Sikhs acquire weapons. Pakistan denied the charge.
   The Times of India, an independent English-language daily, said
in an editorial titled ``Meaningless Agreement'':
   ``Moscow will be able to withdraw its troops without having to
acknowledge the plain fact that it has failed to pacify Afghanistan
in the face of resistance by U.S.-backed mujahedeen. But on the
face of it, the agreement will be pretty meaningless otherwise.
   ``For it will stipulate that the Americans and the Russians will
continue to be entitled to provide arms to their respective
clients. And while Pakistan will formally agree not to interfere in
Afghanistan's internal affairs, it will in reality continue to do
so inasmuch as it will still serve as a conduit for U.S. arms
supplies to the mujahedeen.''
   The accord was praised in communist nations.
   Non-aligned communist Yugoslavia, which has repeatedly condemned
Soviet intervention in Afghanistan, said the agreements represent
``an important first step which could lead to a final peace
settlement in that country.''
   In a commentary, the state Tanjug news agency said the final
solution of the conflict is still far away because the region has
been ``burdened by different international interests.''
   ``All sides involved must now show maximum goodwill,
statesman-like wisdom and responsibility,'' the Czechoslovak CTK
news agency said.
   Both Denmark and Japan said they would join a United Nations
military force observing the accord in Afghanistan.
   Finland and Sweden, both neutral Scandinavian countries, also
have agreed in principle to send observers to Afghanistan.
   Danish newspapers said Poland and Canada also have been asked to
join the force, reportedly to be led by a Finnish general.
   Japan planned to assist in the relocation of 5 million civilian
refugees, said a Foreign Ministry spokesman in Tokyo.
   Acting Foreign Ministry spokesman Koichi Haraguchi said, ``Also,
it is our intention to extend financial assistance to facilitate
the safe and honorable return of the refugees to Afghanistan.''
   Britain also announced plans to aid refugees, with an $18.7
million grant for resettlement.
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe said the grant was
conditional on the setting up of ``properly coordinated
international arrangements'' for the return of millions of Afghan
refugees from neighboring Pakistan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
