<DOCNO> AP880414-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1452EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CondomPatrol     04-14 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Condom Patrol,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Used Condoms Collected From Sewage Plant To Test ``Safe Sex''
Advice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health workers are counting used condoms that
float to the surface of the city's sewage treatment plant pools in
an effort to find out how many people are heeding advice about safe
sex to avoid AIDS.
   Hundreds of condoms float in the water at open-air pools at
waste water treatment plants. For the last eight months, city
workers have been using long-handled fish nets to scoop the
multicolored condoms from the sewage and count them each day.
   The study, which should be completed in a year, may help
determine whether people are heeding warnings to use condoms as a
way to prevent the spread of the acquired immune deficiency
syndrome virus, officials said.
   ``We talk a lot about using condoms, but the question is whether
we're really doing it,'' said Dr. Diane Dwyer, who heads a
federally funded AIDS study in Baltimore. ``We're serious about it,
we really want to find out whether more condoms are being used, or
whether people are just buying them and storing them by the bedside
for potential future use.''
   The study includes counting the number of condoms sold at
drugstores and those given away free by the health department, Ms.
Dwyer said.
   Though officials don't know how many condoms are flushed down
toilets or simply thrown away, they said they had no intention of
going through garbage.
   ``It's certainly not a very pleasant job, but it is important,''
said Courtland Storck, the AIDS surveillance supervisor for the
health department. ``If it does work, and we hope it does, then
hopefully other cities would adapt a similar program.''
   The health department said it has so far retrieved between 200
and 400 condoms each day floating in the sewage pools.
   A Johns Hopkins Hospital doctor first suggested the study method
in Baltimore, but officials say the first such count was made in
the late 1970s in Ireland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
