<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Downey     04-14 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Downey,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Talk Show Host Morton Downey Jr. Cleared Of Assaulting Guest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``You, you, you'' _ the familiar chant of
fans of ultra-conservative Morton Downey Jr. _ rang out in a
municipal courtroom as the talk show host was cleared of charges
that he assaulted a gay rights activist during a program.
   Judge Emil DelBaglivo found Downey innocent of assaulting Andrew
Humm, a 34-year-old spokesman for the Coalition for Lesbian and Gay
Rights.
   DelBaglivo watched a videotape of the show and listened to
testimony during a 4{-hour trial Wednesday before issuing his
decision.
   The 55-year-old Downey, flashed his familiar toothy grin to the
crowd after the verdict and said, ``I am very pleased.'' Downey
faced up to six months in jail and a $1,000 fine had he been
convicted.
   Downey was charged with assaulting Humm Dec. 9 during the taping
of a show that involved a discussion of the role of the Catholic
Church in the modern world. The taping, at WWOR-TV in Secaucus, was
interrupted by a bomb threat, and the show was never broadcast.
   The judge said there were conflicting eyewitness accounts so the
key evidence was the 25-minute videotape.
   The tape shows Downey in a face-to-face argument with Humm.
Downey said, ``Keep your bodily fluids to yourself'' as he wiped a
small amount of spittle from his face.
   Humm said the comment about bodily fluids implied that because
he was a gay person he also had AIDS, and that his fluids were to
be feared.
   On the tape, Humm replied with an epithet, fumbled with the
microphone, and raised his right arm. Downey abruptly struck Humm's
arm away, and in doing so, he grazed Humm's face. Downey then
admonished Humm, ``Watch your language.''
   Downey's attorney, Thomas Roth of Newark, argued that the blow
did not cause pain to Humm and presented a neurologist who
testified that it would have been impossible for Humm to be injured.
   Humm testified: ``I felt humiliated, and it stung. There was no
sustained injury, but it hurt.''
</TEXT>
