<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0835</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Jane Byrne, spurned in her last
three election bids, has signed with a New York agent and says she
will write her autobiography.
   ``There are a lot of people who would pay me a million dollars
not to write the book,'' Mrs. Byrne said Wednesday. ``I might as
well write the book.''
   Gerard McCauley, a former senior editor for Little, Brown & Co.
and Alfred A. Knopf, has been hired to represent her.
   There is ``substantial interest'' on the part of New York
publishers in a book by the former mayor, McCauley said.
   In it, Mrs. Byrne, 54, said she will discuss her tenure as mayor
from 1979 to 1983 as well as her early life, her membership in
former Mayor Richard Daley's cabinet, her association with the
Kennedy family and her roles in local, state and national
Democratic politics.
   Mrs. Byrne lost a primary race to former Mayor Harold Washington
in her bid for re-election in 1983. She lost the Democratic mayoral
primary again last year. Earlier this year, she lost a bid for the
office of clerk of the circuit courts for Cook County.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Valentina Tereshkova, the first woman in
space, said Thursday that nuclear disarmament ``is the only road
for mankind's immortality.''
   Mrs. Tereshkova, who orbited the Earth 48 times aboard the
Soviet Union's Vostok 6 in 1963, made her appeal to 200 political
and spiritual leaders attending a global survival forum in the
university city of Oxford.
   ``Human beings had to break into space to realize how beautiful
is their cradle, planet Earth,'' she said through a translator.
   The former cosmonaut recently became chairwoman of the Soviet
Union's state-run International Cultural and Friendship Union.
   ``The main task is to save the world from nuclear destruction,''
she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elizabeth Taylor is here raising money for the
battle against AIDS, but at her previous stop in Thailand she
raised the eyebrows of a politician who was quoted in local papers
as saying she was getting too much attention.
   Thailand's Nation newspaper, reporting Thursday about a Monday
luncheon in Bangkok for the actress, said that Premier Prem
Tinsulanonda ``could hardly contain his excitement and even asked
what colors the American actress would be wearing, according to
government spokesman Mechai Viravaidya.''
   Then the Bangkok Post newspaper quoted former Prime Minister
Kukrit Pramoj, a frequent, biting critic of Prem, as saying in a
meeting with reporters Wednesday that he felt ``slighted'' by the
attention Prem gave to Ms. Taylor.
   ``I am also a Hollywood actor, but he pays no special attention
to me,'' Kukrit said. ``I was the first Thai to star in a movie
with Marlon Brando.''
   Kukrit, 76, was referring to his appearance in the 1959 movie
``The Ugly American.''
   ``What is so good about Elizabeth Taylor?'' he continued. ``She
has had seven husbands. How can you hold her up publicly?''
   Kukrit said ``if Thai women take her example and have seven
husbands,'' government spokesman Mechai, who is also a pioneer in
family planning in Thailand, ``would hang himself.''
   Ms. Taylor has been married to six different men. She was twice
married to actor Richard Burton.
   During her stay in Bangkok, Ms. Taylor denied rumors she was
going to marry American publisher Malcolm Forbes, who was traveling
with her party.
   And in Tokyo, Japan's Kyodo News Service reported that Ms.
Taylor had met Thursday with Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita at his
official residence and had also gotten a pledge of a $10,000
contribution to the American Foundation for AIDS Research from
Shintaro Abe, secretary-general of the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi is on a
three-day visit to inaugurate the Festival of India at Tokyo's
national theater.
   The six-month festival involves more than 80 artists in
classical Indian dance, music and art programs. It is scheduled to
travel across Japan.
   A Japanese Foreign Ministry official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Gandhi was to meet Friday with Crown Prince Akihito
and Crown Princess Michiko as well as Japanese Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita and other political and business leaders.
   An Indian Embassy official said Gandhi, who arrived Thursday,
was to leave Tokyo on Saturday for Vietnam.
