<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Crash     04-14 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Crash,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Crash Blamed on Crew, Air Traffic Control Error</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crash of an Aeroflot passenger jet in February
in which 20 people died was blamed on errors by the crew and an air
traffic controller, investigators said.
   A report on the investigation of the crash in the Siberian city
of Surgut, 1,400 miles from Moscow, was published Wednesday by the
official news agency Tass.
   The state Civil Aircraft Flght Safety Commission said the pilot
of the Tupolev-134 asked for permission to use a runway not
normally used at the Surgut airport and tried to land the craft in
poor visibility.
   The official report said the plane carried 45 passengers and a
crew of six. Seventeen passengers and three crew members were
killed, and all of the other 31 people aboard were injured.
   ``Since the commander did not stick to the flight parameters set
by the air traffic controller, the plane found itself in a
position, as to the landing strip, which made safe landing
impossible,'' the report said.
   ``The plane therefore made a rough landing away from the landing
strip, it was wrecked by overloads and burst into flames,'' Tass
said.
   The report said co-pilot V. Shuneiko was flying the plane, while
commander A. Shavrovich was talking with the air traffic controller
about switching runways.
   ``Flight director V. Maltsev met the crew's request, but in
doing so, in violation of the rules, he failed to switch on ground
radio facilities for a landing approach and organize observation of
weather in the direction of the landing course,'' Tass said.
   The plane was on a 1,600-mile flight across the western Soviet
Union when it crashed at its final stop.
   Rescue operations were impaired by poorly trained personnel and
insufficient technical facilities at Surgut, the report said.
   ``By the results of the investigation, the Ministry of Civil
Aviation is taking necessary steps to rule out a recurrence of such
aircraft accidents,'' the report said, but did not give details.
</TEXT>
