<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Arizona-KingHoliday     04-14 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arizona-King Holiday,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel To Weigh King-Holiday Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state Senate committee, reversing the stand it
took last year, voted 5-4 Thursday to approve a Martin Luther King
holiday for Arizona.
   The issue has been a source of national controversy since
then-Gov. Evan Mecham rescinded a holiday that his predecessor had
proclaimed without legislative approval.
   The sponsor of the measure, Democrat Carolyn Walker of Phoenix,
said she was confident the full Senate and House will approve the
bill if it gets through the Senate's Republican majority caucus.
The House passed a similar measure 35-25 last year.
   Government Committee Chairman John Mawhinney of Tucson and
Republican member Carol Macdonald of Safford switched their votes.
Mrs. Macdonald did not explain her reasons, but Mawhinney said he
felt it was time to provide spiritual as well as physical help to
those in need.
   The bill is virtually identical to last year's and would conform
Arizona's practice to the federal government's. Instead of being
called a King holiday, the new day off would be known as Martin
Luther King Jr.-Civil Rights Day, however. And instead of being
known as Presidents Day, the combined Lincoln and Washington
holidays would be known as George Washington-Abraham Lincoln Day.
   Mecham was removed by a Senate court of impeachment earlier this
month, and his successor, Gov. Rose Mofford, sent her chief of
staff to the committee Thursday to join religious, union and
tourism industry officials in urging passage of the bill.
   The measure would combine the holidays for George Washington and
Abraham Lincoln into a single February holiday and create a January
holiday for King.
   Although Mecham said that he rescinded the proclaimed holiday on
the advice of Attorney General Bob Corbin and that his Democratic
predecessor, Gov. Bruce Babbitt, usurped a legislative prerogative
in ordering state money spent on a holiday, the action generated an
international controversy.
   Starting with a march of more than 10,000 people on the state
Capitol, the unrest dogged Mecham for the remainder of his term. He
was removed from office April 4 _ the 20th anniversary of King's
assassination _ through a Senate impeachment conviction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
