<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2134EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ASNE     04-14 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ASNE,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Falwell Approves Swaggart Penalties, Doesn't Want Minister in
White House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLL MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelist Jerry Falwell said Thursday he
welcomed tough measures taken against fallen TV minister Jimmy
Swaggart and said that America is not ready for a Pat Robertson or
Jesse Jackson in the White House.
   ``I have no problem with Reverend Jackson running, as long as he
loses,'' Falwell said.
   ``I don't think the American people want a reverend _ it has
nothing to do with Democrat, Republican, black, white, liberal,
conservative. I don't think the American people are ready for a
reverend to be in the White House, and I think it's a pretty good
idea one never is.''
   Falwell's comments came as part of a panel discussion on
televangelists on the second day of a three-day convention of the
American Society of Newspaper Editors.
   An estimated 685 editors attending the convention also heard
from Jackson and his fellow Democratic presidential hopeful, Albert
Gore, as well as from House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and Costa
Rican President Oscar Arias, winner of the Nobel Peace Prize for
his efforts to end fighting in Central America.
   Falwell said he was pleased that television representatives in
the National Religious Broadcasters had agreed to recommend that
all Christian stations drop Swaggart's religious program if he
returns to preaching before his one-year suspension expires.
   ``That doesn't mean all the stations have to comply with that
requirement,'' Falwell said. ``But my guess is that most of them
will.''
   Falwell, along with panelists Jeffrey K. Hadden, sociology
professor at the University of Virginia, and Tulsa (Okla.) Tribune
reporter Mary Hargrove, told the editors that the sex scandals that
brought down Swaggart and Jim and Tammy Faye Bakker marked the end
of an era for televangelists.
   ``We're witnessing a serious readjustment of the work of
religious politics,'' Hadden said.
   ``The questions about financial accountability already had been
raised. The sex scandals were the final icing on the cake,''
Hargrove said.
   Falwell said he believes ``it was inevitable that these
catastrophies occurred'' and said it was not the press that brought
down the Bakkers and Swaggart. ``They brought themselves down.''
   ``Frankly,'' he said, ``an inevitable housecleaning was overdue.
Yes, it's hurt everybody ... but the major hurt is the terrible
damage done to the value systems and the principle systems of young
people in this country.''
   Falwell, who took over the debt-ridden PTL ministry after the
Bakkers' departure and resigned from it late last year, said one
good thing had come out of the Bakker-Swaggart sex scandals: the
end of televangelists' celebrity status.
   ``There will never again, and I thank God it's true, be a person
that people look to as God. Celebrity status is history.''
   Earlier in the day, the editors heard a plea from Wright to
cover all the details of a comprehensive trade bill now before
Congress. He called the measure one of the most important now on
Capitol Hill.
   ``You hold the keys to developing thoughtful commentary on
events,'' Wright said.
</TEXT>
