<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-BaseRights 1stLd-Writethru a0642 04-14 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Base Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Subcommittee Chairman Angered Over Aid Request for NATO
Allies</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: RECASTS lead to reflect that Obey angered over administration
response to documents request, sted administration position;
INSERTS 1 graf with Obey quotes after 3rd graf pvs, bgng: He then.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, At the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House appropriations panel
on Thursday called for suspension of U.S. aid to its three poorest
NATO allies, and stormed out of a hearing to protest the
administration's failure to produce details of previous assistance
to the countries.
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., chairman of the subcommittee on foreign
operations, told State and Defense Department witnesses he was
``fed up with getting this mush from you. You must really think
we're saps up here.''
   He then suspended the hearing after only 50 minutes and strode
out of the room.
   ``There was no sense in my sitting listening for the information
only to be told they they didn't have it,'' Obey told the AP later.
``That was the same thing they said before.''
   At the root of the dispute are demands by Congress that other
NATO members spend more money on the defense of the alliance, in
what is known as ``burden sharing.''
   Obey's outburst was prompted by the administration's failure to
provide the committee with detailed lists of the surplus military
equipment being transferred to Greece, Turkey and Portugal this
year.
   Obey said he had asked for the lists several months ago to help
the committee decide how to allocate funds for the administration's
1989 spending request of $1.4 billion for the three countries,
where the United States maintains military bases and some 15,000
personnel.
   The three are the poorest members of NATO, and the
administration contends the United States must fund them in order
to ensure continued basing rights.
   Obey, a vocal foe of U.S. spending on NATO allies, said the
United States should not ``be engaged in unilateral welfare
efforts'' for these countries. Rather, he said, the aid should be a
joint NATO effort.
   ``My view is that there should be zero funding this year for
base rights countries,'' he said.
   Obey claimed that taxpayers in Athens, Wis., are paying more for
the defense of Greece than those in Athens, Greece. ``My taxpayers
are fed up with this, and so am I.''
   The U.S. taxpayer spends more than $1,000 a year on the defense
of the free world, while British taxpayers spend per capita $488,
the French $511, the West Germans $433 and the Japanese $163, Obey
said. ``We're being taken for a ride.''
   Obey railed against such NATO members as West Germany ``who
constantly lecture us on our deficit and on managing our economy''
but fail to share the burden of maintaining the U.S. presence in
Europe.
   Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Charles Thomas, defending
the administration's spending request _ which is 41 percent higher
than the base rights funding of 1981 _ said U.S. interests clearly
lie in a continued U.S. presence in Europe. ``Our border begins
there,'' he said.
   Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense John A. Woodworth said in
his testimony that while U.S. defense spending grew much more than
that of other NATO members in the years between 1981 and 1986,
``that pattern is now reversed.''
   He said several NATO countries, among them Italy, Greece,
Norway, Spain and Turkey, increased their defense spending by about
3 percent in 1987, while the U.S. increase was only 0.1 percent and
in 1988 it will decline more than 3 percent.
</TEXT>
