<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ScholarshipWithdrawn     04-14 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scholarship Withdrawn,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Choice Of Oral Roberts University Not Factor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of a New York scholarship
program that withdrew its award to an Oral Roberts University
student says the student's choice of college had nothing to do with
the $3,000 grant being taken back.
   But John Kearse, executive director of the Economic Opportunity
Commission of Nassau County, N.Y., told the Tulsa World in a story
for Thursday's editions that future recipients of the scholarships
will be required to attend ``black universities.''
   The Martin Luther King Jr. scholarship, sponsored by the EOC,
was taken away from Karen Warren, 19, of Hempstead, N.Y., in
October 1987, two months after she began classes at Oral Roberts
University. EOC officials said at the time that the scholarship was
rescinded because the high school Miss Warren attended did not have
an EOC-sponsored community action program.
   The Rev. Earl Mitchell, Miss Warren's pastor, responded that the
scholarship was withdrawn ``because John Kearse objects to Karen's
religious beliefs and those of ORU.''
</TEXT>
