<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hijack-Passenger     04-14 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack-Passenger,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Citizen Says Hijackers Overlooked License</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Egyptian-American released after eight days as
a hostage said the Islamic radicals who seized a Kuwait Airways
jumbo jet overlooked his U.S. driver's license.
   ``One of them searched my wallet, and there was my driver's
license,'' Ramadan Ali said during an interview at the home of a
relative in Kuwait. ``I was so lucky. He didn't realize what it
was.''
   Ali was one of 12 passengers freed Tuesday night shortly before
the hijackers of the Boeing 747 flew from Cyprus to Algeria with
more than 30 passengers and crew still aboard.
   Fearful the hijackers would harm him if they knew of his U.S.
citizenship, Ali said he hid his U.S. passport in his briefcase and
used his Egyptian documents.
   When the jet stopped in Iran immediately after the hijacking,
``they collected al our briefcases and put them in a closet and
closed it,'' he said.
   For the rest of his captivity, he said he worried that one might
search his case and discover the document, ``but they had no time
to do it.''
   Ali, who displayed bruises on his wrists, said the hijackers
used plastic handcuffs on the passengers after two days in Iran and
left them on constantly after that.
   ``Clamping your hands 24 hours _ You have to eat, your hand is
tied; go the the bathroom, your hand is tied,'' he said.
   The eight-day ordeal left him nervous, emotionally stunned and
wary of flying, Ali said.
   ``It became to me like a phobia,'' he said. ``It could happen
again.''
   He withheld his American address because ``these guys, they have
long hands.''
   Ali, a consulting engineer who travels widely, said security at
Bangkok airport was loose, ``like a farmer's market.''
   He said he saw passengers who set off alarms on metal detectors
pass unsearched as he was boarding the flight for Kuwait.
   He agreed with other passengers' reports that the hijackers
appeared to take on weapons and two new colleagues during four days
at Mashhad airport in Iran, their first stop.
   But he said he did not actually see any weapons or new men come
aboard. He said screens were drawn across the first-class cabin
where the hijackers stayed and all the aircraft's window shades
were pulled down.
   ``After we left Mashhad, I saw three machine guns,'' which he
said were small weapons resembling the Israeli-made Uzi.
   He said he also saw 10 hand grenades, thick ropes, explosives
and plastic hand grenades only after the plane had been in Mashhad.
He said two new hijackers appeared to join the six younger ones
when the plane was in Iran. He described the newcomers as older
men, 30 to 40, who were giving orders to the others.
   One by one, he said, they called passengers to the front
compartments to question them about their jobs, nationalities,
families and religion.
   He said the people called forward most often were the two
Kuwaitis who were shot to death in Cyprus, although passengers did
not know of the killings until their release.
   Ali said the hijackers also asked the branch of Islam he
belonged to: Sunni or Shiite.
   All of the Kuwaiti men released so far have been Shiites,
members of the branch that predominates in Iran and southern
Lebanon, but is a minority in most of the Islamic world.
   ``I was reading the Koran all the time. They noticed I'm a
religious person,'' he said, speculating that might have helped in
his release.
   He said he tried to pray and that others tried to join in. But
he said the attempt to practice standard Islamic prayers, which
require standing, then kneeling toward Mecca, made the hijackers
nervous.
   ``They said, `Hey guys, if you want to pray, pray in your
seats.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880414-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TradeBreakdown     04-14 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade Breakdown,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade Deficit Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a geographical breakdown of the
February trade balance, based on figures released Thursday by the
Commerce Department. All numbers are negatives, reflecting trade
deficits.
   ``Up'' connotes a worsening, or widening, of the deficit.
``Down'' connotes an improvement, or narrowing, of the deficit.
   Total trade defict: $13.83 billion, up from $12.44 billion in
January.
   Canada: $1.46 billion, up from $1.12 billion in January.
   Western Europe: $1.56 billion, up from $1.33 billion.
   Japan: $4.53 billion, up from $3.95 billion.
   Newly industrialized countries of Asia (Singapore, Hong Kong,
Taiwan and South Korea): $2.9 billion, down from $2.92 billion.
   Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC): $1.3
billion, up from $1.03 billion.
   Mexico: $645 million, up from $553 million.
  
