<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-`Colors'Protest Bjt   04-14 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-`Colors' Protest, Bjt,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filmmakers: Movies Doesn't Glorify Gang Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The violent, realistic gang drama ``Colors''
opens Friday at 425 theaters across the country amid a debate
between its critics and its makers over whether the film will
inspire more youth violence.
   A spokesman for one group of law enforcement officers says the
movie will ``leave dead bodies from one end of this town to the
other,'' but the filmmakers say the film is a statement of
conscience and will save lives.
   ``This is not the right time to release a movie like this,''
said Los Angeles City Councilman Nate Holden. Since April 4, there
have been 89 gang-related deaths in Los Angeles city and county;
last year, there were 387 gang-related deaths in the area.
   ``If there is anything this picture does not do _ it does not
glorify gangs or gang violence,'' said Charles O. Glenn, executive
vice president for the distributor, New York-based Orion Pictures.
   In New York on Thursday, six members of the Guardian Angels, a
community anti-crime group, were arrested during a protest outside
Orion headquarters. The group planned a protest later Thursday in
Los Angeles.
   The movie, starring Sean Penn and Rubert Duvall as gang-fighting
Los Angeles policemen, was directed by Dennis Hopper and used
active area gang members as extras and advisers. The film portrays
the world of the Crips and the Bloods, rival gangs, who use the
colors blue and red, respectively, to distinguish themselves.
   It was made with the ``technical advice, assistance and
cooperation of the LAPD, its anti-gang CRASH unit, the Sheriff's
Department of Los Angeles and the Los Angeles County Probation
Department,'' Glenn said.
   But it has drawn strong criticism from some police, city
officials, the NAACP, community leaders and the Guardian Angels.
   Wes McBride, president of the California Gang Investigators
Association, believes ``Colors'' will ``leave dead bodies from one
end of this town to the other.''
   ``A release of this film may tip the scale in such a way that
will only result in more loss of young lives,'' said Willis
Edwards, president of the Beverly Hills-Hollywood NAACP chapter.
   ``I think the people who are making those predictions are
whipping up the probability and the possibility,'' of violence,
Hopper said. ``The people who are saying blood is going to flow in
the streets are asking for blood to flow in the streets. I think
it's very irresponsible behavior.''
   About 70 theaters in the Los Angeles area alone plan to show
``Colors.'' Many critics called on theaters to cancel the movie.
   The downtown Laemmle Grand did just that. ``The staff at the
theater were in a panic because the home turf of one of the gangs
in the movie is just a couple of miles from downtown,'' said Bob
Laemmle, theater chain co-owner.
   But Joel Maliniak, spokesman for the American Civil Liberties
Union of Southern California, said: ``Officials should be finding
solutions to the gang problem rather than prohibiting something
from being shown.''
   District Attorney Ira Reiner said he believes the movie will
galvanize support for the county's war on gangs.
   At a celebrity showing Wednesday night, which drew Cher, Marlee
Matlin, Richard Dean Anderson, Bono Hewson and Emilio Estevez, 10
members of the Guardian Angels marched and chanted ``Don't Show
`Colors.'''
   ``There is nothing in this film that glorifies being in a
gang,'' said Hopper, who also attended the VIP showing.
   Five Guardian Angels were arrested Tuesday when they tried to
force their way into Orion's Los Angeles offices. The Angels,
including group founder Curtis Sliwa who has called the movie
``racist and irresponsible,'' were arrested for investigation of
battery after allegedly pushing and tackling security guards.
   ``We feel that `Colors' is an honest and socially responsible
portrayal of a problem that obviously exists in Los Angeles and in
the streets of every other American city,'' Glenn said.
   He called ``Colors'' a ``significant work by filmmakers of
substance and integrity,'' and likened it to statement movies made
in the past, including ``Gentleman's Agreement'' about
anti-Semitism, ``I Am a Fugitive from A Chain Gang'' about legal
injustice, ``Platoon'' about the futility of combat and ``On the
Waterfront'' about waterfront gangs.
</TEXT>
