<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-NewspageStocks 1stLd-Writethru a0729 04-14 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newspage Stocks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0729,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Plunges 100 Points; Dollar Slides; Interest Rates Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with closing stocks, late dollar and bonds.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices and the dollar plunged and interest
rates shot higher today after an unexpected bulge in the trade
deficit sent shock waves through the financial markets.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped about
101 points, while in the currency markets the value of the dollar
fell 2 percent against major currencies. Interest rates on a key
long-term U.S. Treasury bond jumped to a three-month high.
   Traders scrambled to sell dollars, bonds and stocks after the
Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's trade
deficit had risen to $13.8 billion in February. That was the
biggest shortfall since the record of $17.6 billion in October and
the second monthly increase in a row. Many economists had been
expecting the deficit to narrow.
   The Dow Jones industrials tumbled 35 points within 20 minutes of
the opening bell on the New York Stock Exchange then stabilized for
a few hours. But the slide resumed in the afternoon and the average
skidded to a 101.46-point loss at 2,005.63, a 4.8 percent drop,
according to a prelimary calculation.
   It was the worst decline since the Dow plunged 140.58 points on
Jan. 8.
   The Dow's decline triggered a ban on the use of a form of
computerized program trading on the New York Stock Exchange, the
first time the ``collar'' has been triggered by a decline of 50
points or more in the Dow.
   The dollar was down about 1.9 percent against the British pound,
about 1.9 percent against the West German mark and about 2.2
percent against the Japanese yen at midafternoon.
   The impact also was felt in the bond market, an important
barometer of the economy and interest rates. By late afternoon,
prices of the key 30-year Treasury bond were down 1\ points, or
about $12.50 for every $1,000 in face amount, and its yield, which
moves inversely to price, surged to 8.855 percent, the highest in
three months.
</TEXT>
