<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Letters     04-14 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Letters,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letters Between Arab, Israeli Youth Start Dialogue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lior, a 13-year-old Israeli, and Salam, a
12-year-old Palestinian, didn't agree on much, but an editor who
published their letter exchange in his newspaper said it was the
start of a fresh dialogue.
   ``If our generation failed to communicate, maybe this young
generation can do a better job,'' said Othman Hallak, editor of the
An Nahar newspaper. Hallak is known for his moderate pro-Jordanian
views.
   An Nahar on Wednesday published a two-page missive by Lior Kay
from Tel Aviv who called for an end to rioting, criticized Arab
extremism and asked Palestnian children to write to him.
   In response, the newspaper received several letters from Arab
children and phone calls from interested Israelis, Hallak said.
   One Arab youth, 12-year-old Salam Ismail Obeidat from Jerusalem,
appealed for an end to violence by Israel's army. His letter is to
be published Friday.
   In his letter Wednesday, the first by an Israeli to be published
in An Nahar, Kay wrote:
   ``I like the Palestinian people, and I understand the reason of
your anger, which is your refusal of the occupation, and which is
your right to refuse live under it.
   ``Through your newspaper, I'm asking the representatives of the
Palestinian people and the Palestinian children to stop violence
and start negotiations.
   ``I want to point out that extremists among your people were a
reason for right-wing extremists among our people. Your rejection
of the occupation does not have to harm the Israeli children, and
pregnant women...
   ``You have the historical right and we also a historical
right...,'' Kay wrote.
   Responded Obeidat:
   ``I reject the occupation because it stole my land, my freedom
and my school.''
   ``I don't think when I ask for my freedom and my state that I am
commiting a violent act or being an extremist. If you, Lior, were a
Palestinian boy I think you probably would have fought the
occupation as the Palestinian kids are fighting.''
   ``We are not the reason for your suffering, Lior. This is not
our fault. But you are the reason of our suffering. This is your
fault.''
   Obeidat said Israelis who returned to their ancient homeland had
not been considerate of the Palestinians living on the same land.
   ``When you came back to live beside us what is the gift which
you brought for me, an airplane, a tank, a gun and tear gas bombs?
Is that a peaceful offering from a peaceful child, Lior?
   ``I am asking the Jews ... to quit using physical force, weapons
and tear gas which kills love and peace and innocents like me and
like you.''
   ``This is the only way to build the bridges for peace and love
between our nations and to build a peaceful state.''
</TEXT>
