<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0749,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Declines to Criticize Jackson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Add 2 final grfs with du Pont meeting bgng ``Later Bush...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush declined Thursday
to criticize Jesse Jackson, saying it would be ``a little
arrogant'' for him to assail a potential Democratic presidential
rival at this point in the campaign.
   Bush, apparently on his way to the Republican nomination, would
not bite at reporters' questions about whether he agreed with
President Reagan's assertion on Wednesday that some people are
reluctant to criticize Jackson because he is black.
   ``I haven't started punching any of the Democrats,'' Bush
replied when questioned during a picture-taking session with Costa
Rican President Oscar Arias Sanchez at the White House.
   A day before, Reagan, who has remained officially neutral in the
Republican Party presidential race, took a swipe at Jackson, a
major contender for the Democratic nomination.
   Answering a question during his appearance before the American
Society of Newspaper Editors, Reagan said he hoped that ``race will
not be a part of this campaign in any way.''
   ``I have to believe that a great many of us would find ourselves
in great disagreement with the policies that he (Jackson) is
proposing, and would perhaps be more vocal about them if it wasn't
for concern that that be misinterpreted into some kind of racial
attack,'' the president said.
   Bush said that his preference was to ``wait until there is one
slow-moving target out there.''
   ``And I have decided that it would be a little arrogant,
somewhat presumptuous, to involve myself in the Democratic side of
this thing,'' the vice president said.
   ``They're working hard. I give them credit for that,'' Bush
said. ``I'm trying to do the same thing myself on our side, and we
would have been quite resentful if any one of them had started
singling out a Republican for criticism. That's what the general
election is about.''
   Bush said ``there will be plenty of time for that. So I've not
been involved in going after Jesse Jackson or Mike Dukakis or Al
Gore or the others.''
   ``You'll see a hard-hitting, tough in my view, close election in
the fall,'' Bush said. ``But the American people are going to have
a clear choice. The issues that they are running on or the
philosophy that they are running on are quite different than what
I'll be running on.''
   Later, Bush met with former former Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont,
who dropped out of the presidential race in February. In response
to questions, Bush said he would make no decisions about a running
mate until after the Democratic convention.
   Du Pont said he would consider accepting the spot if Bush
offered it, but added, ``It is very difficult to directly change
things as vice president of the United States.''
</TEXT>
