<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2152EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RoswellGilbert     04-14 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roswell Gilbert,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Wants to Block Book, Movie Profits for Gilbert's Lawyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida's attorney general asked a
court Thursday to bar a former lawyer for Roswell Gilbert,
convicted of murdering his ailing wife in a so-called mercy
killing, from spending book and movie profits that form part of his
legal fees.
   Attorney General Robert Butterworth cited Florida's so-called
``Son of Sam'' law in a petition to the Broward County Circuit
Court.
   Butterworth is seeking a lien against $45,000 allegedly received
by Joseph A. Varon for an NBC television movie, ``Mercy or
Murder?,'' about the killing, and any other profits from films or
books. Butterworth also wants an injunction barring expenditure of
such monies pending further investigation.
   ``The law says in the state of Florida that a convicted felon
cannot profit from his crime,'' Butterworth said. ``When someone
owes a debt to an attorney or signs over the book rights to their
crime in exchange for a legal fee that is a benefit going right to
the defendant who was convicted. Therefore, we are doing what we
can to get the money back.''
   Varon has been on an around-the-world cruise since January and
isn't due back until Monday, said the secretary in his Hollywood
law office.
   Gilbert, 78, a retired engineer, was convicted of first-degree
murder in 1985 and is serving a life prison term for shooting his
wife, Emily, in their condominium near Fort Lauderdale. He claimed
he killed her to end her suffering from Alzheimer's disease and
osteoporosis, a bone degeneration.
   The Son of Sam law gets its title from the nickname of New York
serial murderer David Berkowitz, whose case inspired a similar law
in that state.
   ``The Legislature did not intend to block felons from profiting
... only to have defense lawyers pocket that money,'' Butterworth
said.
   The law calls for 25 percent of the proceeds from any such works
to go to dependents of the felon, if he has any, and 25 percent to
the victims of the crime or their dependents. The state can recover
prosecution, incarceration and other costs from the remaining 50
percent.
   State investigators have found Varon received $50,000 for the
NBC-TV film, which was broadcast last year starring Robert Young as
Gilbert, and that Varon now is attempting to sell a book,
Butterworth contends.
   He said the investigation showed Gilbert received only $5,000 of
that amount and donated it to a non-profit institution for
Alzheimer's research.
</TEXT>
