<2ND_LINE>AM-Escapee Recaptured,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stacy Recaptured in Columbus; Two Others Still At Large</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE LEACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An escaped murderer who vowed revenge on
those who had helped convict him was found hiding in a closet and
recaptured Thursday by police and federal agents.
   Bobby Dean Stacy, serving a life term in the West Virginia State
Penitentiary for the killing of a Huntington, W.Va., police
officer, offered no resistance, authorities said, when he was
arrested in the apartment of James Kennedy on the city's near west
side. Stacy was being held in the Franklin County Jail, pending his
return to West Virginia to face a charge of unlawful flight to
avoid prosecution.
   The manhunt continued for the two other inmates who, along with
Stacy, used stolen bolt cutters to escape April 3 from the
Mounsdville, W.Va., prison. Tommie Mollohan, 45, and David
Williams, 28, remained at large, although the hunt for Mollohan
narrowed after a sheriff's deputy reported spotting him in Marshall
County, W.Va.
   The FBI said Stacy's friendship with Kennedy led agents and
police officers to the West Rich Street apartment where Kennedy
lived with his wife.
   ``We basically knocked on the door and asked if we could search
it,'' said FBI agent Douglass C. Ogden. ``They let us in.''
   A few moments later, authorities found Stacy hiding in a closet.
He was wearing jeans and a T-shirt, but was not armed.
   Kennedy was taken into custody for questioning and could face
charges related to the escape, Ogden said. Kennedy's wife was not
arrested.
   Stacy, 36, had been convicted of killing a Huntington, W.Va.,
police officer and accused of shooting a Huber Heights, Ohio,
officer and had vowed revenge on those who had put him behind bars,
officials said.
</TEXT>
