<DOCNO> AP880414-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Voinovich-Metzenbaum     04-14 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Voinovich-Metzenbaum,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voinovich Plans Coast-to-Coast Fund-Raisers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Senate candidate George V.
Voinovich, who has criticized the extent of Sen. Howard
Metzenbaum's out-of-state fundraising, is planning his own series
of events outside Ohio to raise money, a campaign spokesman said
Thursday.
   Metzenbaum is seeking re-election to a third full term in
November. He is expected to easily win the Democratic primary
against a little-known opponent, but face a stiff challenge from
Voinovich, the mayor of Cleveland.
   ``The mayor is going to make a prudent number of trips outside
the state for fundraising, but in no way will he be able to match
the pace of Sen. Metzenbaum,'' said Joe Wagner, Voinovich campaign
spokesman.
   ``We never once said we would reserve ourselves to in-state
fundraising,'' Wagner added. ``So I don't see any major change in
strategy. We have made it plain and clear it will take about $7
million for us to run a strong campaign against Sen. Metzenbaum.''
   In a March 31 letter mailed nationally to contributors to The
Republican Senatorial Trust, a GOP campaign fundraising
organization, Voinovich wrote that he will not let Metzenbaum
``dominate'' him in out-of-Ohio fundraising.
   Voinovich events were set for Thursday night in Pittsburgh and
Friday in St. Louis and Houston. Other cities where Voinovich
events are planned or being planned include Atlanta, Baltimore, New
York, Los Angeles, Chicago, San Francisco and Seattle, Wagner
confirmed.
   In a campaign stop Wednesday in Cincinnati, Voinovich said he
will come ``nowhere near'' matching Metzenbaum in percentage of
funds from outside Ohio.
   ``If he criticizes me for raising money outside Ohio, it will be
a classic case of the pot calling the kettle black,'' Voinovich
said.
   Voinovich had previously asked Metzenbaum to agree to a campaign
spending cap of $5 million each.
   ``They didn't do it,'' Voinovich said.
   Metzenbaum is expected to raise at least $10 million for his
re-election campaign.
   ``We have called upon the mayor repeatedly to support the
campaign finance reform act presently in the Senate and he has
refused to do so,'' said Dale Butland, Metzenbaum's campaign press
secretary. ``That bill would also control spending by outside
groups on behalf of candidates, and I don't expect the mayor would
like that.''
   According to Federal Election Commission reports filed earlier
this year, about 70 percent of Metzenbaum's campaign funds had come
from outside Ohio.
   Butland said that when the next round of FEC reports are filed,
the percentage of Metzenbaum funds coming from out-of-state will
have ``reduced substantially.'' Over 10,000 individual Ohioans have
contributed to the Metzenbaum campaign so far, Butland said.
</TEXT>
