<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AbramsPeace     04-14 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abrams Peace,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Dept. Official Makes Peace With Senate Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elliott Abrams, the assistant secretary of
state who has been persona non grata in the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee since it was revealed he lied about secret U.S.
efforts to resupply Nicaragua's Contra rebels, has made peace with
the panel's chairman.
   In a letter to Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., Abrams apologized
for ``misleading'' testimony he gave the committee on Oct. 10, 1986.
   Abrams noted in a March 31 letter to Pell that he previously had
apologized to the House Intelligence Committee for similar
inaccurate responses to questions about U.S. involvement in a
private Contra aid network and about enlisting foreign governments
to aid the rebels.
   Recalling the Foreign Relations hearing, Abrams said, ``My
testimony that day covered much of this same territory, and
accordingly, I want to offer you and through you the members of the
committee the same apology.''
   On Wednesday, Pell sent a two-sentence letter to Abrams saying,
``Your apology is accepted'' and concluding: ``I look forward to
your working again with the committee on important Latin American
issues.''
   During last year's Iran-Contra hearings, it was disclosed that
Abrams' testimony had been wrong. At one point, Abrams told
investigators he didn't level with Congress because he was not
authorized to tell the truth.
   From then on, Abrams _ the administration's chief spokesman on
Western Hemisphere matters as assistant secretary for
inter-American affairs _ ran into credibility problems on Capitol
Hill. Some committees forced him to take an oath of truthfulness
before permitting him to testify, and the Foreign Relations panel
placed a flat ban on any appearances.
   Members of Congress complained bitterly that Abrams' performance
illustrated an aid-at-any-price attitude on the part of the
administration and said they no longer could trust the
administration on anything having to do with Nicaragua policy.
   In an incident March 17, Abrams sought to attend an
administration briefing for senators on a Nicaraguan-Honduran
border incident and was turned away at the door of the Capitol
meeting room by Senate aides.
</TEXT>
