<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hijack 8thLd-Writethru a0761 04-14 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0761,0806</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Negotations To End Hijacking Resume</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to INCLUDE urgent on passenger release;
picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``The hijackers ...; minor editing to
tighten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen holding a hijacked Kuwaiti
jetliner at Algiers airport released one of their hostages today as
negotiations to end the 10-day-old crisis appeared to intensify.
   A man dressed in a white robe came down the stairs of the Kuwait
Airways Boeing 747 at 9:45 p.m. (4:45 p.m. EDT), got into a car and
was driven rapidly across the tarmac to the VIP lounge at Houari
Boumedienne Airport.
   The freed hostage, who was not immediately identified, was
greeted by Kuwaiti officials and hustled inside the building.
   Earlier in the day, a passenger aboard the plane pleaded with
his government to meet the gunmen's demands, saying if it didn't,
all aboard the plane would be killed.
   Algerian mediators and the Shiite Moslem hijackers resumed their
talks for the release of the remaining passengers and crew aboard
the Kuwait Airways Boeing 747 after a suspension earlier in the day.
   The hijackers have demanded that Kuwait free 17 pro-Iranian
extremists convicted of terrorism. Kuwait has rejected the demand.
   The plane was commandeered April 5 on a Bangkok-Kuwait flight
with 112 people aboard. It was first diverted to Mashhad, Iran,
where 57 people were freed. It went on to Cyprus, where two
hostages were killed and 13 released, and flew to Algiers on
Tuesday.
   The hijackers, thought to number five to eight, are armed with
grenades and guns and have threatened to blow up the plane and kill
their hostages.
   A passenger told the control tower today by radio, ``My name is
Ahmed Zayed.'' His words were monitored by reporters. ``Hello.
Hello to my family. I am in good health. I ask the government to
release the 17 Islamic Jihad prisoners. If not, they will kill us
all.''
   The talks had reached an impasse on Wednesday. A ranking
Algerian official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Wednesday that Kuwait's ``intransigence'' had created the
standstill.
   A Cypriot official said the jet was refueled and allowed to
leave Cyprus only after Algeria gave assurances that the remaining
passengers would be freed on arrival there.
   ``Our objective all along was the safe release of the hostages.
We believed we had succeeded in this when the hijackers released
... hostages here, with the rest to be freed in Algiers, according
to the Algerian assurance,'' government spokesman Akis Fantis said.
   There are believed to be about 32 Arab passengers and four crew
members aboard the plane. Three passengers are members of Kuwait's
large royal family.
   Two U.S. congressmen Wednesday asked Secretary of George Shultz
to intervene with the negotiators because one of the hijackers may
also have kidnapped Americans being held hostage in Beirut.
   Sen. Daniel Moynihan and Rep. Louise Slaughter, D-N.Y., cited a
report in the independent Kuwaiti newspaper al-Qabas that said one
of the Kuwaiti jet hijackers may be Imad Mughniyeh.
   They said Mughniyeh may have been the chief kidnapper of
American hostage Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent
for The Associated Press.
   Anderson was kidnapped in Beirut on May 16, 1985, and is the
longest held of 22 foreign hostages in Lebanon. His abductors also
have demanded that Kuwait release the 17 pro-Iranian extremists.
   Al-Qabas quoted unidentified sources as saying Mughniyeh was
believed to have boarded the plane when it stopped in Iran.
   This morning, the blue-and-white plane was moved to the end of a
runway at Houari Boumedienne airport to permit the safe landing of
a plane carrying Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda, who arrived on a
state visit.
   Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid, before greeting Kaunda, met
briefly with Mohammed Al-Osaimi, deputy foreign minister of Kuwait.
   The president was given a message from Kuwaiti Emir Shiek Jabar
Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, according to Algiers radio, monitored by the
British Broadcasting Corp. in London. No details were provided.
   A newspaper in Abu Dhabi said today that an agreement had been
reached for the release of the Kuwaiti hostages.
   Al-Ittihad, quoting unidentified diplomatic sources in Larnaca,
said ``an agreement was signed by hijackers, Kuwaiti, Palestinian
and Algerian officials, for releasing passengers and hijackers in
Algerias in exchanging for reducing sentences against the 17
persons in Kuwait jails.''
   The 17 jailed in Kuwait were convicted for the Dec. 1983
bombings of the U.S. and French embassies there. Kuwait's defense
minister, Sheikh Nawaf Al Ahmed Al Sabah, on Wednesday affirmed his
country's ``unwavering and principled stance of rejecting
blackmail,'' Kuwait's news agency reported.
   Food and water were taken Wednesday afternoon to the jet, which
the hijackers call the ``plane of martyrdom.''
</TEXT>
