<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Panama     04-14 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Panama,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Urges Multinational Effort Against Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee said Thursday the Reagan administration is running out of
plans for ousting Panamanian ruler Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and
is doing little to enlist neighboring countries to turn up the
pressure.
   ``Some of us on the committee feel strongly that we must get
more support from other Latin American countries so it does not
seem as if it's a direct confrontation between Noriega and the
United States,'' said Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., the committee
chairman.
   Pell and others attended a briefing by Pentagon and State
Department officials on the situation in Panama during which
possible further economic sanctions against the country were
outlined, as well as several top-secret, non-economic options.
   ``Mr. Noriega is getting stronger every day that we do
nothing,'' said Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina, the ranking GOP
member of the committee.
   ``He's getting more arms from Cuba, while we're sitting here
talking about what we've done for the banks,'' Helms said in
reference to economic sanctions already in place.
   Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., said there was a consensus among
those at the briefing that ``it is terribly important, although
difficult, to get our Latin American allies to step forward and
play a role. ... As much as they don't want Noriega in power, it's
difficult for them to stand up and be counted in a visible way.''
   Kassebaum said that as the weeks wear on and Noriega remains in
place, the more the United States risks a backlash from the
economic sanctions because of the suffering the sanctions cause for
Panamanian citizens.
   ``It will begin to turn on us and we'll be blamed,'' she said.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said the Reagan administration ``has
been sending divided signals'' that prolong Noriega's tenure.
   ``There is no evidence of a major diplomatic effort'' reaching
out to other Central American leaders or to the internal opposition
inside Panama, Kerry said. ``The way to avoid the use of troops is
to pursue these other measures.''
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., sent a letter to
President Reagan asking that U.S. policy give greater emphasis to
the common hemispheric interest in combatting drugs. Noriega has
been indicted in the United States on drug charges, and has been
accused of turning his country into a haven for drug traffickers.
   ``I believe it is time for the United States to stop going it
alone and to place this serious problem of General Noriega and drug
dealing before the Organization of American States,'' Byrd told
Reagan.
   That theme was taken up by Costa Rican President Oscar Arias
during an appearance Thursday before the American Society of
Newspaper Editors.
   ``If you act unilaterally in Panama, you'll be isolated,'' Arias
said of U.S. policy.
   ``You need to get support from the rest of Central America,'' he
said, adding, ``If you want to punish Noriega, economic sanctions
is not the best answer. You are then punishing the Panamanian
people but not General Noriega.''
   He said the conflict in Panama can only be resolved through
negotiations.
</TEXT>
