<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mail-OrderMinister     04-14 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mail-Order Minister,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused of Hatching Bogus Plot to Frighten Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mail-order minister who claimed his
religious position made his stop-smoking clinics exempt from
licensing requirements has been arrested and accused of fabricating
a plot against city officials, police said.
   Joel Witmer, 45, of Clearwater was charged Wednesday with
threatening a public official, a felony. Bond was set at $50,000
and Witmer remained in the Pinellas County Jail on Thursday.
   He had told police that members of his ``religious cult''
planned to kill three city officials because of his dispute over
the license.
   Police, who put the three officials in protective custody,
eventually concluded there was no such cult and no such plot, said
Capt. Barry Glover.
   According to investigators, Witmer claimed that he unwittingly
released $6,000 to his followers with which they planned to buy
weapons.
   In reality, police said, Witmer hatched the plot and the phone
call ``tip-off'' to police in order to frighten licensing officials
who refused to honor his bid for religious exemption.
   Witmer told police he has a doctorate degree from the Universal
Life Church of Modesto, Calif., a mail-order outfit that once
ordained a dog, investigators said in a statement.
   Several years ago, Witmer was convicted of extortion and
sentenced to two years in prison after another dispute involving
the smoking clinics, but that conviction was reversed on appeal.
   ``I just hope this (arrest) will put a stop to Mr. Witmer's
method of attempting to intimidate people and use threats to get
his own way,'' Glover said Wednesday. ``We are going to ask for
restitution. At one point or another everybody in this division has
worked on this case this past week.''
   Witmer has been at odds with Clearwater officials since 1985,
when an occupational license for his UFS Stop-Smoking Clinic first
became an issue, according to a police affidavit. He conducts the
clinics at various hotels.
   Witmer obtained the license in previous years. But he refused to
renew it this year, claiming he was exempt because of his religious
status. The city would not recognize a religious exemption.
   On April 4, Witmer called police and said three members of what
he described as his own ``religious cult'' planned to kill or
seriously injure city officials because they believed that the city
was harassing Witmer. He said he unwittingly helped the plot by
releasing $6,000 to the conspirators. Witmer promised to try to
stop his followers from harming city officials, but he refused to
identify them until he was held in contempt of court April 6.
   On the way to jail, Witmer named the ``conspirators.'' But the
names he gave were of two Florida State University police officers
who had contact with Witmer during one of his prior arrests.
   In 1976, he told the editors of a Florida State University
campus newspaper that he would ``check into hiring a professional
to rearrange your faces'' because he thought the newspaper libeled
him, according to an arrest warrant.
   The warrant also said during 1976 he threatened the wife of a
professor who told him the university would not renew his
stop-smoking clinic contract. In 1979, his bid to conduct similar
clinics at FSU was again turned down.
   He threatened to kill everyone involved with the rejection and
was convicted of extortion. Witmer was sentenced to two years in
prison, but an appeal court threw out the case, ruling that
authorities erred in their investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
