<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0664 04-14 0865</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0664,0887</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Arab Killed; 12-Year-Old Appeals for Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 3 grafs updating dead to two, picking up 4th graf
`U.N. officials'; inserts 1 graf after 16th pvs `An official' with
report of second death; adds 4 grafs new controversy about Porat
shooting</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers shot two Arabs dead Thursday and
wounded four, including a child who lost an eye, and a 12-year-old
Palestinian wrote an open letter to a Jewish boy saying the
violence kills ``innocents like me and you.''
   A strike called by the PLO to protest mass arrests of Arabs
virtually shut down the the occupied lands and east Jerusalem, but
some Palestinians have begun complaining about the economic pinch
caused by repeated strikes.
   At least 146 Palestinians have been killed since riots began
Dec. 8 in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, according to U.N.
figures, and hundreds have been wounded. An Israeli soldier and a
15-year-old Jewish settler also have been slain.
   U.N. officials in Vienna accused Israeli soldiers of using tear
gas improperly, sometimes causing deadly effects by throwing
canisters into small, enclosed areas, and also indicated Israel
might be using another form of toxic gas. The army denied the
allegations.
   Hospital officials said a 70-year-old Arab woman suffocated on
Wednesday after soldiers threw a tear gas canister into her home.
The army said she died of natural causes.
   Salem Ismail Obediat, who is 12 and lives in an Arab
neighborhood of Jerusalem, wrote to the Arabic-language daily An
Nahar in response to a note it published Wednesday from Lior Kay of
Tel Aviv. The 13-year-old Jewish boy had said he wanted to start a
dialogue with Arab children.
   ``You are the reason for our suffering, Lior,'' Salem's letter
said.
   ``When you came back to live beside me, what is the gift you
brought for me? An airplane, a tank, a gun and tear gas bombs. Is
that a peaceful offering for a peaceful child?''
   ``Quit ... using force which kills love, peace and innocents
like me and you,'' Salem wrote.
   Israeli officials claimed Thursday that the number and size of
Arab protests was declining.
   ``It is clear the level of violence is less but this doesn't
mean the uprising is over,'' said Avi Pazner, an aide to Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, army chief of staff, said protests now
involve only Palestinian activists, ``so when soldiers are forced
to fire, they usually hit the inciters themselves.''
   Israeli military commanders in the West Bank held riot-control
maneuvers in a deserted neighborhood of Nablus and demonstrated a
helicopter that dumps rocks onto Arab protesters. Palestinians say
it has been used for at least two weeks.
   The most serious clash Thursday occurred in the narrow streets
of the Nablus central market, whose shops were closed because of
the strike order.
   Army spokesmen said young Arabs on roofs threw stones and cinder
blocks at soldiers, who opened fire and killed a 24-year-old
Palestinian.
   An official at Al Ittihad Hospital in Nablus identified the
victim as Wael Hassan Asmar and said two other Arabs were wounded.
   Arab reporters said soldiers killed another Palestinian, Nassar
Fahmi al Lidawi, at the Nablus market. The army confirmed the death
and said it was investigating the circumstances.
   In nearby Tulkarm, Mohammed Fuad Taha, 12, lost his right eye
after being hit with a rubber bullet, said an official at Rafidiyeh
Hospital in Nablus. He said a 17-year-old was in critical condition
with a stomach wound.
   At Tekoa near Bethlehem, protesters burned tires and threw
stones at passing vehicles, slightly injuring two Jewish children
in a bus, army radio reported.
   Palestinians padlocked their stores, halted buses and stayed
home from jobs in Israel in response to Leaflet No. 13 issued by
the underground Palestine Liberation Organization leadership.
``Ramallah is a dead city,'' an Arab there said.
   The strike was called ``to protest the collective arrests of our
people,'' the leaflet said. According to Israeli officials, nearly
5,000 Arabs have been rounded up since violence began in the
territories Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967
Middle East war.
   Farah al-Araj, mayor of Beit Jallah, said his city observed the
strike but some Palestinians were ``feeling the seriousness of the
economic strike.''
   ``If no help is given to the people from outside, I think within
one or two months they will get fed up,'' he told Israel radio.
   New questions were raised about the death of Tirza Porat, the
15-year-old daughter of Jewish settlers who was killed April 6 in a
clash with Arabs in Beita, a West Bank town.
   The army said she was hit by a bullet from an M-16 rifle carried
by one of two Israeli guards accompanying Miss Porat and 15 other
teen-agers on a hiking trip. Army investigators said they did not
know who pulled the trigger.
   On Thursday, Israel television cited a police report as saying
it was not known what gun fired the shot because the bullet was not
recovered.
   Some of the other hikers have said they saw a Palestinian point
a Kalashnikov rifle at the girl.
</TEXT>
