<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EconomyGlance     04-14 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Glance,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Widens; Markets React</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade Deficit Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are economic developments Thursday:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TRADE DEFICIT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The monthly U.S. trade deficit expanded by $1.4 billion, more
than 11 percent, in February to $13.8 billion, its second straight
rise.
   Imports increased $2.6 billion to $37.4 billion, led by imports
of electrical equipment and auto and truck parts. Exports also rose
$1.2 billion to $23.6 billion.
   For 1988, the deficit's annual rate is $157.6 billion, below the
record $171.2 billion for 1987 but still worse than the 1986
imbalance of $156.2 billion.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S. STOCK MARKET</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The news of the increase in the trade deficit sent the stock
market reeling. The Dow Jones average fell 101.46 to 2,005.63., its
worst decline since it plunged 140.58 points on Jan. 8.
   Analysts noted the Dow climbed nearly 130 points from April
5-12, anticipating favorable trade news. The report, they said,
wiped out the basis for that rally.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DOLLAR</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plummeted against most major currencies within
minutes of the trade announcement, a tailspin only partially
stemmed by coordinated central bank intervention.
   In London, it cost $1.8755 to buy one pound, up from Wednesday's
rate of $1.8445.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.30 yen to close at 126.15 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 123.60 yen.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSINESS INVENTORIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Growth of business inventories slowed in February, increasing by
only $825 million, or 0.1 percent. The small gain followed a string
of steep increases after the stock market crash.
   The February inventory increase occurred while business sales
climbed 0.6 percent, reversing a 0.5 percent drop in January.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RETAIL SALES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales rose 0.8 percent in March, the government reported
Wednesday, increasing by a seasonally adjusted $1.1 billion to
$130.7 billion.
   It was the fifth consecutive monthly increase and the largest
since December, when sales shot up 1.1 percent.
   The combination of rising sales and slightly rising inventories
pushed the inventory to sales ratio down from 1.54 in January to
1.53 in February. That means it would take 1.53 months to exhaust
inventories at the February sales pace. That ratio is not
considered abnormally high.
</TEXT>
