<DOCNO> AP880414-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2140EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Germany-Trade     04-14 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Germany-Trade,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany Said Doing All It Can To Aid U.S. Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Finance Ministers Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the West German central bank said
Thursday that his country has done all it can to stimulate its own
economy as part of the effort to lower the U.S. trade deficit.
   ``We have the lowest interest rates in the world ... and it
would be irresponsible to pursue more expansionary monetary
policies,'' Karl Otto Poehl told a National Press Club luncheon.
   His remarks came amid turmoil on world financial markets. The
dollar fell and stocks tumbled in reaction to news that the U.S.
trade deficit for February widened by more than 11 percent to $13.8
billion.
   A heated dispute over interest rates last year between Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III and the West Germans has been cited as
one of the contributing factors to Oct. 19 stock market plunge.
   Since that time, world financial leaders have gone out of their
way to stress harmony and coordinated efforts.
   With Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan looking on, Poehl
sidestepped questions at the luncheon about whether the Fed should
tighten the U.S. money supply, which would drive up interest rates
and make the dollar more attractive.
   However, he said West Germany, by keeping its interest rates
low, ``couldn't have done more.''
   Poehl said the Bundesbank's dollar reserves have increased by
$15 billion in the past year to $50 billion and indicated it was
among the central banks intervening Thursday to buy dollars on
world exchange markets.
   ``Today was a day where, I think, we have demonstrated to the
markets our readiness, and our willingness ... in the future,'' he
said.
   Poehl cautioned against overreacting to Thursday's trade deficit
figures.
   ``One should not be confused by a monthly trade figure. That's a
very temporary statistic. The true conditions for more stable
exchange rates are much better than some years ago,'' he said.
   He also said the United States should not expect to be in
equilibrium with every trading partner all the time. He said West
Germany, as an aging nation with a stable population, needs to be a
net exporter.
   Germany's trade surplus with the United States, which was $2.2
billion in the first two months of this year, is far smaller than
Japan's, at $8.5 billion, and less than Taiwan's, at $2.7 billion,
he said.
</TEXT>
