<DOCNO> AP880414-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmlandValues     04-14 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmland Values,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmland Prices Rise for First Time Since 1982</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmland prices are up for the first time in
six years but still are far from returning to the peak levels of
1982, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   As of Feb. 1, the average value of U.S. farmland, including
buildings, was $564 per acre, up 3 percent from a 19-year low of
$548 per acre recorded last year, the department said in its annual
report.
   But the Feb. 1 reading was still down 32 percent from the record
high of $823 per acre in 1982.
   In real terms, allowing for an inflation of nearly 4 percent
last year, farmland nationally dropped again to an average of $288
per acre, down 1 percent from $290 a year earlier. That would be
the lowest since the early 1960s.
   Farmland values vary greatly across the country, and not all
regions or states share in the increase. More than a dozen states
showed a further decline or no gain from a year ago.
   Roger Hexem, a farmland analyst in the department's Economic
Research Service, said there are too many variables _ interest
rates and farm income estimates, for example _ to make a prediction
of a future trend.
   ``It don't think it necessarily follows that they're going to be
higher next year,'' Hexem said in an interview. ``I think there are
just too many uncertainties.''
   Hexem added: ``We just can't put ourselves into the minds of
those who are looking at the markets. One's expectation of what's
going to happen in terms of returns to the land are kind of
peculiar to that individual. And if that individual is more
optimistic than others, then he or she is probably more inclined to
get into the market and bid prices up.''
   The report, which Hexem supervised, noted that U.S. farm income
was a record high in 1987, but ``was enhanced by government
payments equivalent to nearly 30 percent of net cash income.''
   Higher farm income and lower debt improved the equity position
of farmers in 1987, and interest rates averaged lower than in 1986.
However, those rates edged up slightly late last year, the report
said.
   Regionally, the Northeast showed a 9 percent increase in
farmland prices as of Feb. 1, continuing an upward trend that began
in the mid-1940s, the report said. The Corn Belt also rose 9
percent, and the Northern Plains averaged 7 percent higher, the
first advances since the early 1980s.
   ``In both regions, values rose in all states, particularly Iowa
(up 19 percent),'' the report said. ``Minnesota's 14 percent gain
led the Lake States' 7 percent growth, while values were up 6
percent in the Southeast and 2 percent in Appalachia.''
   A 4 percent drop in Louisiana farmland values was offset by
higher prices in other states, which left the Delta states
essentially unchanged for the year.
   ``The upturns in farmland values did not extend to the Western
regions, where most state values continued downward into 1988,''
the report said. ``Regional values were down 3 percent in the
Southern Plains, 2 percent in the Mountain states and 2 percent in
the Pacific region. But the rates of decline were lower than in the
past two years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
