<HEAD>Explosion at American Club in Naples, Five Reported Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with American among dead; picks
up 6th graf pvs, ``The consulate ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An car-bomb explosion ripped through a club
for U.S. servicemen in Naples today, killing five people, Italian
authorities said. A U.S. sailor was among the dead, according to
the Pentagon.
   A U.S. Consulate spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said he had been told five people were killed. Italian media quoted
officials as saying five people died in the blast.
   A Pentagon spokesman in Washington said a U.S. sailor was killed
and four sailors were wounded. Lt. Col. Jim Jannette said the
explosion was the ``result of an apparent car bomb'' near the USO
club.
   An Associated Press photo stringer said he saw two bodies
covered with a blanket at the entrance to the club.
   Consulate spokesman Tim Randall said an investigation is
continuing but that Italian authorities believe the 8 p.m. (2 p.m.
EDT) blast was caused by a car bomb.
   The consulate did not yet know the identities of the dead and
injured and did not know how many were U.S. servicemen, Randall
said.
   The explosion destroyed the inside of the club, ANSA said.
   A police spokesman in Naples said earlier that there were some
dead and between 10 and 15 injured at the United Service
Organizations club.
   Fire officials said the explosion ignited a fire that sent a
dense black cloud of smoke into the sky and caused panic in the
streets nearby.
   The U.S. 6th Fleet is based in Naples.
