<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DEAGuns     04-14 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DEA Guns,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DEA Agents Will Carry More Firepower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal drug agents, starting in Florida, are
getting a big boost in firepower with the issue of semi-automatic
guns to even the odds against drug dealers often armed with Uzis
and Mac-10 machine guns.
   Each of South Florida's 341 DEA agents is being issued a 9mm
Colt submachine gun as well as a 15-shot 9mm sidearm as their
primary, personal weapons, said Jack Hook, a spokesman for the Drug
Enforcement Administration's Miami office.
   Until now, DEA agents have gone into battle carrying six-shot,
.38-caliber handguns and shotguns.
   All 3,000 DEA agents nationwide will get the increased firepower
as soon as possible, Hook said.
   ``The managers of DEA are sick and tired of burying dead DEA
agents who have been killed in gunfights by traffickers who have
outgunned those agents,'' Hook said, noting that five agents have
been killed nationally in the last 14 months.
   The DEA is the first federal agency to issue submachine guns
routinely. Customs and FBI agents still carry .38- and .357-caliber
weapons, Hook said.
   He said agents in cities such as Miami, Los Angeles and New York
with big drug problems are slated to get the guns first.
   He said the Miami division is the first to receive the weapons,
although agents protecting witnesses in Jacksonville for the trial
of reputed drug lord Carlo, said
Luis Caraballo of the governor's task force on immigration. Those
workers picked two-thirds of the crop.
   ``The fear growers have in strawberries is that you need to
replace those 17,000 with about 35,000 people to get the same
production you had before,'' he said.
</TEXT>
