<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1859EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-14 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Drenches Southwest; Cold Descends On Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm system moving in from the Pacific Ocean whipped up surf
and produced scattered showers across the Southwest on Thursday,
while temperatures plunged across the Midwest and Northeast.
   Western Nevada and northern and central California received the
most widespread rainfall from the Pacific storms, which also caused
showers in Oregon, Arizona and New Mexico.
   Rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included an
inch at Fallon Naval Air Station, Nev.; a half-inch at Paso Robles,
Calif., and about four-tenths of an inch at Reno, Nev.
   A winter storm watch was in effect overnight Thursday for the
Southern California mountains, and a snow advisory was issued for
the mountains near Lake Tahoe in Nevada.
   The surf was rough not only along the coasts of Oregon and
Washington state, but also along the North Carolina coast, where a
storm was moving out to sea.
   Rain fell in parts of western New York state and western
Pennsylvania. Cold air near the Great Lakes was expected to produce
snow showers late Thursday.
   A chilly night was forecast across the Midwest, possibly
delaying the start of the growing season across illinois and
Indiana.
   A hard freeze was expected in southeast Nebraska, with
temperatures in the 20s. Forecasters warned that mild weather has
made fruit trees more susceptible to freezing temperatures than
they would normally be in mid-April.
   Cool weather extended from the northern and middle Atlantic
states across the Midwest to the northern and central Great Plains.
Readings were mostly in the 40s and 50s.
   Sunshine and mild temperatures prevailed across the Deep South.
Readings were in the 70s and lower 80s from Georgia across the
lower Mississippi Valley to much of Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 27
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 92 degrees at Cotulla, Texas. The
nation's low Thursday morning was 15 degrees at Williston, N.D.
   Friday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
California across the southern Rockies to western parts of the
southern Plains. Rain showers were expected from New England to the
upper Ohio Valley, with snow showers in the Great Lakes region.
   High temperatures should be in the 60s or 70s across most of the
nation; 80s in Florida and southern Georgia and from southern
Louisiana to much of Texas; 40s or 50s from New England across
Pennsylvania, West Virginia and the Ohio Valley to the upper
Mississippi Valley, and no higher than the 30s in the Great Lakes
region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
