<DOCNO> AP880414-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese-RealEstate 1stLd-Writethru a0822 04-14 0983</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Real Estate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0822,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Calls Members of Real Estate Family in Meese Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs bgng: Accompanied by ... to CORRECT that
Mrs. Bender arrived in afternoon, not morning.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury on Thursday questioned
two members of the Bender family which arranged to pay the wife of
Attorney General Edwin Meese III while leasing office space to the
Justice Department for $50 million.
   The panel, under the direction of independent counsel James
McKay, is investigating whether Meese has violated federal law
through any conflict between his personal financial interests and
his government duties.
   Accompanied by his attorney, Seymour Glanzer, Howard M. Bender
arrived at the grand jury Thursday morning. His wife, Sondra,
arrived at mid-afternoon. He spent more than three hours behind
closed doors. Later, Mrs. Bender was questioned separately for
about an hour.
   Meanwhile, trustees of the Multiple Sclerosis Society said
Thursday that they never voted on the plan to hire Ursula Meese at
$40,000 a year with money donated by the Bender family foundation.
   The Associated Press reported Wednesday that a partnership
headed by Howard Bender won a $50-million lease on Justice
Department offices after the Bender Foundation put up money to pay
Mrs. Meese's salary at the MS society.
   Meese, in Atlanta to attend a drug conference, was asked by a
reporter about the matter but declined to comment. During a stop
later at an Immigration and Nationalization Service center in
Decatur, Ga., he turned aside several questions about the lease
arrangement, saying ``that's not on the subject of immigration.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday that he
knew nothing about the lease but that President Reagan ``still has
full confidence in Ed Meese.''
   MS officials have said that the Bender Foundation, of which
Sondra is president, donated the money in October 1985 to pay Mrs.
Meese for three years. Mrs. Bender and Mrs. Meese are MS trustees.
   Several MS trustees said they first learned about that
arrangement from newspaper accounts in the last two weeks. Others,
however, said the board had been advised earlier.
   Some trustees complained about not hearing earlier, but others
saw no reason for concern. Some acknowledged it was an unusual
arrangement, and all agreed it was not put up for a board vote.
   MS Trustee Susan Sikorski, wife of Rep. Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn.,
said she first learned about Mrs. Meese's salary when her husband
read it in a newspaper March 30 and told her. She said the issue
was never discussed in any board meeting that she attended.
   Another trustee, Remmel Dudley, gave a different version.
   ``I guess you might say it was reported to the board,'' said
Dudley. ``I cannot say that a proposal was put before the board,
discussed pro and con and then a vote was taken, but we were
informed that this had been proposed.
   ``I was pleased. I was told the Benders had this foundation and
they could make a contribution to MS or pay for someone's salary or
designate for a specific purpose. We were delighted to know she
(Mrs. Meese) would be a full-time employee because she's a worker.''
   The board meets quarterly and not all the trustees attend each
meeting.
   Attorney Bryan Barkley, also a trustee, said, ``I don't recall a
discussion at a board meeting about'' the plan to hire Mrs. Meese.
   He said, ``It is not normal to earmark a grant for the salary of
a specific person. That's a little unusual.'' But he added, ``It's
not necessarily something the board would get into to vote on or
ratify.''
   Another long-time trustee, who spoke on condition she not be
identified, said she never missed a meeting but,``When I read the
article in the paper, I was shocked ... I was aghast when I saw
it.''
   She said she had no idea Mrs. Meese was paid as MS development
director and thought the attorney general's wife served solely on
the board as a volunteer.
   MS society attorney James Bierbower said the arrangement was
brought up in October 1985 at a special meeting to discuss
expansion of Operation Job Match, a program to help MS victims find
work. Mrs. Bender was at the session, he said.
   McKay has subpoenaed records of Mrs. Meese's job at the society.
   He also is known to be interested in a $50-million lease renewal
won by a partnership headed by Bender after Mrs. Meese got her job.
Most of the offices in the lease were occupied by the Justice
Department's Immigration and Naturalization Service, which had
complained about the building's maintenance, size, location and
security.
   Renewal of the lease in May 1987 was crucial to the sale of the
building 13 days later for $22.6 million more than it cost the
Bender partnership just two years earlier, according to the new
owner and public records.
   The Bender partnership had bought the building in March 1985 for
nearly twice its assessed value at a time when the government
wanted to move more than a third of its offices elsewhere.
   Three months after the Bender partnership purchased the
building, the Reagan administration disclosed publicly that it had
decided to remain in there.
   An attorney for the Meeses denies any wrongdoing on their part
in the transactions, but acknowledges that the Benders and Meeses
know each other. The Benders refuse to discuss the matter. A key
government official said Meese played no role in the real estate
decision.
   Other Bender buildings have done business with the Justice
Department. Government documents show that Howard Bender and his
two brothers, Morton and Stanley, as a partnership, signed a lease
in June 1985 to give the government more space in a downtown office
building, One McPherson Square, where it has leased several floors
since 1971.
   The Justice Department occupies part of one floor there.
</TEXT>
