<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Iraq     04-14 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Fires 3 Missiles into Iranian Cities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said it fired three missiles into
Iranian cities Thursday in retaliation for an Iranian rocket that
hit Baghdad the night before.
   Iraq also reported air raids on Dezful and Hamadan in western
Iran.
   The official Iraqi news agency said the missiles hit Tehran, the
central city of Isfahan and Qom, seat of Iran's Shiite Moslem
religious hierarchy.
   Dispatches from Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency
said four civilians were killed and 20 wounded, and two mosques and
several houses or shops damaged by missile explosions and the air
raids on Dezful and Hamadan.
   The Iraqi agency said an Iranian missile hit a residential area
of Baghdad on Wednesday night. Iran said two rockets were fired
simultaneously at the Iraqi capital.
   ``Many civilians were killed and wounded,'' the Iraqi agency
reported.
   Iran and Iraq, which have been at war since September 1980,
began firing missiles at each other's cities since Feb. 29 and
hundreds of people have been killed. Iraq has reported launching
123 rockets and Iran has said it fired 57 into Baghdad.
   Kurdish guerrilla leader Jalal Talabani reported heavy fighting
between his men and Iraqi troops deep inside Iraq.
   Talabani, leader of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, said the
main areas of battle were at Tuz, a city on the main road between
Baghdad and the northern oil city of Kirkuk, and around a town 30
miles east of Kirkuk.
   Iraq did not comment. Kurdish guerrillas have been fighting for
independence from Iraq for decades.
</TEXT>
