<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bosch-Parole     04-14 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bosch-Parole,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parole Commission Says Bosch To Be Freed to INS or Paroled into
Community</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal parole commission Thursday said
anti-Castro militant Orlando Bosch would be either released into
the custody of immigration officials on May 16 or paroled into the
community on June 16.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service says
it still plans to institute proceedings to deport Bosch from the
United States.
   Bosch, a Cuban native, came to the United States in the 1960s
and lived in the Miami area. He never became a U.S. citizen.
   Bosch entered the United States illegally in February after his
release from a Venezuelan prison, and he has been detained at the
Metropolitan Correctional Center in South Dade, Fla., for violating
the terms of his parole.
   Four members of the parole commission said Bosch will be
released into the custody of the INS on May 16 if the immigration
service exercises its option to detain him. If the INS doesn't
exercise that option, he would be paroled into the community on
June 16 and would be on probation through 1992.
   Regardless of when or under what conditions he is released, the
INS plans to seek to have Bosch deported, said Duke Austin, an
immigration service spokesman.
   During any exclusionary proceedings, Bosch could be detained by
immigration officials, released on bond, released on his own
recognizance or released into the custody of family or someone else
in the community, Austin said.
   Austin said the INS had made no decision on where Bosch would be
deported if such action were approved.
   Deputy INS commissioner Mark Everson had said earlier this year
that the agency would go forward with proceedings to deport Bosch
because the United States opposes terrorism no matter who the
target is.
   Bosch, 61, was convicted of conspiring to bomb foreign
freighters and of firing a recoilless rifle in 1968 at a Polish
freighter docked in Miami. He served four years of a 10-year
federal prison sentence in the United States and has acknowledged
violating his parole when he traveled to South America in 1974. He
served 11 years in Venezuelan jails until his acquittal on charges
of bombing a Cuban jetliner in which 73 died in 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
