<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Sabotage     04-14 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Sabotage,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Saboteurs Blew Up Ammunition Dump</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq said
Thursday saboteurs caused the ammunition dump explosion that killed
at least 96 people, and denied the weapons were destined for
guerrillas in neighboring Afghanistan.
   ``My personal assessment is that it couldn't be anything but a
very effective way of sabotage,'' Zia told reporters during an
informal briefing at the presidential palace. In previous comments,
Zia had not ruled out an accidental explosion.
   He said ``somebody who is not in line with us,'' was responsible
for a series of blasts at the dump between Islamabad and Rawalpindi
last Sunday that caused rockets and grenades to rain on both cities
for more than half an hour.
   Zia would not elaborate, explaining: ``I don't want to hurt the
inquiries'' being conducted into the explosion.
   Although the official death toll stands at 96, scores of people
still are listed as missing. More than 1,000 were reported injured.
   In rejecting reports that the weapons were meant for Afghan
guerrillas, he said the dump was used only by Pakistan's army.
   After the explosion, witnesses said they saw burning trucks with
Afghan license plates near the site.
   Pakistan has been a conduit for foreign military aid to Afghan
guerrillas, who have headquarters in Pakistan. The United States is
one of the countries that has supplied the rebels.
</TEXT>
