<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     04-14 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Race Issue Was Raised During Campaign In North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic hopeful Jesse Jackson denounced
President Reagan, New York Mayor Ed Koch and others for making race
and religion issues in the presidential campaign, saying they are
``making hysteria while I'm making history.''
   The preacher-turned-politician read a lengthy speech Thursday to
the annual meeting of the American Society of Newspaper Editors in
which he expounded his ``Jackson Doctrine'' of foreign affairs.
   ``The next president must know the world and have a realistic
understanding of our possibilities,'' Jackson said. ``Our policy
must be changed. ... We must change our course or lose our way.''
   He called for ``a new realism'' in U.S. policies and a halt to
the race to modernize the superpowers' nuclear arsenals.
   Jackson then moved back to the rhetoric he uses so well in
answering questions from the editors and later from reporters.
   Asked about those who say the nation is ``not ready for a black
president,'' Jackson said such conclusions are the result of
``journalistic incest'' among those who have not gotten out among
Americans to learn how much the nation has grown.
   ``We went across the South on Super Tuesday without a single
catcall or boo, without a single ugly sign at a mass meeting,''
Jackson said.
   Then he launched his criticism of those who have raised race in
advance of Tuesday's New York primary.
   ``It was not until we got north to New York that the litmus
tests of race and religion became spouted from the mouths of public
officials without a significant media challenge,'' Jackson said.
``...Then joined in yesterday by the president and then joined in
today by Ms. (Geraldine) Ferraro.''
   ``I simply say some people are making hysteria while I'm making
history,'' Jackson added later at a news conference.
   Koch, who endorsed Jackson rival Sen. Albert Gore Jr. on
Thursday, said recently that Jews would ``have to be crazy'' to
vote for Jackson because of his positions on Israel.
   Reagan told the editors on Wednesday that Jackson has been
spared criticism because of the fear that comments would be
interpreted as ``some kind of racial attack.''
   ``That's a statement of trauma,'' Jackson told reporters after
the editors' speech. ``President Reagan no doubt feels the pressure
of our campaign.''
   In a speech on Wednesday night, Ms. Ferraro lauded Jackson but
added that if he ``were not black, he wouldn't be in the race.''
The former Democratic candidate for vice president said Jackson
could win neither the nomination nor the general election.
   In his foreign policy speech, Jackson said that as president he
would impose a nuclear warhead testing and missile testing
moratorium to start the process toward major reduction in both
nuclear and convention forces.
   He denounced the Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative as an
expansion of the arms race, saying, ``If Star Wars takes it to the
heavens, it may soon become literally lunatic.''
   Jackson said his ``Jackson Doctrine'' has four basic principles:
   _Support for international institutions and respect for
international law.
   _Recognition for the right of self-determination for the
``struggling peoples of the Third World.''
   _Support for human rights.
   ``Gross and repeated violators of human rights should not be
recipients of U.S. aid or of trade preferences,'' he said.
   _The United State must be a force for economic growth and
justice.
   ``We will not succeed as an island of affluence in a sea of
misery and we will pay a heavy price for trying,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
