<HEAD>Kudos To Castro For Kicking Habit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fidel Castro won an award from the World
Health Organization for snuffing out his famous cigar and setting a
smoke-free example for his countrymen, Cuba's official news agency
said Wednesday.
   Carlyle Guerra de Macedo, director general of the Geneva-based
organization, gave Castro two medals at a ceremony Tuesday in
Havana's Palace of the Revolution, said Prensa Latina in a dispatch
received in Mexico.
   WHO announced the honor on April 7, the first worldwide ``No
Tobacco Day.'' Castro was cited for pledging in 1981 never to smoke
in public and subsequently quitting.
   Castro's cigars once were almost as much a personal trademark as
his beard.
   Guerra de Macedo noted that the medals for Castro's decision not
to smoke and for ``efforts on behalf of public health at a national
and international level'' were the first such honors given to a
chief of state, Prensa Latina said.
   It said the two discussed plans for Cuba's health services and
other health-related issues.
