<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PiedmontLanding 1stLd-Writethru a0736 04-14 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Piedmont Landing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0736,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Piedmont Jet Forced Down By Engine Explosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with minor injuries reported
among flight attendants; picking up 3rd graf, `If somebody...' SUBS
10th graf pvs, `The pilot ...' with two grafs to conform, ADD name
of engine manufacturer and add distance to airport. ADDS 3 grafs at
end with Fokker and Piedmont safety records.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An engine on a Piedmont jetliner
exploded into jagged pieces Thursday, slicing through both sides of
the plane and forcing the pilot to make an emergency landing as
some passengers screamed and fainted.
   Two flight attendants suffered bumps and bruises when the plane
carrying 56 passengers plunged after the explosion, Piedmont
spokesman Don McGuire said.
   Turbine blades ripped through the right rear bathroom and a work
area for attendants as the plane cruised at 31,000 feet.
   ``If somebody had been in the bathroom or the stewardesses'
quarters, they would have been killed,'' said passenger Doug Bruce
of Columbus, Ohio. ``My first thought was, `This is it.'''
   ``It blew a big hole in the plane,'' said passenger Fred Hinton
of Raleigh, N.C., ``I'm 240 pounds, and it was big enough that I
could crawl through it.''
   ``All the kids were screaming,'' Hinton said.
   Piedmont Flight 486 was flying from Charlotte, N.C., to
Columbus, Ohio, when its right jet turbine disintegrated about 9:45
a.m., Piedmont officials said. The plane, a Fokker F-28, has two
engines, one mounted on each side of the cabin.
   The plane, 40 miles south of Charleston, immediately lost air
pressure in the cabin; several passengers later complained of
headaches, earaches and elevated blood pressure.
   ``It began with a wearing noise and loud vibrations about five
or 10 times straight, and then there was an explosion in the back
of us,'' said passenger Rafael Gonzalez of Charlotte, N.C.
   Turbine blades and engine parts ripped through the fuselage,
punching holes in both sides of the plane. A hole on the right
side, adjacent to the engine that disintegrated, was 2 feet wide by
6 feet tall. On the opposite side, the hole was 2 feet by 1 foot.
   The pilot noticed a fire indicator signal for his No. 2 engine,
manufactured by Rolls Royce, and decided to land at Charleston,
where he ``landed without incident'' at Yeager Airport, about 10
a.m., McGuire said.
   Assistant airport manager Dan Huffman said the F-28 was 40 miles
south of Charleston and traveling north when the explosion occurred.
   The plane made a deep descent after the explosion ``but they got
it under control. They all did a good job,'' Hinton said.
   A National Transportation Safety Board investigator was
dispatched to Charleston to investigate, airport officials said.
   Piedmont owns 25 of the German-built F-28 4000s, said another
Piedmont spokesman, Bill Kress. Piedmont uses the jets, slightly
smaller than Boeing 737s or McDonnell-Douglass DC9s, because many
airports in its mountainous region have short runways.
   Charleston's airport, named for test pilot Gen. Chuck Yeager, is
located atop a mountain 2 miles north of the downtown area.
   Immediately after the explosion, oxygen masks dropped from the
ceiling and flight attendants and adult passengers went through the
aisles and assisted children, passengers said.
   But some masks didn't work and passengers had to be moved to
other seats.
   Gonzalez, who was sitting three rows from the rear of the plane,
said a woman in the seat behind him who was traveling with two
children passed out.
   ``She fainted. I turned around and she was blue. The baby was
blue. And her 3-year-old was blue,'' Gonzales said. ``I grabbed her
and put a mask on her, gave the baby to a woman who was sitting
next to her and I took the 3-year-old up with me.''
   About 90 minutes after the emergency landing, most passengers
were placed on Flight 249, a Charleston-to-Chicago nonstop flight
that was diverted to Columbus. However, a few passengers flocked to
rental car companies; they planned to continue their trip by car.
   Before Flight 249 took off for Columbus and Chicago, paramedics
checked the blood pressure of several passengers.
   ``It's a little high,'' Hinton said of his own blood pressure.
``But if I don't get on that plane today, I'll have trouble flying
again.''
   The NTSB has on file only two injury-related accidents involving
Fokker F-28s, said spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz in Washington, D.C.
One jet was involved in a minor taxiway collision in 1985, and in
1986, an unassisted handicapped passenger fell off the boarding
stairs when a guardrail gave way, he said.
   During the past 4{ years, only seven Piedmont flights resulted
in injuries to passengers, the records show. The worst was on Oct.
25, 1986, when a jet overshot a Charlotte runway, causing three
serious injuries and 31 minor ones.
   On Aug. 10, 1968, a Piedmont plane crashed on approach to the
Charleston airport, killing 35 people.
</TEXT>
