<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Afghan 1stLd-Writethru a0745 04-14 0909</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0745,0933</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Get the News on Afghanistan That `We've Been Waiting For'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-8 with 6 grafs to UPDATE with new comments from
Sakharov. Pickup 9th graf pvs ``From the...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet media on Thursday called the Afghanistan
accord in Geneva ``the news we've been waiting so long for,'' but
there was only sketchy mention of the Kremlin's commitment to bring
its soldiers home.
   Radio Moscow used only one sentence to sum up the consequences
of the pact for the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops deployed in
Afghanistan.
   ``It was agreed that the withdrawal of Soviet troops is to start
on May 15, and to be completed within nine months,'' it said.
   Other media reports, including state-run television's top
evening news broadcast, made no reference to the pullout at all.
   Instead, most reports emphasized that the goal of the pact is
the peaceful settlement of Afghanistan's 10-year-old civil war, and
reiterated Soviet backing for the embattled Marxist government of
President Najib.
   Most Soviets, however, would be aware of the implications of the
accords. Communist Party chief Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who has called
the Afghan involvement his nation's ``bleeding wound,'' said last
week that the pullout would begin in mid-May if the U.N.-brokered
Geneva negotiations were successful.
   Soviet leader Leonid I. Brezhnev sent troops into Afghanistan on
Dec. 27, 1979, to preside over the replacement of one Marxist
leader by another.
   They stayed on to help combat a nationwide insurgency in a
military operation that has cost thousands of Soviet lives and
billions of rubles, sparked domestic dissent, and poisoned the
Kremlin's relations with other Moslem and Third World nations.
   Human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov, who was sent into
internal exile for almost seven years after criticizing the
intervention, called the agreement signed in Geneva ``an enormous
event.''
   ``It was a horrible war, a horrible mistake by the Soviet
leadership that had awful consequences for the Afghan people,''
said Sakharov, the 1975 Nobel Peace laureate, who was reached by
telephone at his Moscow apartment.
   ``I am waiting with great impatience for May 15 to see the troop
withdrawal begin,'' he added.
   From the U.S. withdrawal of the SALT II arms control treaty and
the boycott of the 1980 Moscow Olympics by the United States and 61
other nations to the canceling of grain and other trade agreements
involving foreign suppliers, the Soviets paid the price for sending
tanks and troops across the Afghan border.
   A Moscow newspaper editor recently told a Western reporter of
receiving a letter from a man whose only son was killed in
Afghanistan. ``Now the others are coming home,'' the writer of the
letter said. ``But what did my boy die for?''
   The U.S. State Department has estimated Soviet casualties since
1979 at 33,000-38,000, more than one-third of whom were killed.
Those figures do not include ``heavy losses'' to disease, the
department said in a report issued in December.
   The agreement signed by Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
and U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz commits the Kremlin to
ending its military intervention.
   State-run media's initial reporting on the Geneva agreements
seemed designed to assure Soviets that their government's stated
goal of achieving peace in Afghanistan's civil war had been met, at
least in part.
   Shevardnadze, in a statement to reporters after the ceremony,
spoke not of the withdrawal of Soviet troops but of the end to all
outside interference in Afghanistan mandated by the agreements.
   ``The entire spectrum of possible activities and actions to
meddle in the affairs of Afghanistan has finally been blocked,'' he
said, in remarks reported by the official Tass news agency and
shown on Soviet TV.
   ``Outside interference'' has been the term used by Soviets to
describe the aid by the United States and other countries to
Afghanistan's anti-Marxist Mujahedeen insurgents.
   Shevardnadze said he wanted to do ``justice'' to the U.S. role
in bringing about an Afghan settlement, but depicted the Soviet
Union as the major peacemaker.
   The Afghan pact, he said, ``has been predetermined by my
country's policy of solving acute international problems
exceptionally by political means, which has been proclaimed by
Mikhail Gorbachev.''
   ``Vremya,'' the evening news program, made no mention at all
Thursday night of the troop withdrawal.
   The newcast, with an estimated audience of 150 million, began
with reports on the regular Thursday meeting of the ruling
Politburo, the construction of an atomic icebreaker, and private
farming plots in a region of the Russian federation.
   About 20 minutes into the broadcast, ``Vremya'' showed an
eight-minute report on what a correspondent in Geneva called a
``historic event of exceptional international importance.''
   Another newscaster on state-run TV also waxed eloquent in
reporting the agreements, which were also signed by top diplomats
from Afghanistan and Pakistan.
   ``Today in the World,'' an evening program, led off with a
highly unusual editorial comment from anchorman Igor Kudrin, who
told viewers, ``We begin today with news that we've been waiting so
long for.''
   On Feb. 8, Gorbachev said the future political system of
Afghanistan was ``none of our business,'' and stressed that the
Soviet Union had dropped a previous condition that a coalition
government be formed before the beginning of a military withdrawal.
   Shevardnadze on Thursday reiterated Kremlin backing for Najib,
saying what is crucial in Afghanistan is ``every kind of support
for the success of the national reconcilation policy'' proclaimed
last year by the Afghan leader.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
