<DOCNO> AP880414-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham     04-14 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Attorneys Reportedly Seek Deal on Criminal Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham said Thursday he
wouldn't agree to leave the state in exchange for the dismissal of
criminal charges against him, as his lawyers reportedly proposed.
   The former governor, who was removed from office April 4 when
convicted in his Senate impeachment trial, insisted in a radio
interview he did not know about the alleged proposal by two of his
lawyers.
   Mecham, interviewed on KTAR radio, said: ``I would have made no
deal with anybody that I would leave the state for two years. I've
done nothing wrong.''
   ``I'm in the middle of things in Arizona, and I don't plan to go
away,'' the former governor said.
   State Sen. Bill De Long said Wednesday that the two lawyers met
with state Attorney General Bob Corbin in an attempt to get the
criminal charges against Mecham dropped.
   De Long said he understood the meeting occurred last week, but
Corbin would not say whether the meeting took place. Mecham, De
Long and Corbin are Republicans.
   ``Maybe somebody had some conversations,'' Mecham said, but he
added that the lawyers reportedly involved were not those handling
his criminal case. ``I can't say it didn't happen. I didn't know of
it,'' he said.
   Mecham has repeatedly said he expects to be acquitted in his May
19 criminal trial on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
   In a related development, his criminal-case attorney, Michael
Scott, filed a special action in the Arizona Supreme Court seeking
dismissal of the charges on grounds that Corbin manipulated the
grand jury process in seeking the indictment. A lower court judge
had previously refused to dismiss the charges.
   De Long said Mecham's impeachment trial lawyers, Fred Craft and
Jerris Leonard, approached him a week ago and asked him to set up a
meeting with Corbin to discuss the possibility of having the
criminal charges dropped.
   ``It was a dismissal in return for certain concessions on the
part of the respondent, and while I did not hear all of the
details, I did act as an intermediary for a meeting to be set up,''
De Long said.
   Craft and Leonard did not return calls placed to their
Washington, D.C. office.
   Corbin said he would treat Mecham ``just like I treat anybody
else.''
   Scott said he previously had asked Chief Assistant Attorney
General Steve Twist to dismiss some of the counts but that he had
never approached the attorney general with a suggestion similar to
the one made to De Long.
   ``Craft and Leonard did come to me after the Senate trial and
asked what I thought about them talking to someone,'' he said. ``I
told them it was OK with me, but if they were going to the attorney
general's office, I thought it would be a waste of time. For that
reason, I didn't bother going with them.''
   The concessions that Leonard and Craft suggested to him would
include Mecham leaving the state for a two-year Mormon mission,
calling off political backers who are targeting some legislators
for defeat next fall and promising never to run for office again,
De Long said.
   Mecham and his brother, Willard, face charges of fraud, perjury
and filing false documents for failing to report a $350,000
campaign loan from a Tempe developer to Mecham's 1986 campaign.
   In other developments, state Treasurer Ray Rottas said he might
refuse to release state funds for Mecham's impeachment trial
defense. Corbin said he would issue an opinion on whether the
Senate had the authority to agree to pay $202,000 to Mecham's
lawyers.
   The state Senate Government Committee, reversing a stand it took
last year, voted Thursday for a state holiday to honor Martin
Luther King Jr. The sponsor, Democratic Sen. Carolyn Walker, said
that if the bill gets through the Republican caucus to the Senate
floor, she believes both houses would approve it.
   Mecham caused a storm of controversy shortly after taking office
in January 1986 by rescinding a limited King holiday for
executive-branch employees, arguing his predecessor had no legal
right to create it. Although Mecham said he did so on the advice of
Corbin, the action generated an international controversy.
</TEXT>
