<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PuertoRico-Dukakis     04-14 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Dukakis,1st-Ld Writethru,a0707,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 54 Puerto Rico Delegates to Vote for Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds three grafs after lede to give Jackson reaction;
CORRECTS spelling of Agosto in 4th graf pvs: Puerto Rico ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon said
Thursday that he and at least 53 other members of Puerto Rico's
delegation will vote for Michael Dukakis at the Democratic National
Convention because of commitments Dukakis has made to help this
U.S. commonwealth.
   But Jesse Jackson, who won the non-binding beauty contest
primary here, said his campaign would look into the situation and
perhaps challenge the decision.
   ``We do not know all the details behind that. Suffice to say, it
is radically inconsistent in a democracy for the people to go in
one direction and the delegates to go in another direction,''
Jackson told a Washington news conference.
   ``It's premature to respond. We will seek clarity,'' he added.
``There should be a reaonsable correlation between popular votes
and delegates votes in a democracy.''
   Dukakis as president would end discrimination and provide just
treatment in welfare, Medicaid and other federal programs for
Puerto Ricans on this Caribbean island as well as on the U.S.
mainland, Hernandez Colon said at a news conference.
   And if Puerto Ricans vote in a referendum on political status to
reject statehood and keep the current commonwealth form of
government, Dukakis would ``submit to Congress the necessary
measures to strengthen commonwealth,'' Hernandez Colon said.
   Puerto Rico will send 56 voting delegates to the national
convention. The majority decided at a meeting of Hernandez Colon's
Popular Democratic Party last Thursday to endorse Dukakis, Senate
President Miguel Hernandez Agosto said.
   ``No one spoke in favor of Jesse Jackson or Albert Gore,'' said
Cirolo Tirado Jr., the PDP's youth coordinator and a delegate-elect
whose selection will be confirmed at a party caucus on April 24.
   ``It was unanimous in favor of Dukakis,'' said Connie
Carasquillo, a delegate who also attended.
   
   Hernandez Colon and Hernandez Agosto endorsed Dukakis at a news
conference Wednesday in New York. Initially, it was unclear how
many delegates they represented because most either were elected
March 20 on a non-committed slate, or have yet to be formally
appointed.
   Hernandez Agosto said Thursday that most of the 33 delegates
elected last month attended last week's meeting, as did the 18
delegates-elect who formally will be appointed later this month.
   The main issues in the March 20 primary were local. The PDP and
the out-of-power New Progressive Party, which favors statehood,
each submitted their own slates. The PDP, which favors
commonwealth, won in every district. Members of the other party
will have two delegates to the convention.
   A non-binding straw poll was held the same day. Jackson finished
first with about 32 percent of the vote, but Hernandez Colon and
Hernandez Agosto stressed even then that the delegates were not
bound by the results of the poll.
   Hernandez Colon, whose son works in the Dukakis campaign, and
Hernandez Agosto met with Dukakis Wednesday in Boston. Both said
they will campaign this weekend for Dukakis in New York, which has
large Puerto Rican communities. The New York primary is set for
next Tuesday.
   Puerto Rico, located 1,000 miles southeast of Florida, is a U.S.
territory whose residents are U.S. citizens with most every right
and obligation except they cannot vote for president and they pay
no federal taxes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
