<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-TWAHijackTrial     04-14 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TWA Hijack Trial,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Spokesman Says Hamadi Could Get Life from Juvenile Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court spokesman on Thursday
confirmed reports from Washington that a juvenile court could
sentence Mohammed Hamadi to life in prison if he is convicted in
the 1985 TWA hijacking.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Wednesday that
West German authorities had informed American officials a juvenile
court could sentence Hamadi as an adult and give him life, the
maximum sentence, if he is found guilty of murder and air piracy.
   Thomas Kehren, spokesman for the Hesse state court, said the
juvenile court could decide to deal with Hamadi as adult.
   ``The juvenile court in fact has more leeway in handling this
case and sentencing him if he's found guilty,'' he told The
Associated Press in a telephone interview.
   ``If it determines Hamadi was more juvenile than adolescent, the
maximum sentence is 10 years. If found more adolescent than an
adult, 10 to 15 years, and if the court decided he was an adult, up
to life imprisonment.''
   Hamadi awaits trial on charges that he led the June 1985
hijacking to Beirut of TWA Flight 847 during which U.S. Navy diver
Robert Stethem was killed and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17
days.
   On Tuesday, the Hesse state court said it had turned Hamadi's
case over to a juvenile court because there was doubt about his
exact age at the time he allegedly began planning the hijacking.
   West German law defines a juvenile as anyone under 18 years of
age, an adolescent as 18 to 21 years old and an adult as 21 or
over. Personality development and family environment also play a
role in determining what category is applicable, the newspaper
Frankfurt Allgemeine said Thursday.
   Files in the Hesse prosecutor's office give Hamadi's birth date
as June 13, 1964, which would have made him 21 the day the
hijacking began on June 14, 1985.
   Asked how long the juvenile court would study the case before
setting a trial date, Kehren said: ``My guess would be in a month,
maybe a little longer. But to say six months as some have been
asking about is in my opinion way off the mark.''
   The United States asked West Germany to extradite Hamadi on
murder and hijacking charges, but the West Germans turned down the
request and said he would be tried here.
   Mohammed Hamadi's brother Abbas is on trial in West Germany on
charges of kidnapping two West Germans in Lebanon to use as ransom
for the release of his brother. One of the hostages has been freed.
   Both Hamadis were living in West Germany when they were arrested
two weeks apart at the Frankfurt airport in January 1987 on charges
of possessing explosives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
