<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Denies Clanton Stay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court denied the bid of convicted
killer Earl Clanton Jr. of Virginia for a stay of execution
Thursday night.
   The vote was 7-2, with Justices William Brennan and Thurgood
Marshall dissenting, said spokeswoman Kathy Arberg.
   In addition, the court denied a petition for certiorari that
would have led to a rehearing of the case, she said.
   The court acted at 7:50 p.m. EDT on the applications filed about
2{ hours earlier, Ms. Arberg said. The execution was scheduled for
11 p.m.
   Clanton, 33, was convicted of the November 1980 robbery and
strangling of Wilhemina Smith, a school librarian who lived in the
same apartment building where Clanton lived.
</TEXT>
