<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CollegeGrads     04-14 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-College Grads,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salaries Climb For 1987-88 Graduates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum engineers commanded the highest
starting salary among recent college graduates, earning an average
of $33,840, according to a survey issued Thursday.
   The salary level represented a gain of nearly 10 percent since
July, while job offers climbed 36 percent, said the report by the
private, non-profit, College Placement Council.
   ``The college recruiting picture for 1987-88 continues to look
bright, if average salary offers are an indication,'' the survey
said.
   Only inexperienced master's of business administration
candidates with non-technical undergraduate degrees saw a drop in
salary offers. Their salaries fell 4.4 percent since July to
$30,480.
   Experienced MBA graduates with non-technical degrees received
higher offers, as did inexperienced MBA graduates with technical
backgrounds.
   The average salary offers for mechanical engineers climbed 3.8
percent to $29,388, while the average for electrical engineers went
up 1.4 percent to $29,316. Chemical engineers earned $30,768, a 3.1
percent increase.
   Salary offers for accounting graduates jumped to an average of
$23,700 a year, up more than 9 percent since July. Salaries for
graduates in marketing and distribution rose 2.7 percent to $20,904.
   Banking-finance graduates averaged $21,792, while human resource
graduates averaged $19,212, about the same as in January.
   In the allied health field, offers ranged from $19,440 to
$30,000, with an average of $24,660, about the same as in January.
   Salaries for nurses fell slightly since January. In this latest
report, they ranged from $18,996 to $28,368 and averaged $23,604.
   Salaries for computer science graduates rose slightly since
July, for an average of $26,676, but job offers declined 2 percent
from this time last year.
   Computer programmers were offered $20,064 to $30,492 and
averaged $25,944, which represents a slight increase since July.
   Of all job offers made to graduates with bachelor's degrees, 53
percent went to non-technical graduates while 47 percent were
extended to technical graduates.
   Public accounting employers made the most offers to
non-technical graduates, offering 45 percent of their entry level
jobs at an average salary of $24,024.
   The aerospace industry continued to provide the most job offers
to technical graduates, offering 16.5 percent of entry level jobs
at an average pay of $29,280.
   Comparing salaries around the nation, the survey found that New
York City employers offered the highest average salaries to
accounting graduates, $27,408.
   Aerospace engineers commanded the highest salaries of $28,776 in
St. Louis, Mo., while electrical engineers there commanded the
highest average of $30,144. Chemical engineers received an average
salary offer of $31,428 from employers in Houston, Texas.
   The College Placement Council represents career planning nd
placement directors of 1,300 U.S. colleges and universities, as
well as the nation's leading corporate and government recruiting
organizations.
   The organization has conducted such surveys for more than 20
years.
   The current survey, which covered the period from Sept. 1 to
March 7, includes several new categories covering different periods
of time, making some comparisons with last year's data impossible,
the organization said.
</TEXT>
