<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Italy-USOExplosion 2ndLd-Writethru   04-14 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-USO Explosion, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0858,0776</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Explosion Reportedly Kills Five People at American Club in Naples</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thout with Pentagon saying 3 sailors hurt,
possibility of military deaths but none confirmed. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb blew up in front of a club for
U.S. military personnel in Naples on Thursday, killing five people
and wounding at least 17, Italian officials said.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the blast
that happened shortly after 8 p.m. (2 p.m. EDT) at the USO club.
   The Pentagon initially reported one sailor was killed and four
injured, but Navy Cmdr. Connie Haney later said authorities in
Naples could not confirm any U.S. military deaths. He said three
sailors were hurt.
   Italian media quoted officials as saying three men and two women
died in the blast. Witnesses said one of the bodies at the entrance
of the club was draped in a U.S. flag.
   Italian hospital officials said at least four Americans were
among the injured.
   Italian media said the bomb exploded during a reception at the
club for the commander of the USS Paul, a torpedo boat destroyer
docked in Naples. A U.S. Consulate official could not confirm the
report.
   Passers-by screamed and ran when the explosion occurred outside
the club, which is in one of Naples' busiest areas.
   ``It was a huge boom and we were all knocked to the ground. When
we got up, all we could see was flames everywhere,'' an
unidentified Italian woman told the state-run RAI television
network from her hospital bed.
   ``We can confirm there are no fatalities from the three ships in
port,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Chris Baumann, a Pentagon spokesman, adding
that there was a possibility that ``there could be a sailor dead
from the local command,'' although he knew of no such death.
   The ships were the USS Paul, based in Mayport, Fla.; the USS
Capodanno, with a home port in Newport, R.I.; and the USNS Kaiser,
a fueling vessel with no specific base, the Pentagon said.
   Two crew members from the USS Capodanno and one from the USS
Paul were being treated for injuries in Naples, Haney said in a
statement. One crew member from the Capodanno was treated and
released, it said.
   The Pentagon did not immediately release the names of the
injured.
   The initial report of a dead sailor was the result of confusion
following the blast, Haney said.
   A spokesman for Pellegrini Hospital said 14 of the wounded,
including four Americans and eight Italians, were taken to a
hospital.
   The spokesman, who spoke on condition he was not identified,
said the Americans later were sent to a U.S. military hospital. He
said he had no details on the extent of the injuries.
   RAI said one of the wounded, a 27-year-old Italian woman, was
reported in grave condition.
   It said 60 to 70 people were inside the club at the time of the
explosion.
   ``The entire scene is apocalyptic,'' said Naples Mayor Pietro
Lezzi, as he surveyed the damage.
   Antonio Barrel, the inspector general of public security in
Naples, told the Italian news agency ANSA that authorities do not
yet know if the car bomb was set by foreigners or Italians.
   But the agency also quoted an unidentified police official as
saying ``the Middle East connection seems most likely.''
   Investigators said Thursday's blast destroyed the inside of the
club and wrecked other parked cars. The bomb apparently was hidden
in a Fiat 127 auto that was ripped apart by the explosion.
   The USO club is just off Piazza Municipio, about 200 yards from
the Naples waterfront.
   Italian media noted the blast occurred almost exactly two years
after U.S. warplanes attacked Tripoli and Benghazi in retaliation
for alleged Libyan involvement in the bombing of a nightclub in
West Berlin that killed an American soldier.
   A USO club in Barcelona, Spain, was attacked Dec. 6 by an
attacker with hand grenades who shouted ``Long live Lebanon.'' The
blasts killed U.S. Navy Petty Officer Ronald C. Strong and injured
nine other people.
   The Navy has a major presence in Naples, the headquarters for
NATO's southern command and the support center for the 6th Fleet.
   About 45 ships, 200 aircraft and more than 23,000 people make up
the fleet, which is deployed in the Mediterranean.
   Most 6th Fleet ships come from ports on the U.S. East Coast to
spend six months in the Mediterranean. A small number have home
ports in Naples and La Maddalena, Sardinia, according to the Navy.
</TEXT>
