<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua     04-14 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas, Contras Iron Out Differences On Renewing Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the U.S.-supported Contra
rebels and the leftist Sandinista government said Thursday they had
reached a compromise that would allow cease-fire talks to go ahead.
   The agreement to start high-level negotiations in the Nicaraguan
capital Friday came during the first official visit of Contra
representatives to the capital since the war started more than six
years ago.
   The two sides also resumed stalled talks on technical details of
a temporary cease-fire, such as how to provide the rebels with
humanitarian aid and security.
   Maj. Gen. Joaquin Cuadra Lacaso, chief of staff of the
Sandinista army and head of the government's delegation to the
technical talks, said before the meeting he was confident the two
sides would ``finish discussing the plan'' for implementing the
temporary cease-fire.
   Contra political representatives at the meeting included
Aristides Sanchez, Roberto Ferrey, Bosco Matamoros and Alejandro
Montiel Arguello. The rebels' military delegation included Jose
Benito Bravo Centeno and Juan Rivas.
   In a compromise, the Sandinistas backed off demands that the
technical talks be held in Managua.
   In exchange, the Contras retreated from their earlier insistence
that Friday's high-level negotiations be conditioned on the
successful outcome of the Sapoa talks.
   ``The Contras agreed that if the talks are not finished today
(Thursday), they'll conclude in Managua,'' government Information
Minister Manuel Espinoza said in a telephone interview.
   Two Contra delegates, Ferrey and David Stadthagen, arrived from
Costa Rica in a private plane in the morning to negotiate the
compromise. They were met at Managua's Sandino airport by Tourism
Minister Herty Lewites.
   It was the first time since the war began that the Sandinistas
allowed Contra representatives to set foot in the capital.
   In a brief talk with reporters later, Ferrey confirmed
Espinoza's announcement that a compromise was reached.
   In the technical talks, military representatives from both sides
are seeking agreement on how to implement a provisional cease-fire
accord they signed at Sapoa on March 23.
   The 60-day cease-fire began April 1 even though many issues were
still to be resolved.
   So far both sides have agreed to seven cease-fire zones where
the rebels will gather.
   Two points in the Contra proposal were termed ``non negotiable''
by the Sandinistas. The Contra proposal would allow the combatants
to receive arms and amunition while in the zones and bar the
government from accepting military aid, which comes from the Soviet
bloc.
   According to the March 23 cease-fire accord, the Sandinistas
would permit the rebels to receive humanitarian aid, allow them to
participate in a national reconciliation dialogue and release 700
political prisoners.
   Contra leaders also insisted on freedom of movement to meet with
opposition leaders inside Nicaragua, which the Sandinistas at first
refused. The government later said the rebels would be permitted to
meet with Roman Catholic Church leaders and visit La Prensa, the
country's only opposition newspaper.
   The cease-fire talks are within the framework of a regional
peace initiative signed by the presidents of five Central American
countries including Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
