<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CommercialActors     04-14 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commercial Actors,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Leaders Vote To End Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of two actors' unions voted
resoundingly to end a strike that virtually halted production of
new radio and TV commercials for more than three weeks, officials
announced Thursday.
   The Screen Actors Guild and the American Federation of
Television and Radio Artists boards voted 123 to 29 to approve a
tentative three-year contract, said SAG spokesman Mark Locher.
   The vote Tuesday and Wednesday must be ratified by the 100,000
members of the two unions, but the strike is being suspended as of
Friday morning, Locher said.
   The unions will mail contract terms and ballots to members next
week recommending approval of the contract, he said. The final
votes are due back May 20.
   ``We feel that we achieved the most important principal behind
the strike and that was establishing payment for the cable use of
commercials which used to be free,'' Locher said.
   Other terms of the contract, Locher said, include a 10 percent
increase in minimum session fees, raising payments from $333 to
$366 for an eight-hour workday; a 13.5 percent increase in radio
commercial rates for AFTRA members; and an increase in
contributions by producers to performers' health and pension plans.
   Bob Stephens, vice president of the western office of the
American Association of Advertising Agencies, said Thursday
afternoon that he had not yet been notified of the settlement.
   ``I'm sure the (advertising) agency community will be
thrilled,'' Stephens said.
   A call seeking comment from the association's New York
headquarters went unanswered Thursday evening.
   The strike, which began March 21, virtually halted production of
new commercials, but ads continued to be broadcast because typical
contracts between advertisers and actors allow use of the product
for up to 21 months.
   Commercial work accounted for payments of $417 million to actors
in 1987, about half the total paid for acting of all kinds.
</TEXT>
