<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0813 04-14 0946</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0813,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Denounces Racial Litmus Tests: Dukakis on Top in New Poll</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 13 grafs to update with New York debate; picks up
4th graf pvs, ``Jesse, Jesse...; edits to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. on Thursday renewed his attack on
Democratic presidential rival Michael Dukakis for his statement
about use of nuclear weapons in the event of a Soviet invasion of
Europe. Dukakis told Gore: ``Give me a buzz and I'll tell you
exactly what I said.''
   Gore, Dukakis and Jesse Jackson met in a one-hour debate in New
York City that served more to highlight their similarities than
their differences.
   Except for the exchanges between Gore and Dukakis on nuclear
weapons, the forum, sponsored by WCBS and Newsday was a low-key,
gentlemanly encounter in which the candidates appeared determined
to avoid the sharp clashes that have marked the New York primary
campaign.
   Earlier in the day, Jackson denounced ``litmus tests of race and
religion ... spouted from the mouths of public officials'' as one
official, New York Mayor Edward Koch, endorsed Gore.
   Meanwhile, polls put Dukakis on top, with Jackson trailing and
Gore at the bottom in the battle for survival in Tuesday's New York
primary.
   During the debate, Gore was asked if there were any
circumstances under which he would consider using nuclear weapons.
The Tennessee senator used the occasion to renew his criticism of
Dukakis for saying in a newspaper interview that he would reserve
his option to use nuclear weapons in the event of a Soviet invasion
of Europe.
   ``This is a serious mistake'' said Gore, referring to the
Dukakis statement. ``It has never been done'' by presidents or
presidential candidates.
   ``Was that an answer to your question?'' Dukakis asked the
moderator.
   Jackson said there was ``a real danger in those of us who may
very well lead our country to get trapped into a hypothetical
situation on who will shoot your gun first and destroy the whole
world to prove that you got macho.''
   When Gore raised the issue again later in the debate, Dukakis
said: ``Don't pick up the morning newspaper and then have a press
conference. Give me a buzz and I'll tell you exactly what I said
and there'll be much less confusion.''
   Even on Middle East policy, which has produced sharp differences
during the New York campaign, the candidates concentrated on their
areas of agreement.
   Meanwhile, Republican nominee-to-be George Bush, keeping to a
low-key campaign schedule, ran into a wave of enthusiasm for
Jackson among Washington toddlers.
   ``Jesse Jackson, Jesse Jackson, Jesse Jackson'' the children
chanted after a reporter shouted a question to Bush about Jackson
during the vice president's visit to a Labor Department day care
center.
   With the focus on the New York primary, Koch stepped into the
spotlight Thursday afternoon to announce his endorsement of Gore as
``a man of intellect, courage and integrity.'' He said, ``Gore is
head and shoulders above his rivals'' on Israeli issues.
   Dukakis reacted mildly to the endorsment, saying in Boston, ``He
likes us both.'' And Jackson said, ``What he has done by choosing
someone is positve and fair and proper.''
   But Jackson's tone was quite different when he lashed out at
Koch, President Reagan and former Democratic vice presidential
candidate Geraldine Ferraro for what he called ``race-based
questions.''
   ``We went across the South on Super Tuesday without a single
cat-call or boo, without a single ugly sign at a mass meeting,''
Jackson told the American Society of Newspaper Editors in
Washington. ``It was not until we got north to New York that the
litmus tests of race and religion became spouted from the mouths of
public officials without a significant media challenge.''
   ``There are those who are making race-based statments
unfortunately _ whether Mr. Reagan or Mr. Koch or Ms. Ferraro,''
Jackson said to reporters. ``I simply say some people are making
hysteria while I'm making history.''
   Koch said recently that Jews would be ``crazy'' to vote for
Jackson because of his positions on Israel.
   Reagan told the editors on Wednesday that Jackson has been
spared criticism because of the fear that comments would be
interpreted as ``some kind of racial attack.''
   In a Wednesday night speech, Ms. Ferraro lauded Jackson but
added that if he ``were not black, he wouldn't be in the race.''
She said he can't win the nomination nor the general election.
   The news from the New York polls was good for Dukakis and
improving for Jackson but bad for Gore.
   Dukakis led Jackson by 45 percent to 28 percent in a CBS News
poll, 46 percent to 34 percent in a Marist College poll and 49
percent to 34 percent in an ABC News-Washington Post poll. Gore had
only 8 percent support in two polls and 7 percent in the third.
   Among likely Democratic primary voters, surveyed Monday and
Tuesday by the Marist College Institute for Public Opinion, Dukakis
had the support of 46 percent, Jackson 34 percent, Gore 7 percent
and ``uncommitted'' 5 percent. Eight percent of those polled were
undecided. The poll of 359 people had a potential sampling error of
5 percentage points either way.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis picked up the support of at least 54 of
Puerto Rico's delegates to the Democratic National Convention in
July. That gave Dukakis a gain of 74 delegates in the past seven
days as he continued to pick up strength among the party's
unpledged ``super delegates.''
   The latest AP delegate count gave Dukakis 816.15 to 715.1 for
Jackson. Gore trailed with 404.55, while uncommitted delegates
totaled 474.75. Sen Paul Simon of Illinois, whose campaign is on
hold, had 173.5.
</TEXT>
