<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-WillieBrown Adv17   04-14 1057</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Willie Brown, Adv 17,1085</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaign Chairman Faces Revolt on Home Front</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These are the best of times and the
worst of times for Willie L. Brown Jr., the flamboyant speaker of
the California Assembly and national chairman of Jesse Jackson's
presidential campaign.
   They are heady times for Brown as the Jackson campaign continues
to exceed expectations and Jackson emerges as a serious contender
for the Democratic nomination for president.
   They are also tough times for Brown as he is under siege as
never before on his home turf, in the halls of the state Capitol,
where his 7{-year rule of the Assembly is in danger.
   Brown voices quiet confidence in both arenas. In the Jackson
campaign, he modestly understates his current role or potential
influence at the Democratic National Convention. In California
political circles, his public calm conceals a desperate battle to
hold his powerful office.
   Brown's appointment as Jackson's national chairman last November
was widely reported as a major boost to Jackson's campaign.
   As the black leader of a predominately white legislative body
and as a pre-eminent fund-raiser for California Democrats, Brown
was seen as someone possessing the political skills, prestige,
experience and contacts Jackson needed most to broaden his
constituency among white political leaders and voters.
   That's exactly what has happened to the Jackson campaign. And
while Brown publicly gives all of the credit to Jackson, his
influence in the campaign appears strong, and Brown is increasingly
being viewed as a key player in picking the next Democratic nominee
if the convention becomes deadlocked.
   Brown, who originally backed New York Gov. Mario Cuomo for the
1988 nomination, acknowledges that he was initially attracted to
the Jackson campaign as a vehicle to ``get in the room'' of major
players who would pick the Democratic nominee if the convention
deadlocked.
   ``I need to get a horse with 1,000 chits (delegates) to get in
the room. Jesse looks like my best agent,'' the Washington Post
quoted Brown as saying a year ago.
   Brown confirmed that quote earlier this month, but said ``I'm
beyond that now,'' and that his goal is ``trying to secure the
nomination for Mr. Jackson.''
   ``I've been there once, (in the inner circle picking a
presidential nominee) and I'm going to be back,'' Brown said,
referring to 1972, when he co-chaired the California delegation
which was key to winning the nomination for George McGovern.
   Brown claims to have raised $1 million for Jackson, a good chunk
of the candidate's overall treasury. And he talks regularly by
telephone to Jackson, a compulsive caller.
   But while Brown's potential influence on national politics is
greater than ever before, his political base is Sacramento is
crumbling.
   The 54-year-old Brown, who was raised in a one-room house in
racially segregated Mineola, Tex., hitchhiked to San Francisco
after high school and worked as a janitor while living with an
uncle and attending college and law school.
   He started a storefront law practice in 1959 which, by his own
description, was primarily ``pimps and prostitutes,'' and became
active in civil rights demonstrations. Within five years, Brown,
then 30, had won a seat in the state Assembly.
   By 1971, Brown was chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, a
powerful fiscal post which paradoxically made Brown nominally the
legislative author of then-Gov. Ronald Reagan's state budgets.
   Then, in a 1980 coalition with the Republican minority, Brown
defeated two other Democrats to become Assembly speaker, an office
which the late Jesse Unruh had transformed a decade earlier from a
ceremonial presiding officer's job into a fund-raising and
policy-making post second in influence only to the governor.
   The speaker's office, replete with both the subtle and overt
trappings of power, fit Brown like a glove.
   His wit and flamboyant style made him an instant success as a
fund-raiser, helping him raise up to $5 million annually for other
Democrats, thereby cementing his hold on the office and freeing him
from dependence on a coalition with Republicans.
   Being speaker, Brown said, was like being ``the Ayatollah of
California,'' with power to set the legislative agenda and assign
or remove colleagues from legislative committees.
   It also gave him an office in the Capitol he describes as
``bigger than my home town,'' which matched nicely the taste for
lavish parties, $1,000 suits and $100,000 sports cars which Brown
acquired as his private law practice has evolved from criminal to
corporate.
   But as the Democratic majority in the 80-seat Assembly has
slipped under Brown from 47 to the current 44 seats, complaints
grew that his flamboyance and sometimes embarrassing remarks were
hurting Democrats more than his fund-raising was helping them.
   This came to a head earlier this year when five conservative
Assembly Democrats, motivated by a variety of relatively obscure
personal disagreements with Brown, bolted his leadership. Without
their support, Brown retains the title and outward trappings of the
speakership, but without a working majority.
   The five have aligned themselves with Republicans to push
anti-abortion, death penalty and wiretap bills which Brown
previously bottled up in committee, and they have even defeated
routine legislative housekeeping rules backed by Brown.
   Brown at first punished the five, stripping them of most
legislative duties and banishing them to smaller Capitol offices.
More recently, he has ignored or downplayed the defeats, contending
it never was his intent to dictate policy.
   The five dissident Democrats, who hold the balance of power in
the Assembly, say they have no intention now of trying to oust
Brown.
   ``Why should we? We are controlling the policy agenda,'' says
one of the five, Democrat Rusty Areias.
   That means Brown can probably continue to occupy the speaker's
office until the current Assembly session adjourns Aug. 31.
   Brown says he will re-elected speaker next year. But unless he
wins back the five dissident Democrats, his hopes for another term
as speaker depend on either winning at least two more Democratic
seats this year to create a majority not dependent on the five
rebels or forging another coalition with Republicans.
   As Sacramento-based political columnist Dan Walters puts it,
``There is a growing sense in the Capitol that Brown's days as
speaker are numbered. But no one has figured out the number yet.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
