<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessConfidence     04-14 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Confidence,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Leaders' Confidence Rises In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confidence among top business executives in the
U.S. economy following October's stock market crash has rebounded,
according to the Conference Board.
   During the first quarter, the business research group's measure
of business confidence ticked up to 51 after falling to a five-year
low of 47 in the final quarter of 1987, the group said Wednesday.
The measure reflects a scale of 0 to 100.
   More than a third of the 1,000 executives polled said they
expect to have greater problems finding qualified employees this
year than in the previous year. The Conference Board said nearly 20
percent of the executives polled expect employment in their
industries to rise this year, but 29 percent expect job losses.
   Business services and the instruments and primary metals
industries hold the brightest employment prospects, while banking,
gas and electric utilities and the insurance industry are likely to
be hit with job losses, the board reported.
   ``The moderate rise in business executives' confidence parallels
an upturn in consumer confidence during the first quarter,'' said
Conference Board economist Steven Malin.
   ``A strong irony in the latest survey is that all of the
increased optimism revolves around likely business conditions later
this year, not now,'' he added.
</TEXT>
