<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru f0303 04-14 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0303,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Hit New Highs; Dollar Up Marginally</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning stock closing figures,
other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange reached
new highs again on Thursday morning, while the U.S. dollar rose
marginally against the Japanese yen in early foreign exchange
activity.
   The bellwether Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues
climbed for the fourth consecutive day, adding another 67.52 points
to Wednesday's record close to finish the morning session at
27,053.07.
   It was the first time the Nikkei average ever topped 27,000,
surpassing its previous intraday high of 26,988.36 points hit in
early trading on Monday. The Nikkei index has come within five
points of the 27,000 mark in intraday trading three times this
week, but slipped back each time amid the continuing market rally.
   In currency trading, the dollar opened at 126.20 yen, down 0.25
yen from Wednesday's finish, but later edged higher and was
changing hands at 126.35 yen by late morning.
   Fumihiko Morimoto of the investment firm First Boston said the
market was supported by continued strength on Wall Street and
somewhat by the agreement among the seven top industrialized
nations to continue cooperating to keep the dollar from falling
further.
   In a two-page joint communique after a meeting Wednesday in
Washington, the finance ministers and central bank governors of the
seven nations announced the extension of a Dec. 22 agreement in
which they pledged to stabilize the U.S. currency.
   The so-called Group of Seven nations are the United States,
Japan, France, Britain, Canada, Italy and Germany.
   A dealer at a major U.S investment firm, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said the foreign exchange market likely would be
affected more by the release Thursday of U.S. trade figures for
February.
   The U.S. trade deficit has affected the dollar's direction in
recent months because the U.S. administration has supported a lower
dollar as a way of narrowing the gap.
</TEXT>
