<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     04-14 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0350</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market took a sharp drop today, faced
with the surprise news of an increase in the nation's trade deficit.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials tumbled 37.30 points to
2,069.79 in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers swamped gainers by more than 12 to 1 in the early tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 91 up, 1,160 down
and 203 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 32.71 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Before the market opened the Commerce Department reported that
the nation's trade deficit widened to $13.83 billion in February
from $12.44 billion the month before.
   That came as a big disappointment to market participants, who
had been looking for a continued narrowing in the gap between
imports and exports.
   The dollar dropped sharply in foreign exchange markets on the
news, and U.S. credit markets also took the news badly.
   Prices of long-term Treasury bonds fell about $15 for each
$1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the 8.85-8.9 percent
range. Just a few weeks ago government bond yields got as low as
about 8.3 percent.
   Stock-market analysts said persistent strength in imports, in
particular, raised fears that the Federal Reserve might soon feel
the need to tighten credit to restrain the economy as well as to
support the dollar.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines dropped 1~ to 114\; Ford Motor 1] to 45}; General Electric
1[ to 41}, and USX 1\ to 33.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
tumbled 2.53 to 150.67. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 3.58 at 302.21.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average slipped 2.98 to
2,107.10.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 4 on the
NYSE, with 664 up, 811 down and 495 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 185.12 million shares, against 140.40 million in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
