<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold 2ndLd-Writethru   04-14 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Tumbles, Gold Also Down in Early Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to DELETE garble at bottom.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plummeted in Europe today after the
U.S. government reported the American merchandise trade deficit
unexpectedly widened in February.
   Gold prices dropped during the morning session.
   The dollar fell almost two and a half cents against the British
pound, nearly three pfennigs against the West German mark and more
than two and a half Japanese yen after the trade report.
   The tumbling U.S. currency compelled several major central banks
to intervene and buy dollars to cushion the fall, traders reported.
   The merchandise trade deficit widened to $13.83 billion in
February from $12.44 billion in January, the Commerce Department
reported in Washington.
   Economists had expected the deficit to narrow to between $11.2
billion $11.8 billion.
   Dealers said the dollar was not affected by Wednesday's
announcement by finance ministers and central bankers of the seven
major monetary nations that they had reaffirmed their December
commitment to stabilizing exchange rates.
   The move was widely expected and had already been discounted in
the market, dealers said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell marginally to 126.15 yen, closing 0.30 yen lower
than Wednesday. Later, in London, it was quoted at 123.75 compared
126.30 yen in the morning.
   ``The news of the (Group of Seven) meeting was nothing
substantial,'' said a dealer at a major U.S investment firm in
Tokyo.
   Here are dollar rates after the trade report was released, with
midmorning rates in parentheses and compared with late Wednesday:
1.6650 (1.6920) West German marks, down from 1.6895; 1.3745
(1.4010) Swiss francs, down from 1.3983; 5.6510 (5.7385) French
francs, down from 5.7295; 1.8740 (1.8972) Dutch guilders, down from
1.8950; 1,238.45 (1,254.00) Italian lire, down from 1,252.50;
1.2382 (1.2371) Canadian dollars, up from 1.23675.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8675, compared with $1.8420
earlier in the day and $1.8445 dollars late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $446.85 a troy ounce,
down from late Wednesday's $449.25, and at midmorning today the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $447.
   Bullion dealers said trading was quiet as the market waited for
the U.S. trade figures.
   In Zurich, Switzerland, the bid price for gold was $447, down
from $449.50 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.34 to close at a bid $449.48.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.34 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's $6.41.
</TEXT>
