<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Wides Unexpectedly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to update market reaction to trade report
and include business inventories report, picks up 6th grav pvs,
``On Wednesday ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit widened unexpectedly in February to $13.8
billion, its biggest shortfall since October, the government said
today.
   The Commerce Department said the excess of imports over exports
rose $1.4 billion from January's $12.4 billion imbalance.
   The dollar fell shortly after the announcement and on Wall
Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was down about 38 points
to about 2069, reflecting traders' disappointment with the news.
Financial markets had expected the deficit to shrink slightly.
   For the first two months of 1988, the deficit ran at an annual
rate of $157.6 billion, below the record $171.2 billion of last
year but still worse than second highest imbalance of $156.2
billion in 1986, the Commerce Department said.
   Imports of foreign manufactured goods, oil and farm products
increased by $2.3 billion in February. U.S. exports also rose, but
by a smaller $1.3 billion from January.
   In another report today, the Commerce Department said business
inventories rose a slight 0.1 percent in February, much slower than
the pace in recent months.
   The department said the gain in inventories pushed them up by
$825 million during February to a seasonally adjusted $715.9
billion.
   The gain came as total business sales were climbing 0.6 percent
to a seasonally adjusted $468.3 billion in February, reversing a
0.5 percent decline in January.
   On Wednesday, top finance ministers of seven major industrial
nations said the countries will keep working to stabilize the value
of the dollar against other major currencies.
   The finance ministers and central bankers of the Group of Seven
nations also announced they would develop a plan to use gold and
other commodities as a way of measuring inflation pressures.
   Mindful of investors' continued uneasiness at any signs of
disunity, the finance leaders went out of their way in their joint
statement to emphasize their strong desire to cooperate with each
other in keeping the global economy from toppling into a recession.
   The statement reaffirmed a Dec. 22 agreement that had been
issued after long-distance discussions in which the seven countries
pledged to work together to keep the dollar from falling further
against major currencies.
   The dollar rose against most other major currencies Wednesday
although most traders stayed on the sidelines waiting for today's
trade deficit figures.
   The group meeting in Washington consists of finance ministers
and central bank leaders from the United States, Japan, West
Germany, Britain, France, Canada and Italy.
   In their first face-to-face meeting since before the October
stock crash, the finance ministers also were critical of the newly
industrialized nations of South Korea, Taiwan, Singapore and Hong
Kong for not doing enough to reduce global trade imbalances.
   In other economic news on Wednesday, the Commerce Department
said retail sales rose 0.8 percent in March and automakers said
sales of domestic cars and light trucks fell 10.8 percent in early
April compared with a year earlier.
   The drop in auto sales came after three months of unexpectedly
strong results. One analyst, David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., described it as a ``hiccup.''
   Retail sales were helped by Easter buying at department and food
stores. The Commerce Department said it was the fifth consecutive
monthly increase and the largest since December.
   On Wall Street, stock prices retreated slightly as the Dow Jones
industrial average fell 2.98 points to 2,107.10. It was the first
Dow decline after gains totaling more than 129 points in six
sessions.
</TEXT>
