<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ResortsInternational     04-14 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Resorts International,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Griffin, Trump Reach Agreement Over Resorts International</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Merv Griffin has reached
an agreement to buy Resorts International Inc. from property
developer Donald Trump, ending a much-publicized takeover battle,
the two dealmakers said today.
   Griffin, who was in New Jersey this morning to meet with state
gaming regulators, said he and Trump came to the agreement after a
day-long meeting in New York on Wednesday.
   Shareholders other than Trump would be paid $36 a share under
the plan, giving the deal an indicated value of about $206 million.
   Trump, who paid $135 a share for his stake in the company, also
is getting paid in cash, said Jack Nusbaum, the developer's
attorney. But he would not provide details of the payment to Trump
except to say his client is ``pleased he is making a profit.''
   Under terms reached between the two high-living businessmen,
Trump would acquire Resorts' troubled 1,250-room Taj Mahal hotel
and casino project under construction in Atlantic City to add to
his battery of gaming operations. He also would acquire other
unidentified assets.
   Griffin, who hosted the ``Merv Griffin Show'' for 23 years,
would control the existing Resorts Hotel and Casino in Atlantic
City and all Paradise Island operations in the Bahamas.
   The agreement ends a lengthy jousting match that observers
initially expected would see Trump emerge as the victor. Trump, who
controls Resorts through his 95 percent ownership of the company's
outstanding Class B shares, had been trying to take the company
private for $22 a share since February.
   Griffin, who began bidding for a majority stake in Resorts last
month, had been spurned repeatedly by Trump.
   In a joint statement issued in Los Angeles, Trump and Griffin
said: ``We are extremely pleased that the future of Resorts may
finally have been resolved in a manner which benefit the public
shareholders of Resorts and each of us.''
   They said they planned to meet with the Resorts board ``as soon
as possible'' to outline their agreement.
   Nusbaum called the accord ``one of those rare agreements that is
good for all parties.'' He noted that Trump's main interest in
Resorts had been for the Taj Mahal, ``which (Trump) thinks is the
crown jewel of Atlantic City.''
   Griffin said he would meet with members of the state Casino
Control Commission and the Division of Gaming Enforcement today and
expected to exchange ``a lot of pleasantries.''
   If the deal is completed, Griffin will acquire 5.7 million Class
A shares and the 40,000 Class B shares not owned by Trump. The New
York developer maintained a controlling interest in Resorts because
his Class B shares each carried 100 votes.
</TEXT>
