<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in a continuation of the
profit-taking that began Tuesday.
   The sell-off is not unusual considering last week's dramatic
gains, which were based largely on a pair of Agriculture Department
reports indicating potentially tight supplies of soybeans, analysts
said.
   ``It's just a technical correction,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``We had a big upswing last
week, the market started going down Tuesday, it went down yesterday
and it's continuing down today.''
   The USDA said Wednesday it had targeted India for 1.2 million
metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices. Such news would be
bullish if it was unexpected, but Lespinasse said the market had
anticipated the export offer.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.16{ a bushel; corn was \ cent to
} cent lower with May at $2.04 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 2\
cents lower with May at $1.60{ a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to
3} cents lower with May at $6.72{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .55 cent higher with April at
73.65 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .30 cent higher
with April at 79.70 cents a pound; hogs were .18 cent lower to .08
cent higher with April at 44.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .15 cent lower to .18 cent higher with May at 51.65 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Wednesday.
