<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     04-14 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0304</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices tumbled today on the surprise news
of an increase in the nation's trade deficit.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 32.50 points to
2,074.60 by noontime today on Wall Street.
   Losers swamped gainers by more than 7 to 1 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 182 up, 1,313 down
and 334 unchanged.
   Before the market opened the Commerce Department reported that
the nation's trade deficit widened to $13.83 billion in February
from $12.44 billion the month before.
   That came as a big disappointment to market participants, who
had been looking for a continued narrowing in the gap between
imports and exports.
   The dollar dropped sharply in foreign exchange markets on the
news, and U.S. credit markets also took the news badly.
   Prices of long-term Treasury bonds fell about $15 for each
$1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the 8.85-8.9 percent
range. Just a few weeks ago government bond yields got as low as
about 8.3 percent.
   Stock-market analysts said persistent strength in imports, in
particular, raised fears that the Federal Reserve might soon feel
the need to tighten credit to restrain the economy as well as to
support the dollar.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines dropped { to 115|; DuPont 1} to 85{; General Electric 1 to
41~; Ford Motor 1 to 46[, and USX 1[ to 33[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
2.13 to 151.07. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 2.76 at 303.03.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 88.75 million shares at
noontime, against 107.70 million at the same point Wednesday.
</TEXT>
