<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-TaxFraud     04-14 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Tax Fraud,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indictment Hits Tax-Shelter Schemes Day Before Tax Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury has returned an
86-count indictment against 12 individuals charging them with
conducting one of the largest tax-shelter frauds ever prosecuted in
the United States, officials announced Thursday.
   The indictment charges that defendants involved in a tax shelter
promoted OEC Leasing Corp., of Garden City, N.Y., in tax years 1982
and 1983. The indictment said the 12 obtained at least $30 million
from more than 4,000 taxpayers, costing the United States a
potential revenue loss of at least $65 million.
   The indictment also charges that a tax shelter promoted by First
Energy Leasing Corp., Melville, N.Y., obtained at least $14 million
from more than 1,900 taxpayers and cost the United States a
potential revenue loss of at least $23 million.
   Three of the 12 defendants, Frank J. Giuffrida of Belle Terre,
N.Y., Salvatore Giuffrida of Dix Hills, N.Y., and William B. Medina
of Port Jefferson, N.Y., are charged with racketeering in the form
of mail fraud and interstate transportation of securities and money.
   All 12 defendants, including those three, are charged with
conspiracy to defraud the United States, aiding the filing of false
tax returns, mail fraud and interstate transportation of securities
and money taken by fraud.
   Others charged in the indictment, released at a news conference
of the Internal Revenue Service and U.S. Attorney's Office, are:
   _Zayle A. Bernstein, Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   _William L. Eckard Jr., Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   _Robert J. Cleary, Levittown, N.Y.
   _John A. DeRaffele, New Rochelle, N.Y.
   _Leo I. Tobin, Cherry Hill, N.J.
   _Irwin Berman, Crystal Lake, Pa.
   _Michael Enden, Port Washington, N.Y.
   _James E. Marcie, Coram, N.Y.
   _John Oster, Miller Place, N.Y.
   U.S. Attorney Edward S.G. Dennis Jr. said the case developed
from leads that came to the Philadelphia office of the IRS. Dennis
said arrests would begin immediately.
   ``This prosecution involves a very sophisticated attempt to lure
taxpayers into making investments that would, according to their
promoters, result in many times the investment in tax savings,''
Dennis said.
   According to the scheme, investors would buy an energy-saving
device for $5,000, which they could use to obtain investment and
energy tax credits to save $20,000 to $30,000 in taxes during the
first year, Dennis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880414-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Helmsleys 3rdLd-Writethru   04-14 0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helmsleys, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0844</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helmsleys Plead Innocent to Tax Evasion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with federal charges, other
details of counts, editing to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire developer Harry Helmsley and his
wife, Leona, the self-styled hotel queen, were arraigned today on
tax evasion charges in state court, where they loudly proclaimed
their innocence.
   The Helmsleys, in ringing voices, replied, ``Not guilty,'' when
asked how they pleaded to charges involving the disguising of
millions of dollars in renovation costs for their estate as
business expenses.
   Also pleading innocent were Frank Turco, Mrs. Helmsley's former
top aide, and Joseph Licari, the couple's former financial manager.
   All four also were named in a 47-count federal indictment
containing similar charges. That indictment also charges Mrs.
Helmsley and Turco with extortion conspiracy; they allegedly
received kickbacks by threatening suppliers with a cutoff of
Helmsley business and by threatening Helmsley employees with loss
of their jobs.
   State prosecutors had asked that the Helmsleys each be required
to post $1 million bail, and that bail for their aides be set at
$100,000. But acting state Supreme Court Justice Carol Berkman
released them on their own recognizance. A June 1 court date was
set.
   The trial-level judge said she was angry because news of the
indictments leaked earlier in the week.
   ``I am asking Mr. (Robert) Morgenthau (the Manhattan district
attorney) to investigate this grand jury leak. A crime has been
committed. This particular grand jury was under my supervision, and
I am quite upset that this information was leaked to the press,''
she said.
   Helmsley, 80, and his 68-year-old wife are one of the world's
wealthiest couples. Their holdings, including the Empire State
Building and the Helmsley Palace Hotel, are worth an estimated $1.4
billion.
   The couple arrived at the attorney general's office to surrender
in a gray limousine, followed by a second limousine carrying their
own security people.
   They said ``Good morning'' to reporters; when one reporter asked
Helmsley what his greatest achievement had been, he answered,
``Marrying her.''
   From the attorney general's office, the Helmsleys were taken to
police headquarters for booking and then to Manhattan Criminal
Court.
   In the courtroom, the Helmsleys sat quietly in the front row as
drug dealers and thieves were arraigned, and exchanged words from
time to time.
   The state indictment against each defendant included 139 counts
of falsifying business records; 44 counts of offering a false
instrument for filing; three counts of scheme to defraud; one count
of conspiracy; and one misdemanor count of scheme to defraud.
   The indictment said the crimes were committed between 1982 and
1986.
   The charges in the federal indictment include conspiracy, income
tax evasion, filing false and fraudulent income tax returns, mail
fraud and, for Mrs. Helmsley and Turco, conspiracy to commit
extortion.
   The Helmsleys are accused of disguising millions of dollars in
renovation costs on their Greenwich, Conn., mansion as business
expenses and writing the bills off as tax deductions.
   Approximately $4 million was used to refurbish the mansion. That
money bought an enclosure for one of the estate's two pools; a
breakfast room and marble dance floor on the roof of that
enclosure; installation of an elaborate indoor-outdoor stereo
system; more than $200,000 in landscaping; and an assortment of
furniture and paintings.
   In addition, a $45,000 birthday present for Helmsley was billed
to and paid by the Park Lane Hotel in December 1984, and one or
more jade art objects worth $500,000 were paid for by four New York
City hotels as furniture purchases in 1984, according to the
charges.
   The federal indictment says there were four jade objects, and
estimates the value of the landscaping work at $370,000.
   On Wednesday, the Helmsleys' attorney, Stephen Kaufman,
denounced the tax-cheating accusations ``unfounded, unfair and
unjust.''
   ``The Helmsleys have paid more taxes to the government over the
years than practically any other individual in this city or
country,'' Kaufman said. ``In the last five years alone they have
paid more than $250 million in taxes.''
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani and state Attorney General Robert
Abrams mounted a joint investigation into the Helmsleys' taxes 18
months ago.
   There were indications of legal action against the Helmsleys on
Monday, when they obtained a show cause order and filed a writ of
prohibition against Abrams in state Supreme Court.
   The papers were sealed by the judge, so it was not known what
the Helmsleys sought. A writ of prohibition can bar public
officials from actions ordinarily in their power, such as an
indictment or grand jury appearance.
   Mrs. Helmsley, who is featured in ads as the ``queen'' of a
string of hotels owned by her and her husband, turned down a deal
from prosecutors, who said they would not seek the indictment of
her husband if she pleaded guilty to fraud, a law enforcement
source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told The Associated
Press.
</TEXT>
