<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BritishStocks     04-14 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Sharply Lower On Trade Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices tumbled Thursday after the U.S.
government reported a wider-than-expected trade deficit for
February.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 23.2
points, or 1.3 percent, lower at 1,787.2, after trading as high as
1,826.8, or 16.4 points up, ahead of the trade report.
   Dealers said the $13.83 billion trade deficit in February,
compared with a deficit of $12.44 billion in January, renewed fears
of a sharp downturn in stocks worldwide.
   The October stock markets' crash followed a poor U.S. trade
report.
   Volume was moderate at 517.3 million shares, down from 523.4
million on Wednesday.
   London shares were buoyed in morning business on continued
buying interest on news of British takeovers.
   But all was lost in a matter of minutes when the Commerce
Department announced its trade deficit widened in February instead
of narrowing to between $11.2 billion and $11.8 billion, as the
markets had expected.
   ``The figures were plainly bad, suggesting there's been no real
recovery in the (U.S.) trade situation at all,'' one dealer said.
   A sharply lower opening on Wall Street depressed the London
market further.
   Bob Semple, a U.K. equities strategist at County Natwest Wood
MacKenzie Ltd., said the equity market's sharp reaction to the U.S.
trade data reflected an underlying worry about whether ``the second
stage of the bear market (is) right around the corner.''
</TEXT>
