<DOCNO> AP880414-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Media     04-14 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Media,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gannett, Knight-Ridder, Tribune Co., Media General Post Profit
Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Four major media companies _ Gannett Co. Inc., Knight-Ridder
Inc., Tribune Co. and Media General Inc. _ said Thursday they each
had double-digit profit gains for the first quarter.
   After-tax profits were up 41 percent at Gannett, 18 percent at
Knight-Ridder, 93 percent at Tribune Co. and 42 percent at Media
General.
   Gannett, the Arlington, Va.-based publisher of USA Today and 89
other daily newspapers, said its profit rose to $74 million, or 46
cents a share, from $52.5 million, or 33 cents a share, in the same
quarter a year earlier. Operating revenue rose 8 percent to $757.9
million from $703.2 million.
   The latest results included a pre-tax gain of about $45 million
on its sale of stock in another company. A lower effective tax rate
also helped earnings, Gannett said.
   Gannett said overall newspaper advertising linage rose 4 percent
in the quarter, reflecting strength in classified advertising. It
said paid advertising pages rose 2 percent at USA Today while ad
revenue at the national newspaper rose 21 percent.
   Gannett said its broadcasting revenue rose 9 percent, while
outdoor advertising revenue were flat compared with last year's
results that had included revenue of a sign manufacturer sold last
year.
   In addition to its daily newspapers, Gannett publishes 35
non-daily newspapers and USA Weekend, a newspaper magazine. It
operates 10 television stations, 16 radio stations, Gannett News
Services and the largest outdoor ad company in the United States.
   Knight-Ridder, based in Miami, said its profit rose to $33.8
million, or 59 cents a share, in the first three months of the
year, compared with $28.6 million, or 49 cents a share, a year
earlier. Operating revenue increased 5.3 percent to $514.9 million
from $488.9 million in 1987.
   ``A lower tax rate, lower interest costs, excellent control of
other costs and a slightly smaller number of shares outstanding
helped us produce a good earnings gain for the quarter,'' said
Robert Singleton, senior Knight-Ridder vice president and chief
financial officer.
   Knight-Ridder owns 30 daily newspapers and eight television
stations.
   Tribune Co., based in Chicago, said its profit rose to $32.2
million, or 42 cents a share, in the quarter from $16.7 million, or
21 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 9 percent to $522
million from $477.1 million.
   The operating profit in Tribune's newspaper publishing group
rose 22 percent to $51.8 million on a 7 percent revenue increase to
$375 million. The company said the biggest improvement came at the
New York Daily News as a result of increased revenue and labor
savings.
   Tribune said the operating loss at its broadcasting and
entertainment group narrowed to $3.5 million from $10.1 million a
year earlier as revenue rose 7 percent to $91 million.
   Tribune also had a $23 million operating profit from newsprint
operations, up from $12.8 million a year earlier.
   Tribune owns nine daily newspapers, six television stations and
five radio stations.
   Media General, based in Richmond, Va., said its first-quarter
profit rose to $11.5 million, or 43 cents a share, from $8.1
million, or 28 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 11.3
percent to $186 million from $167.1 million.
   Media General owns 4 daily and 32 weekly newspapers and has an
interest in 16 other daily newspapers. It owns three television
stations and two cable television systems that have about 175,000
subscribers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
