<HEAD>Pharmaceutical Company Reports Sales, Earnings Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Upjohn Co.'s sales of pharmaceuticals
and strength in animal health products helped boost the company's
first-quarter earnings 17.9 percent, the company said Thursday.
   Upjohn said it earned $95.4 million, or 51 cents a share, up
from $80.8 million, or 43 cents a share, in the same a year ago.
   The company reported sales of $662.4 million for the three
months ending March 31, up from $597.4 million in the first quarter
of 1987.
   Upjohn cited an 11 percent gain in worldwide sales of human
health care products, with strong performances by its Xanax and
Halcion agents for central nervous system disorders and Micronase,
an oral anti-diabetes agent.
   Rogaine, Upjohn's drug for male pattern baldness, has been
approved for marketing in 36 countries after approval in the United
Kingdom during the first quarter, and is a strong contributor to
foreign sales, the company said.
   Worldwide agricultural sales rose 12 percent, with gains for all
major animal health products, especially in foreign markets.
Naxcel, an antibiotic for bovine respiratory disease, made a strong
contribution to domestic sales after approval for U.S. use early in
the quarter, Upjohn said.
