<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     04-14 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wider U.S. Trade Deficit Sends the Dollar into a Tailspin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AM version expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended sharply lower in Europe Thursday
after news that the U.S. trade deficit widened in February sent the
currency into a tailspin that was only partially stemmed by
coordinated central bank intervention.
   Gold prices rose.
   Dealers had expected the trade deficit to narrow in February and
had built up long dollar positions _ or had bought dollars that
they hadn't yet agreed to sell _ which had to be quickly sold off.
   The dollar plummeted against most major currencies within
minutes of the Commerce Department announcement that the trade gap
had widened to $13.8 billion in February from $12.4 billion in
January.
   ``The trade figure caught everyone on the hop,'' said Marek
Stefanowicz, a corporate adviser at Nomura Bank International in
London.
   Within minutes of the start of the dollar's fall, the central
banks of the United States, West Germany, France, Britain, Italy,
Switzerland, Canada and the Netherlands intervened to buy dollars,
dealers reported.
   Later, several of the central banks, notably the Deutsche
Bundesbank and The Bank of France, confirmed their intervention.
   The interventions were not particularily large, dealers
reported, but were effective because all the banks intervened at
once.
   The intervention did not push the dollar any higher but was able
to stem its decline.
   ``It is only the central banks keeping the dollar at these
levels,'' said a trader at a British merchant bank.
   In London, it cost $1.8755 to buy one pound, more expensive than
$1.8445 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's: 1.6635 West German marks, down from 1.6895; 1.3745
Swiss francs, down from 1.3983; 5.6390 French francs, down from
5.7295; 1.8680 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8950; 1,244.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,252.50; and 1.2368 Canadian dollars, up from
1.23675.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar fell 0.30 yen to close at 126.15 yen. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 123.60 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $451.00 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $449.25. In Zurich, gold was higher,
closing at a bid $450.50 compared with $449.50 late Wednesday.
Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.34 to close at a bid $449.48.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.43 a troy ounce, compared
with Wednesday's $6.41.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
