<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     04-14 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0349</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices took a sharp drop today on the
surprise news of an increase in the nation's trade deficit.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 52.56 points to
2,054.54 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers swamped gainers by nearly 8 to 1 in the overall tally of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 182 up, 1,414 down and
313 unchanged.
   Before the market opened the Commerce Department reported that
the nation's trade deficit widened to $13.83 billion in February
from $12.44 billion the month before.
   That came as a big disappointment to market participants, who
had been looking for a continued narrowing in the gap between
imports and exports.
   The dollar dropped sharply in foreign exchange markets on the
news, and U.S. credit markets also took the news badly.
   Prices of long-term Treasury bonds fell about $15 for each
$1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the 8.85-8.9 percent
range. Just a few weeks ago government bond yields got as low as
about 8.3 percent.
   Stock-market analysts said persistent strength in imports, in
particular, raised fears that the Federal Reserve might soon feel
the need to tighten credit to restrain the economy as well as to
support the dollar.
   The decline in the Dow reached 50 points at midafternoon,
activating for the second-time the ``collar'' set up by the NYSE in
early February. At that point the exchange asked its member firms
not to use its main computerized trading system for program trading.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines dropped 1| to 114{; Exxon 1[ to 44]; General Electric 1\
to 41|; Ford Motor 1} to 45], and American Telephone & Telegraph 1
to 27.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
3.49 to 149.71. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 3.97 at 301.82.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 130.84 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
