<HEAD>Black & Decker Earnings More Than Double in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOWSON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black & Decker Corp., a leading producer of
power tools and household appliances, reported Thursday its second
quarter earnings more than doubled from the same period a year ago.
   Black & Decker said it earned $21.1 million, or 36 cents per
share, in the three-month period ending March 27, compared to
earnings of $9.3 million, or 16 cents per share, in the same
quarter a year earlier.
   Sales for the quarter rose to $537.8 million from $438.7
million, the company said.
   For the last six months, net earnings rose 65 percent to $52.3
million, or 89 cents per share, compared to $31.6 million, or 54
cents per share, in the first six months of the previous fiscal
year.
   Six-month sales totaled $1.15 billion, up from $967.7 million.
   Nolan D. Archibald, chairman and chief executive officer, said,
``With manufacturing restructuring basically behind us, our stream
of new products and aggressive marketing programs are producing
consistently improved sales and earnings.''
   The quarterly earnings statement did not include expenses
related to the company's recent offer to buy American Standard,
Inc., or a $25 million settlement payment that the company will
receive if Kelso & Co. buys shares or assets of American Standard
on or before May 2.
   The payment is expected to offset Black & Decker's expenses in
the attempted takeover, the statement said. Black & Decker
abandoned the fight on March 22 after Kelso submitted a higher bid.
