<HEAD>Ad Violates Court Order, Koppers Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. Thursday accused British investor
Brian Beazer of defying a federal judge by placing a newspaper ad
promoting his $1.7 billion hostile takeover attempt.
   ``You, our fellow shareholders, ought to ask: `How long must we
wait?' '' for Koppers' management to accept the $60-per-share
tender offer, the ad said.
   In papers filed with U.S. District Court in Pittsburgh, Koppers
said the ad violates U.S. District Judge Maurice Cohill's April 6
temporary restraining order. The order bars the Beazer group from
taking any actions to advance the takeover.
   Koppers said the ad also misrepresented Beazer's financial
backing and misrepresented court testimony by company Chairman
Charles R. Pullin and board member Charles Barber.
   Beazer spokeswoman Lissa Perlman in New York said that while the
Beazer group had not seen the complaint ``to the extent that it
criticizes our ad, we believe it is entirely frivolous and without
merit.''
   Koppers' resistance to the hostile offer, launched March 3 at
$45 per share and raised twice since, ``has deteriorated into one
of history's sorriest examples of management self-entrenchment,''
said the full-page ad in Wednesday's Wall Street Journal.
   The tender offer comes from BNS Inc., a takeover company formed
by the British industrialist's company, Beazer PLC, along with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. of New York and National Westminster
Bank of Britain.
</TEXT>
