<DOCNO> AP880414-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2145EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USG-DesertPartners     04-14 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USG-Desert Partners,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USG Eyes Ways To Gird Against Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. appears to be taking Desert Partners'
takeover attempt more seriously since the Texas-based partnership
increased its cash offer this week from $903 million to $1.63
billion, an analyst said Thursday.
   USG says it is now considering a number of options for remaining
independent, possibly indicating a change in its attitude toward
Desert Partners, said Paul Kleinaitis, an analyst for the
Chicago-based investment research firm Duff & Phelps Inc.
   He said USG had been resisting Desert Partners ``with a
no-comment, no-action, let's-see-what-they-come-up-with sort of
approach.
   ``But maybe Desert Partners at this level is starting to look a
little threatening to them,'' Kleinaitis said. ``Given Desert
Partners' persistence in this deal, you'd think USG would have to
do something.''
   Desert Partners, controlled by oilmen Jack Brown and Cyril
Wagner Jr. of Midland, Texas, has maintained since it announced its
initial offer in February that it is truly interested in acquiring
the Chicago-based building-products producer.
   But skeptical analysts have speculated that Brown and Wagner's
real intent was either to boost the value of USG's stock so they
could sell their 9.8-percent stake in the company at a good profit
or to bully USG's management into paying them off to drop the
takeover bid.
   On Monday, Desert Partners said it would pay $42 cash per share
for up to 39 million shares of USG's outstanding stock. Previously,
Desert Partners had been seeking to buy only 21.5 million shares at
$42 a share.
   If Desert Partners were to obtain all the shares it is now
seeking, it would own 85 percent of USG. USG has urged its
stockholders not to tender their shares to Desert Partners, which
said about 12.6 million shares had been tendered as of last Friday.
   USG's board met Monday to discuss Desert Partners' latest move,
then filed a statement with the Securities and Exchange Commission
saying it was exploring options to remain independent.
   The options mentioned in the filing included selling part of USG
to a third party for cash or assets, recapitalizing the company or
repurchasing its own stock.
   Any of those actions would make it difficult for Desert Partners
to obtain the shares it is seeking.
   Frederic Spar, a spokesman for Desert Partners, said Thusday
that the offer for more shares should leave no doubt about the
Texas group's intentions.
   ``There should be no doubt that Desert Partners has been
interested in acquiring USG for quite some time,'' he said. ``That
commitment is underscored by the fact that they have now put up a
substantial amount of money in commmitment fees for the financing
and expenses related to the tender offer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
