<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Farmers-Batus     04-14 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Injunction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge said Batus Inc. can
continue to seek proxies in support of a non-binding resolution
asking that Farmers Group Inc. negotiate with Batus over a takeover
attempt.
   U.S. District Judge Howard McKibben of Reno, Nev. denied on
Wednesday a preliminary injunction Farmers Group sought against
Batus regarding the solicitation of proxies.
   But McKibben ordered Batus to clarify a statement in the
stockholder resolution the company will submit at Farmers' annual
meeting May 20, according to a release issued Thursday by Batus.
   Batus said in a news release it was pleased with the ruling.
   ``Once again, we say to Farmers that there is no need for all
this legal maneuvering,'' Batus said. ``We are ready to sit down
and negotiate all points in our offer, including a possible
increase in price in a friendly transaction supported by the
Farmers board.''
   The resolution recommends that the Farmers' board reconsider its
decision not to negotiate with Batus over the sale. The statement
ordered rephrased said a vote in favor of the resolution would
indicate shareholder support for the sale of Farmers to Batus.
   McKibben said the statement needed to be clarified in order to
conform to the literal wording of the resolution.
   Batus, the Louisville-based subisdiary of Britain's BAT
Industries, has said it was willing to raise its $63-per-share bid,
but refused on Wednesday to meet Farmers' ground rules for
negotiations.
   Farmers, the nation's third-largest home and auto insurer and
seventh-largest property and casualty insurer, insisted it would
not sit down unless Batus agreed to keep certain information
confidential. Farmers also asked Batus to reveal how much it was
willing to pay for the company.
   Batus, whose U.S. businesses include Kool and Viceroy cigarettes
and retailers such as Saks Fifth Avenue, responded by proposing
alternate confidentiality provisions.
   Farmers, which is based in Los Angeles, has about $11 billion in
assets.
   Batus earned $886 million on revenue of $5.8 billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
