<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Warner     04-14 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Warner,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 36 Percent Profit Increase in 1st-Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. said Thursday its
first-quarter profit jumped 35.8 percent as its film and music
divisions each turned in best-ever quarterly performances.
   Warner said its earnings rose to $89.1 million, or 56 cents per
share, in the three months ended March 31 compared with a profit of
$65.6 million, or 41 cents per share, a year earlier.
   Revenue rose 22 percent to $960.8 million for the quarter from
$788.3 million in 1987.
   The company said its filmed entertainment division had an
operating profit of $55.3 million, up 17 percent from a year ago
and its highest profit for any quarter in the division's history.
   The results were helped by sharply higher results from Warner
Bros.' international distribution of films such as Steven
Spielberg's ``Innerspace'' and Stanley Kubrick's ``Full Metal
Jacket.''
   Strong domestic and international home video sales, pay
television and television syndication revenue also contributed
significantly, Warner said.
   Warner said its recorded music and music publishing divisions
had operating income of $70.5 million, up 50 percent from a year
earlier and its highest quarterly performance ever.
   Million-selling releases by artists such as INXS, Debbie Gibson,
David Lee Roth, George Harrison, and Foreigner contributed to the
record-setting performance, the company said.
   Warner Cable's results more than doubled to $15.5 million, but
losses at BHC Inc., the television station operation in which
Warner has a 42.5 percent stake, left the cable and broadcasting
division's earnings at $13.5 million, up from $5.3 million a year
earlier.
   The company's publishing division had first-quarter earnings of
$2 million, down from $2.5 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
