<HEAD>Motorola Profits Double As Electronics Sales Soar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First-quarter profits at Motorola Inc.
were more than double those of a year ago, thanks to sharply
increased sales of its electronic equipment, the company said
Thursday.
   For the first three months of 1988, Motorola reported net income
of $114 million, or 88 cents a share, compared to $56 million, or
44 cents a share, for the same period a year ago.
   Sales increased 26 percent, to $1.95 billion from $1.55 billion
a year earlier, the suburban Chicago company said in a statement.
   First-quarter sales of Motorola's paging and two-way radio
systems advanced 25 percent while sales of its semiconductor
products jumped 31 percent. New orders in both divisions reached
the highest level in the company's history, said George Fisher,
president and chief executive officer.
   Sales in Motorola's General Systems Group, which includes
computer and cellular telephone businesses, rose 35 percent, and
sales of electronic equipment for government applications were up
23 percent for the quarter, the company said.
   Chairman Robert W. Galvin expressed satisfaction with the
results and said he was optimistic about the company's future.
   ``We are delivering higher quality products and services in less
time,'' Galvin said. ``Our customers use these products to improve
their productivity, which builds further momentum for long-term
growth in the years to come.''
</TEXT>
