<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GM-Pontiac     04-14 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM-Pontiac,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Adds Second Shift at Truck Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 1,300 laid-off autoworkers will be
called back to work as General Motors Corp. adds a second shift at
its full-size pickup truck plant here, GM said Thursday.
   Most of the workers will come from a pool of 1,050 United Auto
Workers Local 594 members furloughed from three GM Truck & Bus
Group plants in Pontiac.
   But about 300 to 400 laid-off Flint-area workers also are
eligible to transfer into the plant, said UAW Vice President Donald
Ephlin, who heads the union's GM department.
   ``It's wonderful news. We've got a good product here and a good
work force,'' said Don Douglas, president of Local 594, which
represents about 9,500 active and laid-off truck workers in Pontiac.
   The recalls will begin gradually within 30 days so GM can give
workers new to the plant extensive training before the plant begins
building 1989 models, said Charles Katko, a GM vice president and
Truck & Bus Group executive.
   Sales of the new Chevrolet C-K and GMC Sierra pickups,
introduced last year, have risen steadily since the start of the
year. Sierra sales have risen 18.4 percent since Jan. 1 while C-K
sales rose 22.7 percent.
   The Pontiac East plant employs 2,000 workers _ 1,750 hourly and
250 salaried. When the second shift reaches full speed, it will
employ 1,250 additional hourly and 50 additional salaried workers.
   GM earlier this year announced plans to boost companywide
production by about 175,000 vehicles for 1988, most of it in
trucks. Last year, GM and other automakers had trimmed production
plans in an effort to reduce inventory backlogs. But sales in the
first quarter surpassed expectations.
</TEXT>
