<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Fell $2.02 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report are for the
week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended
Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 419 money market mutual
tumbled $2.02 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The decline, to $274.8 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $1.43 billion drop in the funds' assets the
previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade
group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 210 general purpose funds fell $1.41 billion to $82.23
billion, assets of 97 broker-dealer funds fell $97.4 million to
$117.3 billion, and assets of 112 institutional funds fell $519.8
million to $75.24 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 6.10 percent from 6.05 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield edged up to 6.06 percent from 6.05
percent, Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
42 days, the same as the previous week, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts fell to
5.67 percent as of Wednesday from 5.68 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.14 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 6.82
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 6.81 percent
the previous week. Yields were 7.14 percent on 1-year CDs,
unchanged; 7.57 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 7.56 percent; and
8.01 percent on 5-year CDs, unchanged.
</TEXT>
