<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Trade-Markets 4thLd-Writethru   04-14 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade-Markets, 4th Ld-Writethru,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Plunges 100 Points; Dollar Slides; Interest Rates Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 1-10 new with closing stocks, late dollar and bonds.
Picks up 11th graf: The bulge ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices and the dollar plunged and interest
rates shot higher today after an unexpected bulge in the trade
deficit sent shock waves through the financial markets.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped about
101 points, while in the currency markets the value of the dollar
fell 2 percent against major currencies. Interest rates on a key
long-term U.S. Treasury bond jumped to a three-month high.
   Traders scrambled to sell dollars, bonds and stocks after the
Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's trade
deficit had risen to $13.8 billion in February. That was the
biggest shortfall since the record of $17.6 billion in October and
the second monthly increase in a row. Many economists had been
expecting the deficit to narrow.
   The Dow Jones industrials tumbled 35 points within 20 minutes of
the opening bell on the New York Stock Exchange then stabilized for
a few hours. But the slide resumed in the afternoon and the average
skidded to a 101.46-point loss at 2,005.63, a 4.8 percent drop,
according to a prelimary calculation.
   It was the worst decline since the Dow plunged 140.58 points on
Jan. 8.
   The Dow's decline triggered a ban on the use of a form of
computerized program trading on the New York Stock Exchange, the
first time the ``collar'' has been triggered by a decline of 50
points or more in the Dow.
   Prices also fell on the London Stock Exchange, where the
Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 1.3 percent,
dropping 23.2 points to 1,787.2.
   Currency brokers reported the Federal Reserve and other central
banks, concerned about a rout in the dollar, swooped into foreign
exchange markets to buy dollars with Japanese yen, British pounds
and West German marks to try to stabilize the currency's value.
   The dollar was down about 1.9 percent against the British pound,
about 1.9 percent against the West German mark and about 2.2
percent against the Japanese yen at midafternoon.
   The impact also was felt in the bond market, an important
barometer of the economy and interest rates. By late afternoon,
prices of the key 30-year Treasury bond were down 1\ points, or
about $12.50 for every $1,000 in face amount, and its yield, which
moves inversely to price, surged to 8.855 percent, the highest in
three months.
   The bulge in the trade deficit suggested America's trade
problems remain more stubborn than earlier believed, leading some
traders to believe that the dollar needs to fall further to make
U.S. goods more competitive in the global market.
   However, Carl B. Weinberg, chief economist of High Frequency
Economics, noted that the February deficit was smaller than the
deficit of $14.4 billion in February 1987, indicating that trade
flows are improving.
   Central banks that bought dollars to halt the currency's slide
ranged across the board, from the Bank of Italy to the central bank
of Australia, said Marc Chandler, a currency analyst in Chicago for
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   A seven-nation accord announced Wednesday in Washington had
little effect on the currency market, Chandler said, because it
merely reaffirmed a December agreement by finance officials of the
countries to support the dollar.
   The seven nations are the United States, Canada, Japan, Britain,
France, West Germany and Italy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880414-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1719EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-Banks     04-14 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Banks,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical, Hanover, Security Pacific and Bank of New York Report
Earnings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: With AM-Bank Bid, Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Four major bank holding companies _ Chemical New York Corp.,
Manufacturers Hanover Corp., Security Pacific Corp. and Bank of New
York Co. _ reported sharp rises Thursday in their first quarter
profits from a year ago.
   Analysts said the results generally were in line to slightly
better than expected and showed that the banks' continuing efforts
to trim expenses were paying off.
   Chemical, the nation's fourth-largest banking company, said net
income for the first three months of this year rose 45.6 percent,
to $125.5 million, or $1.95 a share, from $86.2 million, or $1.58 a
share, a year ago.
   Manufacturers Hanover, ranked sixth, reported a 73.2 percent
jump in its earnings, to $140.3 million, or $2.56 a share, from
$81.0 million, or $1.68 a share, in first quarter 1987.
   Security Pacific, No. 7, netted $147.2 million, or $1.30 a
share, compared with $116.5 million, or $1.06 a share.
   No. 26 Bank of New York, which is engaged in a hostile battle to
acquire Irving Bank Corp., reported net earnings of $54.4 million,
or $1.47 a share. That was up 15 percent from $47.3 million, or
$1.32 per share, a year earlier. ``Most banks have been pretty good
restraining overhead costs. That has helped the results,'' said
Stephen Berman, a banking analyst with County Securities USA. ``Fee
income and trading activity is also very strong.''
   Chemical said fees for trust and other banking services totaled
$211.1 million, up 33.9 percent from the previous year. It said
securities trading profits were $32.7 million in the quarter, up
from $21.9 million last year.
   The company also said its provision for loan losses rose to
$105.6 million from 87.2 million.
   Manufacturers Hanover said it lowered its loan-loss provision to
$141.6 million from $152.5 million last year.
   The company also reported big increases in trading revenue and
other fees. Revenue from all trading activities was $67.3 million,
up 72.4 percent from $39.1 million in the first quarter.
   ``Strong core operating results were in line with what we had
been projecting, and our financial plan to replenish common
shareholders' equity is on track,'' Chairman John F. McGillicuddy
stated.
   As part of that plan, Manufacturers Hanover announced earlier
this week it reached an agreement in principle to sell its consumer
finance subsidiary, Manufacturers Hanover Consumer Services Inc.
   Security Pacific Chairman Richard J. Flamson III said his bank
also was beginning to see positive results from its programs to
control expense growth. ``We expect to be implementing more new
expense reduction plans ...'' he said.
   At Bank of New York, Chairman J. Carter Bacot said strong
performances by the company's core businesses contributed to the
overall earnings growth. Core businesses at Bank of New York are
corporate banking, securities processing, retail banking and trust
and investment management.
</TEXT>
