<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-14 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wider U.S. Trade Deficit Sends the Dollar into a Tailspin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged on foreign exchange markets
Thursday after traders were shocked by an unexpected jump in the
U.S. trade deficit.
   ``The market was caught by surprise,'' said Ron Sapiro, a vice
president at Continental Illinois National Bank & Trust Co. in
Chicago.
   Financial markets had expected the trade gap to shrink in
February from its January level of $12.4 billion, so when the
Commerce Department announced a $13.8 billion deficit Thursday
morning, panic selling of dollars set in, Sapiro said.
   But gold prices benefited from the report. Republic National
Bank of New York quoted a bid of $452.65 for a troy ounce of gold
as of 4 p.m. EDT, up more than $6 from late Wednesday's $446.60.
   The central banks of several nations, including the Federal
Reserve, bought dollars to help stabilize the currency, but the
dollar still lost about 2 percent of its value against the West
German mark, British pound and Japanese yen.
   ``They stemmed what would have been a momentary freefall,'' said
Varick Martin, a vice president at Union Bank of Switzerland, of
the banks' intervention.
   Martin said the dollar fell 2 pfennigs against the mark
immediately after the trade report, regained some ground and then
fell again before closing near its lows for the day.
   The trade report came on the heels of an agreement among the
Group of Seven industrial nations that reaffirmed a Dec. 22 pact to
keep the dollar stable. Martin said that agreement contributed to
the dollar's slide.
   ``The (dollar) rates on Dec. 22 were substantially lower (than
they are now),'' Martin said, suggesting that the currency markets
interpreted the ministers' agreement as supporting the dollar at
lower levels.
   Martin predicted traders would test the dollar at its lower
levels to see if the central banks will again step in to support
the U.S. currency.
   If the dollar does not resume its fall Friday ``it will come
back somewhat,'' Sapiro said. However, he did not expect any
dramatic improvement.
   In London, it cost $1.8755 to buy one pound, more expensive than
$1.8445 late Wednesday. In later New York trading, sterling jumped
to $1.8739 from $1.83755 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.66275 West German marks, down from
1.6950; 1.3720 Swiss francs, down from 1.4055; 5.6325 French
francs, down from 5.74375; 1,233.00 Italian lire, down from
1,255.75; and 1.2365 Canadian dollars, down from 1.23775.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's, rates, included: 1.6635 West German marks, down from
1.6895; 1.3745 Swiss francs, down from 1.3983; 5.6390 French
francs, down from 5.7295; 1.8680 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8950;
1,244.00 Italian lire, down from 1,252.50; and 1.2368 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.23675.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ended before the trade figures
came out, the dollar fell 0.30 yen to close at 126.15 yen. Later,
in London, it was quoted at 123.60 yen and in New York, it fell to
123.725 yen from 126.44 late Wednesday.
   Gold bullion prices rose in response to the trade report, said
Steven Pepper, vice president and bullion dealer at Republic
National Bank.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, a troy ounce of gold
climbed to $454 from $447 late Wednesday.
   The metal's gain was smaller in earlier London trading. Gold
closed there at a late bid price of $451.00 a troy ounce, compared
with late Wednesday's $449.25. In Zurich, gold closed at a bid
$450.50 compared with $449.50 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.34 to close at a bid $449.48.
   Silver was up on the Comex in New York, closing at $6.450 a troy
ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $6.325. In earlier London
trading, silver traded at a late bid price of $6.43 a troy ounce,
compared with Wednesday's $6.41.
</TEXT>
