<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   04-14 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0558</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top finance officials of the world's seven
major industrial powers have agreed to continue efforts to
stabilize the value of the dollar.
   The group, consisting of finance ministers and central bank
leaders from the United States, Japan, West Germany, Britain,
France, Canada and Italy, issued a statement Wednesday announcing
the extension of a Dec. 22 agreement that has so far successfully
halted the currency's three-year decline.
   The two-page joint communique followed a full day of private
meetings hosted by Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III and
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department has launched an
investigation into the finances and management of Texas Air Corp.,
the nation's largest airline company.
   The department wants to determine if Texas Air and its
management are ``fit, willing and able'' to carry commercial air
traffic, Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said at a news
conference Wednesday.
   In a separate action, the Federal Aviation Administration
imposed $823,000 in fines against Texas Air's Eastern Airlines
subsidiary, for violating safety regulations and said it has begun
a new round of safety inspections of the Miami-based air carrier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The French communications giant Hachette SA made
its second major venture into the U.S. publishing market this week
with an announcement that it will buy a major magazine publisher
for $712 million.
   Hachette said Wednesday it had agreed to buy Diamandis
Communications Inc., a privately held concern that publishes a
dozen magazines, including Woman's Day, Car & Driver, Popular
Photography, Road & Track and Stereo Review.
   The announcement came four days after Hachette reached an
agreement to buy Grolier Inc., the Danbury, Conn.-based book
publisher, for $450 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestic cars and light trucks fell 10.8
percent in early April from a year ago after three months of
unexpectedly strong results, according to domestic automakers.
   The automakers said Wednesday they sold 230,486 domestic cars
and light trucks in the eight selling days of April 1-10, down from
290,826 domestic vehicles in nine selling days the same period last
year. Sales per day fell by 10.8 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Securities and Exchange
Commission has endorsed far-reaching legislation to permit banks to
enter the securities business as long as consumers are protected
adequately.
   SEC Chairman David S. Ruder told the House telecommunications
and science subcommittee on Wednesday that the commission supports
the Senate-passed repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act ``as long as the
investor protection concerns arising from the entry of banks into
securities activities are simultaneously addressed.''
   Glass-Steagall is a Depression-era law that separated banking
from the securities business in the aftermath of the 1929 financial
crash.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recent poll of more than 1,000 top executives
indicates their confidence in the U.S. economy is recovering in the
wake of the stock market's collapse six months ago, a new study
says.
   The Conference Board, a business research concern, said
Wednesday that its measure of business confidence rose to 51 after
falling to a five-year low of 47 in the final quarter of 1987. The
measure reflects a scale of 0 to 100.
</TEXT>
