<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Computers     04-14 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Computers,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unisys Net Income Up 35 Percent in First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE BELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computer manufacturer Unisys Corp.
reported a 35 percent increase in net earnings for the first
quarter, citing continued savings from the summer 1986 merger of
Sperry and Burroughs.
   Net income was $149.3 million, or 72 cents per fully diluted
common share, for the three months ended March 31. For the same
period a year ago, Unisys net income was $110.2 million, or 57
cents per fully diluted common share, adjusted for a July 1987
three-for-one stock split.
   Revenue fell 2.1 percent to $2.37 billion from $2.42 billion a
year ago, when heavy end-of-the-year selling related to the old
Sperry fiscal calendar raised revenues above typical first-quarter
levels, the company reported.
   ``Our conservative business plan for 1988 and the cost
advantages that continue to accrue to us from the merger put us in
a strong position to achieve our plan in a modest business
environment,'' said Unisys President W. Michael Blumenthal.
   Unisys, created in 1986 from Burroughs Corp.'s $4.8 billion
purchase of Sperry Corp., is the world's third-largest computer
company after International Business Machines Corp. and Digital
Equipment Corp.
   ``We are pleased with results for the quarter as earnings
exceeded expectations and our continued progress faster than
planned augurs well for achieving our aggressive five-year growth
goals,'' Blumenthal said.
   ``Business in the quarter was basically on target, with order
and revenue trends similar to what we experienced in 1987, when
international business was generally stronger than in the U.S.
Unisys operations continue to benefit from the fundamental
structural changes made in 1986 and 1987,'' he said.
   Unisys reports its earnings per share on a fully diluted basis _
that is, based on the number of shares that would exist if all
stock options were exercised and all convertible preferred shares
were converted into common stock. Earnings per primary common share
were up to 77 cents from 57 cents a year earlier.
</TEXT>
