<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Stocks-Collar 2ndLd-Writethru   04-14 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stocks-Collar, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plunge In Dow Average Triggers Ban on Computerized Trading Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS closing Dow average to 2,005.64 in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A restriction on computerized stock trading that
went into effect when the Dow Jones industrial average tumbled more
than 50 points Thursday stemmed the slide only briefly and actually
may have worsened it, brokers said.
   The widely followed barometer of 30 blue chip stocks dropped
101.46 to 2,005.64, its largest loss since falling 140.58 on Jan. 8.
   It marked the second time the so-called ``collar'' on
index-arbitrage program trading was triggered since the restriction
was announced in February as part of an effort to restore stability
to a market still suffering after-effects of the October market
disaster.
   It also was the first time the collar was triggered by a
downward move in the Dow average. The collar was triggered for the
first time ever on April 6, when the average rose 64.16 points.
   Under the collar rule, traders are banned from using the New
York Stock Exchange's automated order system to execute
index-arbitrage program trades for the rest of the day when the Dow
average moves up or down 50 points from the previous close.
   The Big Board said the collar went into effect at about 1:55
p.m. Thursday when the average tumbled below the 50-point limit,
battered by massive selling over disappointing news on the U.S.
trade deficit, fears of higher interest rates and a weaker dollar.
   Although computerized program trading was halted, brokers who
utilize the strategy began using an old-fashioned manual method for
selling stocks and the Dow average kept falling.
   ``I guess there's really a lot of selling that's built up,''
said Peter DaPuzzo, manager of retail equities at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. ``You can't ignore the fact that there's heavy selling
and profit-taking going on. Right now the selling is more chaotic
because people want out at the same time.''
   Others said the collar may have worsened the Dow average's drop
because after the 50-point threshhold was reached, only sellers
remained in the market.
   ``Once this thing goes below 50, nobody shows up to do any
buying,'' said Joseph Barthel, a technical strategist at Butcher &
Singer Inc.
   In index arbitrage program trading, brokers use computers to buy
massive amounts of stocks in New York and the equivalent
stock-index futures in Chicago, or vice versa, in order to profit
from price disparities.
   The technique has been mentioned in some studies of the stock
crash as a possible contributor to the volatility and soaring
volumes that pummeled the market and frightened millions of
investors into selling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880414-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1858EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bonds     04-14 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Fall On Trade Deficit Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices finished broadly lower Thursday,
dropping sharply on news of an unexpected widening in the nation's
trade deficit but recovering some lost ground later in the day as
stock prices plunged.
   Long-term yields moved higher, but some short-term interest
rates fell as investors worried by the steep stock market decline
sought the relative safety of Treasury issues.
   The Treasury's 30-year bond ended the day down a full point, or
$10 for every $1,000 in face value. The issue, viewed as a
bellwether for the credit markets, careened 2 points lower shortly
after the trade report was released.
   The 30-year bond's yield rose to 8.86 percent from 8.73 percent
late Wednesday.
   But some short-term rates fell. Yields on three-month Treasury
bills, for instance, slid to 5.72 percent from 5.83 percent late
Wednesday.
   Bond prices skidded immediately after the Commerce Department
reported the nation's trade deficit widened to $13.8 billion in
February, its biggest shortfall since October. Most analysts
expected the gap to narrow.
   A wider deficit suggests that the dollar may have to fall
further to reduce the trade gap. A falling dollar makes
dollar-denominated securities less attractive to foreign investors,
who have been major buyers of Treasury bonds.
   ``The bond market was in a state of shock when the number
printed,'' said Elliott Platt, research director for the investment
firm Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette Securities Inc.
   But later in the day, bond prices retraced some lost ground as
stock prices fell. Platt said as the stock market's decline
deepened, some traders decided to buy bonds where yields were
becoming more attractive compared with stocks.
   The Dow Jones industrial average wound up down 101.46 points.
   Platt said yields on three-month Treasury bills fell because
demand surged for the government-backed instruments, which are
viewed as secure and can be easily converted into cash. The
phenomenon, known as a ``flight to quality,'' often occurs in times
of financial uncertainty.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
issues fell \ point, intermediates slipped by between \ point and {
point and 20-year governments dropped 1] points, according to the
financial information service Telerate Inc.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, fell 0.46 to 111.30. The Shearson Lehman composite
index, which makes a similar measurement, fell 6.21 to 1,162.82.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, slid 2.52 to to 279.88.
   Yields on six-month Treasury bills fell 2 basis points to 6.02
percent, but one-year bills rose 4 basis points to 6.46 percent. A
basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 611-16 percent, up from 6| percent late
Wednesday.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyers Municipal Bond Index
that measures prices on 40 long-term bonds fell 25-32 point to 87
29-32 while its yield rose to 8.17 percent from 8.09 percent.
</TEXT>
