<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TexasAir-Eastern     04-14 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Air-Eastern,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Blames Union Agitation For Government's Texas Air Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Texas Air Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reeling from setbacks in Congress, the courts, and
at the cash register, Eastern Airlines faces new problems with
federal government investigations under way.
   But the airline's president says he welcomes a major federal
investigation into the management of its parent Texas Air Corp. as
a way to highlight his company's performance.
   The Department of Transportation launched an unprecedented
inquiry Wednesday into Texas Air's finances and management, to
determine whether the company is fit to carry commercial air
traffic.
   The Federal Aviation Administration also on Wednesday slapped
Eastern with $823,000 in new fines for safety violations and said
it was beginning an inspection of the carrier's entire fleet.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes said the DOT probe ``certainly
isn't going to help'' Eastern's financial troubles, which include
the loss of $900 million over the past 10 years. Eastern also
reported a nearly 20 percent drop in passenger revenue during March.
   ``The very idea of an investigation into safety is scary to the
flying public, but we welcome it because we hope the whole story of
Eastern Airlines dedication to safety and performance will finally
be told,'' Bakes said.
   Bakes blamed the labor unions at Eastern, which was near
bankruptcy when Texas Air acquired it in 1986, for political
agitation that he said brought on the government's scrutiny of the
company.
   ``We hope this (investigation) means an end to the
behind-the-scenes lobbying and media manipulation by the unions and
the end of the scare tactics,'' Bakes said.
   Charles Bryan, the leader of Eastern's Machinists union, said
Washington was expressing its own concern over the management of
Eastern and would not have acted so decisively simply because of
complaints from labor unions.
   ``What we have right now at Eastern Airlines and the Texas Air
empire is dealmakers and lobbyists running the airline,'' said
Bryan, president of the Machinists District 100, which represents
12,000 of Eastern's 32,000 employees.
   Eastern pilots, flight attendants and mechanics contend Texas
Air management has sacrificed safety and intimidated employees in
order to cut costs at Eastern, where Bakes wants to reduce labor
costs by nearly 30 percent.
   Eastern's unions bitterly have opposed Texas Air Chairman Frank
Lorenzo's plans for trimming costs and restructuring the airline,
including the spinoff of its profitable Northeast corridor shuttle.
   On Wednesday, a new union lawsuit accused Eastern of violating a
labor contract by using company planes to train non-union flight
attendants to serve passengers in the event of a strike.
   The Transport Workers Union of America, Local 553, charged
Eastern planes are being used by Orion Lift Services Inc., an
independent cargo airline, to train non-union flight attendants.
   Eastern also faces troubles from Congress and federal
authorities.
   In recent weeks, more than 150 congressmen have expressed
support for a closer examination of Texas Air management practices
and held hearings over the issue.
   Federal judges last month blocked Eastern from spinning off its
Boston-New York-Washington shuttle into a Texas Air subsidiary and
also from using Eastern planes to train Orion Air personnel.
Eastern had lined up the North Carolina-based cargo carrier to fly
its routes in case of an employee strike.
   The $823,000 civil penalty imposed Wednesday against Eastern
comes 14 months after Eastern agreed to pay $9.5 million in
penalties because of earlier safety infractions. FAA officials said
the latest fine stems from record keeping and maintenance
infractions similar to those found in the earlier action.
</TEXT>
