<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru,0850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate OKs $1.1 Trillion Spending Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to specify that development money is for grants
to local governments; subs pvs grafs 9-10, ``But the ... 1989,'' to
clarify that $1.4 billion is part of total $2.6 billion increase. A
version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Thursday approved a $1.1
trillion budget that calls for bypassing last fall's
deficit-reduction pact with President Reagan to expand the war on
drugs.
   The fiscal 1989 spending blueprint, passed 69-26, also includes
increases for education, the space program and AIDS research while
freezing or cutting back transportation, housing and development
grants to local governments.
   ``We made tough choices,'' said Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla.,
chairman of the Budget Committee. He defended his plan while
conceding that the deficit problem remains unsolved. ``We can't
keep consuming more than we earn and living on credit,'' he said.
   Sen. J. James Exon, D-Neb., called the budget a ``lost
opportunity'' that resulted from ``a decision to coast rather than
deal with the deficit'' in an election year.
   ``The next president and the next Congress will be left with
enormous problems,'' he said.
   The House approved a different version of the spending plan last
month. The two chambers will begin negotiations next week toward a
final budget resolution.
   Conforming with last fall's deficit-reduction agreement with the
president, the Senate plan earmarks $294 billion for military
spending and $16.1 billion for international assistance. It
includes no new taxes beyond the $14 billion enacted last December
for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1.
   The agreement also capped spending by domestic agencies. The
House plan, like Reagan's proposed budget, conformed with those
limits.
   But the Senate voted 93-0 Wednesday night to bypass the spending
caps to provide an additional $2.6 billion for anti-drug efforts
beginning next year. The money would go for treatment programs, law
enforcement and interdiction of smuggled drugs.
   The amendment offered by Sens. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., and
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., called for increasing government tax and
debt collections to cover the $1.4 billion portion of this new
money that would be spent during the 1989 fiscal year.
   Sponsors said they weren't busting the deficit agreement,
because that pact includes a clause allowing exceptions for dire
emergencies.
   The Senate budget claims to reduce the deficit to $136 billion,
as required by the Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing law. Like the
House, the Senate adopted the administration's optimistic economic
scenarios in order to show less red ink.
   The Congressional Budget Office estimates the deficit would be
$35 billion higher. The deficit was $150 billion in fiscal 1987,
and it is expected to dip to $147.5 billion this year.
   Overall, the Senate budget would cut the deficit $7.2 billion
below what would otherwise be expected under current law, according
to budget committee figures. Less than half of those savings would
come from spending cuts, with the bulk relying mostly on sales of
government assets to show a deficit reduction.
   The DeConcini-D'Amato drug amendment and a smaller one, also
shifting more money to drugs, were the only two substantive
amendments adopted by the Senate in four days of debate.
   The Senate on Thursday rejected, 57-38, a proposal by Sen.
Lowell Weicker, R-Conn., to postpone starting construction of the
superconducting super collider research project until after next
year, and using the $50 million saved for health care.
   Senators also defeated, 66-29, an amendment by Sen. Bill
Armstrong, R-Colo., to cut development programs to pay for a
reduction in the capital gains tax.
   Like Reagan's budget, the Senate plan greatly increases space
and science spending. The space program would get a 27 percent
increase and the National Science Foundation 11 percent more than
during the current fiscal year.
   AIDS research would get more than $1.3 billion.
   ``This is one of the most futuristic budgets in the history of
the United States,'' said Sen. Pete V. Domenici of New Mexico, the
senior Republican on the budget committee.
   The Senate plan also boosts aviation safety programs by 19
percent, to allow for hiring of more air traffic controllers and
purchase of new equipment.
   The House approved a more modest boost in the space program,
opting instead to protect housing, development and transportation
programs from cutbacks.
   Neither plan contemplates major changes in agriculture programs.
The Senate version includes $500 million for buying commodities to
continue the distributions to the needy.
   The Senate budget adopts Reagan's proposal to increase military
pay by 4.3 percent but civilian federal salaries by only 2 percent.
The House opted for a 3 percent pay hike for all federal employees.
   The Senate budget action came on the earliest date in years, but
Congress was still missing its April 15 deadline for finishing
budget action.
   The budget is a congressional resolution that does not require
the president's signature. It serves as a guideline for Congress as
it produces its annual spending bills.
</TEXT>
