<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 2211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Tax-Glance     04-14 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax-Glance,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summary of Tax News</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tax Night Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are some taxing developments on the eve of
the income tax filing deadline:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TAX FREEDOM</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The ``average'' American will have to work 126 days this year _
two more than in 1987 _ just to pay federal, state and local taxes,
the Tax Foundation said. ``Tax Freedom Day'' will fall on May 5,
the latest ever.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GOP-TAXES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Some House Republicans used the tax-filing deadline to launch an
offensive to block income-tax increases.
   The congressmen want: no tax rate increases or further cuts in
deductions unless accompanied by rate reductions; a balanced budget
amendment to the Constitution; and a ``taxpayer bill of rights''
that seeks to protect citizens dealing with the IRS.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TAX PENALTIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The IRS offered taxpayers tips on avoiding penalties for
following erroneous advice given by is own information service.
   The IRS said it will consider the specifics of the telephone
assistance call and whether the taxpayer tried to get the correct
answer from tax forms, instructions or official publications.
   The agency indicated the taxpayer's case would be helped if he
or she noted the name of the employee who gave the bad advice and
the date and time of the call.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ROSTENKOWSKI-TAX MAIL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aides to Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, chairman of the tax-writing
House Ways and Means Committee, say he has been flooded with more
than 2,000 letters from angry, befuddled taxpayers lambasting tax
changes.
   ``Simplification of the tax code must have been a joke. There is
nothing that has been simplified,'' said one of the letters.
   The staff said most of the letters are part of a write-in
campaign by Money magazine and contain copies of an article, ``Nine
Tax Laws Congress Should Repeal Tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TAX NIGHT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In many towns, post offices will send clerks to curbside to
collect tax forms for last minute taxpayers.
   Local broadcasters and others have helped turn tax night into an
``event'' with promotions including coffee, doughnut, and aspirin
giveaways. One radio station will offer taxpayers a chance to vent
their feelings by taking a sledgehammer to a used car when they
drop off their returns. A small charge for taking part will be used
for charity.
</TEXT>
