<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   04-14 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domestic Sales Drop in Early April But Upturn Expected Later in
Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestic cars and light trucks fell 10.8
percent in early April from a year ago, a drop that analysts labled
a statistical blip and that some industry participants blamed on
unique holiday and tax factors.
   Automakers reported Wednesday they sold 230,486 domestic-built
cars and light trucks in the eight selling days of April 1-10, down
from 290,826 domestic vehicles in the nine selling days of the same
period a year earlier. Because of the difference in selling days,
percentage changes for the period reflect changes in average daily
sales, not straight totals.
   ``It's just the usual (market) volatility, nothing special.
There's no question sales will pick up,'' said Ronald Glantz,
analyst with Montgomery Securities Inc. in San Francisco.
   Glantz and others said increased difficulty and confusion among
people preparing this year's revised federal income tax forms may
have kept more buyers than usual out of the market in early April
as the April 15 filing date neared.
   Adam Lee, sales manager of Lee Hyundai in Portland, Maine, said:
``The last two weeks have been slow. You see people waiting to
finish their tax returns ...to see how much they can afford.''
   The April 1-10 period also included Good Friday, Passover and
Easter, a time when many people take extra days off work but aren't
likely to wander into dealerships, analysts said.
   Sales were unexpectedly strong during the first quarter of 1988,
leading many analysts to increase their forecasts for the rest of
the year. Early April marked the first real slowdown.
   ``It's the weakest period in a long time. (But) I think it's
just a hiccup,'' said David Healy, industry analyst with Drexel
Burnham Lambert in New York.
   ``The pressure on dealers to move out excess inventory is
lightening up. Inventories were on the low side of normal at the
end of March,'' he said.
   Dealerships had a 58-day supply of domestic cars at the end of
March, according to the weekly trade publication Ward's Automotive
Reports. A 60-day to 65-day supply is considered normal.
   Car sales dropped in early April for all domestic producers
except Honda Motor Co., whose sales jumped 31.7 percent, and Mazda
Motor Corp., which began assembling cars in the United States late
last year.
   Chrysler Corp., the third-largest U.S. automaker, saw its car
sales drop 7.8 percent from last year but saw its U.S. market share
rise to 15.6 percent from 14.3 percent a year earlier.
   Chrysler truck sales jumped 15.3 percent as its market share
rose to 23.9 percent from 20.4 percent a year ago.
   Of the Big Three, General Motors Corp. suffered the largest drop
in domestic car sales, 18.8 percent from a year ago, compared to a
15.9 percent drop for Ford Motor Co.
   GM held 49.2 percent of that market, down from 51.2 percent a
year ago, while Ford's share held steady at 29.7 percent.
   Ford's domestic light truck sales fell 12.7 percent and its
share of the market shrank to 35.1 percent from 39.6 percent. GM's
truck sales rose 0.8 percent and its market share rose to 39.3
percent from 38.4 percent a year ago.
</TEXT>
