<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0280,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Supply Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-4 pvs The Fed...$768.3 billion to CORRECT
previous week's total for aggregates. Picks up 5th grav, M1
includes...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply rose in the week ended April 4, the Federal Reserve Board
reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 rose $4.6 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $2,982.7 billion in the week ended April 4 from
$2,978.1 billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, increased to a seasonally adjusted
$3,751.7 billion from $3,745.4 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, fell $3.2 billion
to a seasonally adjusted $765 billion from a revised $768.2 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures
   For the latest 13 weeks, M1 averaged $761.2 billion, a 4.3
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous
13 weeks.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks rose $1.76 billion in
the week ended April 6, compared with an increase of $456 million a
week earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said discount window borrowings from the
Federal Reserve System averaged $167 million a day in the week
ended Wednesday, down from $426 million the previous week.
</TEXT>
